{"title_page": "Smith College", "text_new": "{{distinguish | William Smith College}}\n{{short description|Private women's liberal arts college in Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox university\n|image_name      = Smith College seal.svg\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         =\n|motto           = \u1f18\u03bd \u03c4\u1fc7 \u1f00\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u1fc7 \u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u03b3\u03bd\u1ff6\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd ([[Greek language|Greek]])\n|mottoeng        = In Virtue [One Gains] Knowledge\n|established     = 1871 (opened 1875)\n|type            = [[Private school|Private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]]<br>[[Women's colleges in the United States|Women's college]]\n|endowment       = $1.91 billion (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|president       = [[Kathleen McCartney (college president)|Kathleen McCartney]]\n|faculty         = 285<ref name=\"justthefacts\">[http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php Just the Facts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050512074309/http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |date=2005-05-12 }}, Smith College website.</ref>\n|students        = 2,903 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019>{{cite web |url= https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2018\u20132019 |publisher=Smith College |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227180325/http://www.smith.edu/ir/docs/Smith_College_CDS_2015-2016_Published_for_Distribution_incomplete.pdf |archivedate=2015-12-27 }}</ref>\n|undergrad       = 2,502 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019/>\n|postgrad        = 401 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019/>\n|city            = [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]\n|state           = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country         = United States\n|coor            = {{Coord|42.318119|-72.638139|region:US_type:edu|display=inline, title}}\n|campus          = [[Town|Small-town]]\n|colors          = Blue with gold trim {{Color box|#002D62|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#F1AB00|border=darkgray}}<ref name=Colors>{{cite web|title=Smith College:Visual Identity Program|url=http://www.smith.edu/vid/using.php|publisher=Smith College|accessdate=20 August 2012|year=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520112207/http://www.smith.edu/vid/using.php|archive-date=20 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|nickname        = Pioneers\n|athletics       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference|NEWMAC]]\n|affiliations    = [[National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities|NAICU]]<ref>[http://www.naicu.edu/member_center/members.asp NAICU \u2013 Member Directory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109231238/http://www.naicu.edu/member_center/members.asp |date=2015-11-09 }}</ref><br>[[Five Colleges (Massachusetts)|Five Colleges]]<br>[[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]]<br>[[Annapolis Group]]<br>[[Oberlin Group]]<br>[[Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|CLAC]]\n|website         = [http://www.smith.edu/ smith.edu]\n|logo = [[File:Smithcollege-logo.png|200px]]\n}}\n'''Smith College''' is a [[Private university|private]] [[Women's colleges in the United States|women's]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Northampton, Massachusetts]]. Although its undergraduate programs are open to women only, its graduate and certificate programs are also open to men. It is the largest member of the [[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]]. Smith is also a member of the [[Five Colleges Consortium]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fivecolleges.edu |title=Five Colleges, Incorporated: Home |publisher=Fivecolleges.edu |accessdate=2016-09-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913145340/https://www.fivecolleges.edu/ |archive-date=2016-09-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> which allows its students to attend classes at four other [[Pioneer Valley]] institutions: [[Mount Holyoke College]], [[Amherst College]], [[Hampshire College]], and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]].<ref>[http://www.fivecolleges.edu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216091104/https://www.fivecolleges.edu/ |date=2019-12-16 }} Five College Consortium website. \"Accessed July 9, 2009\"</ref> ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks it 11th best among National Liberal Arts Colleges.<ref name=USNWR/> Smith is one of the few women's colleges that offers an engineering degree in four years.\n\n==History==\nThe college was chartered in 1871 by a bequest of [[Sophia Smith]] and opened its doors in 1875 with 14 students and 6 faculty.<ref>[https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/smith-history/sophia-smith \"Sophia Smith\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211124848/https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/smith-history/sophia-smith |date=2016-12-11 }}, Smith College website.</ref> When she inherited a fortune from her father at age 65, Smith decided leaving her inheritance to found a women's college was the best way for her to fulfill the moral obligation she expressed in her will:\n\n<blockquote>I hereby make the following provisions for the establishment and maintenance of an Institution for the higher education of young women, with the design to furnish for my own sex means and facilities for education equal to those which are afforded now in our colleges to young men.<ref>[http://www.smith.edu/about_smithtradition.php smith.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226230052/http://www.smith.edu/about_smithtradition.php |date=2009-02-26 }}, Smith College Web site</ref></blockquote>\n\nBy 1915\u201316, the student enrollment was 1,724, and the faculty numbered 163. Today, with some 2,600 undergraduates on campus, and 250 students studying elsewhere,<ref name=\"smith1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |title=Smith College: Just the Facts |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527115157/http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |archive-date=2010-05-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> Smith is the largest privately endowed college for women in the country.<ref>{{cite book|title=Peterson's Four-year Colleges 2008 |publisher=Peterson |year=2007 |page=2226 |isbn=978-0-7689-2400-8}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Naval Reserve Midshipmen's School]] at Smith College in [[Northampton, Massachusetts]], was training grounds for junior officers of the [[WAVES|Women's Reserve of the U.S. Naval Reserve (WAVES)]] and was nicknamed \"USS Northampton\". On August 28, 1942, a total of 120 women reported to the school for training.<ref name=\"smith-waryears\">{{cite web |url=http://lmliberty.us/2011/08/28/naval-history-aug-28/#axzz1YkXn9YQa |title=Naval History \u2013 August 28 |accessdate=September 19, 2011 |publisher=Lake Minnetonka Liberty, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402203740/http://lmliberty.us/2011/08/28/naval-history-aug-28/#axzz1YkXn9YQa |archivedate=April 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:\"Lt.(jg.) Harriet Ida Pickens and Ens. Frances Wills, first Negro Waves to be commissioned. They were members of the fin - NARA - 520670.tif|thumb|right|200px|[[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Harriet Ida Pickens and [[Ensign (rank)|ENS]] Frances Wills, first African-American [[WAVES]] to be commissioned. They were members of the final graduating class at USNR Midshipmen's School (WR) Northampton, Massachusetts on December 21, 1944.]]\n\nSmith has been led by 11 presidents and two acting presidents. ([[Elizabeth Cutter Morrow]] was the first acting president of Smith College and the first female head of the college, but she did not use the title of president.) For the 1975 centennial, the college inaugurated its first woman president, [[Jill Ker Conway]], who came to Smith from [[Australia]] by way of [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and the [[University of Toronto]]. Since President Conway's term, all Smith presidents have been women, with the exception of John M. Connolly's one-year term as acting president in the interim after President Simmons left to lead [[Brown University]].\n* [[Laurenus Clark Seelye]] 1875\u20131910\n* [[Marion LeRoy Burton]] 1910\u20131917\n* [[William Allan Neilson]] 1917\u20131939\n* [[Elizabeth Cutter Morrow]] 1939\u20131940 (acting president)\n* [[Herbert Davis]] 1940\u20131949\n* Benjamin Fletcher Wright 1949\u20131959\n* [[Thomas C. Mendenhall (historian)|Thomas Corwin Mendenhall]] 1959\u20131975\n* [[Jill Ker Conway]] 1975\u20131985\n* [[Mary Maples Dunn]] 1985\u20131995\n* [[Ruth Simmons]] 1995\u20132001\n* John M. Connolly 2001\u20132002 (acting president)\n* [[Carol T. Christ]] 2002\u20132013\n* [[Kathleen McCartney (college president)|Kathleen McCartney]] 2013\u2013present\n\nOn December 10, 2012, the Board of Trustees announced Kathleen McCartney had been selected as the 11th president of Smith College effective July 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newpresident/|title=The 11th President of Smith|accessdate=January 17, 2013|publisher=Smith College, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115002436/http://www.smith.edu/newpresident/|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elm Tree at Smith College, Northampton, MA June 2012.jpg|thumb|right|One of the oldest American Elm trees on the Smith campus.<ref name=\"100years\" />]]The campus was planned and planted in the 1890s as a [[botanical garden]] and [[arboretum]], designed by [[Frederick Law Olmsted]].<ref name=\"100years\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/news/2002/OldTrees.html |title=100 Years And Counting, If These Trees Could Talk |website=Smith College website (News & Events) |date=2002-03-01 |accessdate=2014-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226020058/http://www.smith.edu/news/2002/OldTrees.html |archive-date=2014-12-26 |url-status=live }}</ref> The campus landscape now encompasses {{convert|147|acre}} and includes more than 1,200 varieties of trees and shrubs.\n[[File:Camperdown Elm at Smith College campus, Northampton, MA - January 2015.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Camperdown Elm tree near arboretum.]]\n\nIn April 2015, the faculty adopted an [[open-access policy]] to make its scholarship [[open access|publicly accessible]] online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roarmap.eprints.org/832/ |title=Smith College |work=[[ROARMAP]]: Registry of Open Access Repository Mandates and Policies |publisher=[[University of Southampton]] |location=UK |accessdate=2018-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713063743/http://roarmap.eprints.org/832/ |archive-date=2017-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nSmith College has 285 professors in 41 academic departments and programs, for a faculty:student ratio of 1:9.<ref name=\"smith1\"/> It was the first women's college in the United States to grant its own undergraduate degrees in [[engineering]]. The Picker Engineering Program offers a single [[ABET]] accredited [[Bachelor of Science]] in engineering science, combining the fundamentals of multiple engineering disciplines.\n\nSmith has joined the [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States#SAT optional movement|SAT optional movement]] for undergraduate admission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/metrowest/republican/index.ssf?/base/news-14/1211786427249410.xml&coll=1|title=Smith drops SATs|last=Contrada|first=Fred|date=May 26, 2008|publisher=MassLive.com|accessdate=October 10, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625004817/http://www.masslive.com/metrowest/republican/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-14%2F1211786427249410.xml&coll=1|archivedate=June 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSmith runs its own junior year abroad (JYA) programs in four European cities: [[Paris]], [[Hamburg]], [[Florence]] and [[Geneva]].<ref>[http://www.smith.edu/studyabroad/jya.php Smith College: Study Abroad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719145941/http://www.smith.edu/studyabroad/jya.php# |date=2012-07-19 }}. Smith.edu. Retrieved on 2013-09-07.</ref> These programs are notable for requiring all studies to be conducted in the language of the host country (with both Paris and Geneva programs conducted in French). In some cases students live in homestays with local families. Nearly half of Smith's juniors study overseas, either through Smith JYA programs or at more than 40 other locations around the world.\n\nJunior math majors from other undergraduate institutions are invited to study at Smith College for one year through the [[Center for Women in Mathematics]]. Established in the fall of 2007 by Professors [[Ruth Haas]] and Jim Henle, the program aims to allow young women to improve their mathematical abilities through classwork, research and involvement in a department centered on women. The [[Center for Women in Mathematics|Center]] also offers a post-baccalaureate year of math study to women who either did not major in mathematics as undergraduates or whose mathematics major was not strong.<ref>[http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/NAM/newsletter/NAM38.1.pdf \"Smith College Women in Mathematics Program\" National Association of Mathematicians, Spring 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910095330/http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/NAM/newsletter/NAM38.1.pdf |date=2008-09-10 }}. Retrieved 3 September 2008.</ref>\n\nThe Louise W. and Edmund J. Kahn Liberal Arts Institute supports collaborative research without regard to the traditional boundaries of academic departments and programs. Each year the Institute supports long-term and short-term projects proposed, planned and organized by members of the Smith College faculty. By becoming Kahn Fellows, students get involved in interdisciplinary research projects and work alongside faculty and visiting scholars for a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/kahninstitute/ |title=Smith College: Kahn Liberal Arts Institute |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701234250/http://www.smith.edu/kahninstitute/ |archive-date=2010-07-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStudents can develop leadership skills through Smith's two-year Phoebe Reese Lewis Leadership Program. Participants train in public speaking, analytical thinking, teamwork strategies and the philosophical aspects of leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialleadership.php |title=Smith College: Academic Programs |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527184341/http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialleadership.php |archivedate=2010-05-27 }}</ref>\n\nThrough Smith's internship program, \"Praxis: The Liberal Arts at Work,\" every undergraduate is guaranteed access to one college funded internship during her years at the college. This program enables students to access interesting self-generated internship positions in social welfare and human services, the arts, media, health, education, and other fields.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialpraxis.php |title=Smith College: Academic Programs |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010171913/http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialpraxis.php |archivedate=2010-10-10 }}</ref>\n\n===Admissions===\nThe 2019 annual ranking of ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' categorizes Smith as 'most selective'.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209 |title=U.S. News Best Colleges Rankings: Smith College |year=2019 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=July 2, 2019 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702140454/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209 |archive-date=July 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFor the Class of 2022 (enrolling fall 2018), Smith received 5,780 applications, accepted 1,789 (31.0%) and enrolled 613.<ref name=CDS>{{cite web |url=https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2018\u20132019, Part C |publisher=Smith College |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105231541/https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-05 |url-status=live }}</ref> The middle 50% range of [[SAT scores]] was 670\u2013750 for critical reading and 670\u2013770 for math, while the middle 50% range for the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] composite score was 31\u201334 for enrolled first year students.<ref name=CDS/>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes   = 81\n| USNWR_LA = 11\n| Wamo_LA  = 28\n| THE_WSJ  = 41\n}}\n\n[[File:SmithCollege Seelye Hall.jpg|thumb|right|Seelye Hall]]\n\n''U.S. News & World Report'''s 2020 rankings placed Smith tied for the 11th best liberal arts college in the nation.<ref name=USNWR>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209/overall-rankings |title=Smith College Rankings |year=2020 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=November 5, 2019 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124141821/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209/overall-rankings |archive-date=November 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same publication's rankings of liberal arts colleges, Smith is rated 5th for \"Best Value\" and tied for 11th in \"Most Innovative Schools\".<ref name=USNWR/> In 2019, ''[[Forbes]]'' rated Smith 81st overall in its America's Top Colleges ranking of 650 military academies, national universities, and liberal arts colleges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/top-colleges/list/ |magazine=Forbes |title=America's Top Colleges |date=August 15, 2019 |access-date=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810053444/http://www.forbes.com/top-colleges/list/ |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Kiplinger's Personal Finance]]'' places Smith 16th in its 2019 ranking of 149 best value liberal arts colleges in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-best-college-values-college-finder/index.php#Table | magazine=Kiplinger's Personal Finance | title=Kiplinger's Best College Values | date=July 2019 | access-date=2019-08-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823230821/https://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-best-college-values-college-finder/index.php#Table | archive-date=2019-08-23 | url-status=live }}</ref>  For 2019, ''[[Washington Monthly]]'' ranked Smith 28th among 214 liberal arts colleges in the U.S. based on its contribution to the public good, as measured by social mobility, research, and promoting public service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://washingtonmonthly.com/2019college-guide/liberalarts |title=2019 Liberal Arts College Rankings |magazine=Washington Monthly |access-date=November 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927151745/https://washingtonmonthly.com/2019college-guide/liberalarts |archive-date=September 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Ada Comstock Scholars Program===\nThe '''Ada Comstock Scholars Program''' is an undergraduate degree program that serves Smith students of [[Non-traditional student|nontraditional college age]]. The program accommodates approximately 100 women ranging in age from mid-twenties to over sixty. Ada Comstock Scholars attend the same classes as traditional undergraduates, either full or part-time, and participate fully in a variety of extracurricular activities. They may live on or off campus. Financial aid is available to each Ada Comstock Scholar with demonstrated need.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/admission/ada.php|title=Smith College: For Nontraditional Students|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419185939/http://www.smith.edu/admission/ada.php/|archive-date=2015-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1968, with the approval of the Committee on Educational Policy, Smith College initiated a trial program loosely titled ''The Continuing Education Degree'' for several women of non-traditional age who were looking to complete their unfinished degrees. Their successes inspired President [[Thomas C. Mendenhall (historian)|Thomas C. Mendenhall]] and Dean Alice Dickinson to officially expand the program. In January 1975, the '''Ada Comstock Scholars Program''' was formally established under President [[Jill Ker Conway]] and in the fall of that year forty-five women were enrolled. The students range in ages, backgrounds, and geographical locations. The growth of the program peaked just over 400 students in 1988.\n\nThe program is named for [[Ada Comstock|Ada Louise Comstock Notestein]] (1876\u20131973), an 1897 Smith graduate, professor of English and dean of Smith from 1912\u201323, and president of [[Radcliffe College]] from 1923\u201343. Ada Comstock Notestein devoted much of her life to the academic excellence of women. Considering education and personal growth to be a lifelong process, she stayed actively involved in women's higher education until her death at the age of 97.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/classdeans/adas_history.php|title=Smith College: Class Deans|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419014932/http://www.smith.edu/classdeans/adas_history.php|archive-date=2015-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate degrees and study options===\nSmith offers men and women graduate work leading to the degrees of master of arts in teaching (elementary, middle or high school), master of fine arts, master of education of the deaf, master of science in biological sciences, master of science in exercise and sport studies and master and Ph.D. in social work. In special one-year programs, international students may qualify for a certificate of graduate studies or a diploma in American studies. Each year approximately 100 men and women pursue advanced graduate work at Smith.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/degrees.php |title=Smith College: Graduate Study |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615153802/http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/degrees.php |archive-date=2010-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso offered in a non-degree studies program is the Diploma in American Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/nondegree.php |title=Smith College: Graduate Study |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615144512/http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/nondegree.php |archive-date=2010-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> This is a highly competitive one-year program open only to international students of advanced undergraduate or graduate standing. It is designed primarily, although not exclusively, for those who are teaching or who plan to teach some aspect of American culture and institutions.\n\nThe [[Smith College School for Social Work]] is nationally recognized for its specialization in clinical social work and puts a heavy emphasis on direct field work practice. The program is accredited by the [[Council on Social Work Education]]. The school offers a Master of Social Work (M.S.W.) degree as well as a Ph.D. program designed to prepare MSWs for leadership positions in clinical research education and practice.\n\nThe college has a limited number of other programs leading to Ph.D.s, and is part of a cooperative doctoral program co-administered by [[Amherst College]], [[Hampshire College]], [[Mount Holyoke College]] and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]].\n\n==Traditions==\n\n===Residential culture and student life===\nSmith requires most undergraduate students to live in on-campus houses unless they reside locally with their family. This policy is intended to add to the camaraderie and social cohesion of its students. Unlike most institutions of its type, Smith College does not have dorms, but rather 36 separate houses, ranging in architectural style from 18th-century to contemporary. It is rumored the architecture of Chapin House was the inspiration for the Tara Plantation House in ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]''. (Author [[Margaret Mitchell]] went to Smith for one year and lived in Chapin.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2017-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104143010/https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> A novelty of Smith's homelike atmosphere is the continuing popularity of Sophia Smith's recipe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clio.fivecolleges.edu/smith/sophia/fun/fun.htm |title=Sophia Through the Years |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309173039/http://clio.fivecolleges.edu/smith/sophia/fun/fun.htm |archive-date=2018-03-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> for molasses cookies. These are often served at the traditional Friday afternoon tea held in each house, where students, faculty and staff members and alumnae socialize.<ref name=\"justthefacts\" />\n\nTwo cultural spaces on campus, used by students of color to build their community, include the Mwangi Cultural Center and Unity House. Mwangi originally opened as the Afro-American Cultural Center in 1968, but was later renamed in honor of the first female physician in Kenya, and Smith alum, Dr. Ng\u2019endo Mwangi 61\u2019. After loaning Mwangi to the other cultural organizations on campus for four years, the Black Students\u2019 Alliance decided to reclaim Mwangi in April 1990. [https://sophia.smith.edu/weaving-voices-archives/1990/04/26/black-students-alliance-bsa-unanimously-votes-to-reclaim-mwangi-center/ Reclaiming Cultural Center Smith College] Leaders, members and supporters of cultural organizations got together to form a group called UNITY, in October of the same year, to demand a space for other cultural organizations. [https://sophia.smith.edu/weaving-voices-archives/1990/10/26/unity-orgs-hold-rally-college-hall-sit-in-to-protest-for-space/ Weaving Voices Archive UNITY] Today, Unity House serves as a home to the 11 cultural organizations on campus. [https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/multicultural-affairs/cultural-spaces Cultural Spaces Smith College]\n\nTwo recent additions to the campus, both of which enhance its sense of community, are the architecturally dramatic Campus Center <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/campuscenter/ |title=Smith College: Office of Student Engagement |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724043800/http://www.smith.edu/campuscenter/ |archive-date=2010-07-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the state-of-the-art Olin Fitness Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/news/2003-04/OlinOpening.html |title=Smith College: News |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720045318/http://www.smith.edu/news/2003-04/OlinOpening.html |archive-date=2011-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, construction was also completed on Ford Hall, a new science and engineering facility. According to the Smith College website, Ford Hall is a \"...facility that will intentionally blur the boundaries between traditional disciplines, creating an optimum environment for students and faculty to address key scientific and technological developments of our time.\" The building was officially dedicated on October 16, 2009.<ref>Ford Hall: http://www.smith.edu/fordhall/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305171516/http://www.smith.edu/fordhall/ |date=2010-03-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe campus also boasts a botanic garden that includes a variety of specialty gardens including a rock garden and historic glass greenhouses dating back to 1895. The botanic garden formerly featured a Japanese tea hut, which was removed in October 2015 following concerns over \"issues of safety and vandalism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/news/announcement.php?id=26939|title=Smith College: Grecourt Gate Announcement|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2016-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012153347/https://www.smith.edu/news/announcement.php?id=26939|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSmith offers \"panel discussions and seminars for lesbian, bisexual, and transgender students on subjects such as coming out as transgender at work.\"<ref>April 8, 2007 article, Boston Globe, http://www.boston.com/news/globe/magazine/articles/2007/04/08/when_she_graduates_as_he/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127062345/http://www.boston.com/news/globe/magazine/articles/2007/04/08/when_she_graduates_as_he/ |date=2009-01-27 }}</ref> In 2003, Smith students voted to remove pronouns from the language of the Student Government Association constitution, in order to make that document inclusive of transgender students who don't identify with the pronouns \"she\" and \"her.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/oid/gender_faq.php |title=Smith College: Office of Institutional Diversity |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128180340/http://www.smith.edu/oid/gender_faq.php |archivedate=2011-01-28 }}</ref>\n\nUntil 2013, transgender women were not allowed to attend Smith unless all their legal documentation consistently stated they were female. This policy came to public attention in March 2013 when Smith rejected the application of a [[trans woman]] named Calliope Wong. In the rejection letter, Smith's Dean of Admission Debra Shaver wrote \"Your [[FAFSA]] indicates your gender as male. Therefore, Smith cannot process your application.\" This policy was changed in 2013 to only require all non legal application materials to indicate a female identity, including references. Not satisfied with the change, students as well as various alumni formed the group Q&A (\"Queers and Allies\") to advocate for more trans-inclusive policies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Drew|first=Sophie|date=|title=Challenging Gender at a Women\u2019s Institution: Transgender Admission and Inclusion at Smith College|url=|journal=Women Leading Change \u00a9 Newcomb College Institute|volume=3|pages=25-36|via=}}</ref> Q&A subsequently protested the policy on [[Facebook]] and other [[social media]] websites, as well as staging protests on campus that garnered significant media attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/students-at-smith-protest-the-colleges-refusal-to-admit-tran|title=Students At Smith Protest The College's Refusal To Admit Transgender Women|last=Yandoli|first=Krystie Lee|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2014, Smith formed an Admissions Policy Study Group, co-chaired by Daphne Lamothe and Audrey Smith, who at the time were associate professor of Afro-American studies and vice president for enrollment, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/president-kathleen-mccartney/letters/2014-15/admission-policy|title=President - Letters - Admission Policy Study Group|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The group recommended that to be considered for admission to Smith, applicants live and/or identify as a woman, check the \"female\" box when applying, and that the President establish a working group to support all [[Transgender|trans]] and [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]] students at Smith.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/about.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> These recommendations went to the faculty<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/about.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and the Board of Trustees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/05/04/living/smith-college-transgender-women-feat/index.html|title=Smith College to admit transgender women|first=Brandon |last=Griggs|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and in 2015, Smith announced a [[Transgender admissions policies at women's colleges|new policy]] that only required female identification on the common application.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jaschik |first1=Scott |title=Tipping Point for Trans Admissions? |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/04/smith-college-will-accept-transgender-applicants-who-identify-women |website=Inside Higher Ed |accessdate=5 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706213758/https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/04/smith-college-will-accept-transgender-applicants-who-identify-women |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the policy, [[transgender men]] and non-binary or [[genderqueer]] applicants are not eligible for admission.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/faq.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group FAQ|last=|first=|date=|website=www.smith.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> This new policy also affirms that any student who, once admitted, transitions to another identity other than \"female\" and, who completes the college\u2019s graduation requirements, will be awarded a Smith degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/gender-identity-expression|title=Offices - Diversity - Gender Identity & Expression|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129052732/https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/gender-identity-expression|archive-date=2019-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref> The Resource Center for Sexuality and Gender; The Office for Equity and Inclusion and its Trans/Non-binary Working Group; Transcending Gender, a student group focused on support and education; and the Transgender Support Group run by Counseling Services work to support trans and non-binary students at Smith across the [[gender identity]] spectrum.  \n\nIn the fall of 2018, students at Smith protested after a Smith employee called the police on a black student working at Smith over the summer, when the employee saw her in a common space. Organized by the Black Students\u2019 Alliance and the Smith African & Caribbean Students Association, students protested and walked out of the annual Smith [[convocation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/05/protests-mark-start-new-semester-smith-college/RCtAtCTdwGV28AhdWxygcM/story.html|title=Protests mark start of new semester at Smith College - The Boston Globe|last=Fern|first=Deirdre|last2=|first2=|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|date=September 5, 2018}}</ref> While the incident received national attention and news coverage, Smith conducted an independent investigation and investigators found that there was no [[bias]] in the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/10/30/investigation-finds-no-policy-violations-when-police-were-called-black-student|title=Investigation finds no policy violations when police were called on a black student|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In response to the incident, Smith hosted an Inclusion and Diversity Conference on April 10th, 2019, featuring workshops and presenters run by various members of the Smith community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/president-kathleen-mccartney/letters/2018-19/inclusion-diversity-conference|title=President - Letters - Inclusion and Diversity Conference on April 10|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, during that time another controversy arose: the hiring of [[Mount Holyoke College]] and Smith's joint police chief, Daniel Hect. Students from both campuses brought to their administrators' attention the fact that Hect had \"liked\" far-right tweets on [[Twitter]], such as [[Donald Trump]] tweeting \"Build that Wall!\" and a tweet from the [[National Rifle Association]], before deleting his account once the conflict with students began.Tensions came to a head at the conference, when students protested a presentation from the campus police, including Hect, about policing in a diverse community. Protests continued the next day when hundreds of students participated in a [[sit-in]] organized by the group Students for Social Justice and Institutional Change, or SSJIC, outside of John M. Greene Hall. The group was originally formed to advocate for undocumented students, but expanded to a broad coalition of marginalized students, including [[students of color]], [[Low income|low-income]] and trans students. The coalition presented a broad list of demands to the administration, proposing reform to many sectors of campus life, including curriculum, health and counseling services, accessibility, policing, admissions policies and affinity housing.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazettenet.com/Smith-College-students-protest-against-racism-new-police-chief-24764370|title=As students protest, Smith and Mount Holyoke colleges put new joint chief of police on leave|last=Christensen|first=Dusty|date=2019-04-11|website=Daily Hampshire Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In response to the demands, Smith launched a working group charged with identifying key themes in response to the day of inclusion and ensuing protests<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/inclusion-in-action/working-group-report|title=Offices - Diversity - Inclusion Conference - Working Group Report|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and revamped the Office of Equity and Inclusion, adding programmatic changes, new or modified positions, training and development opportunities and new events to promote inclusion and equity.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/toward-equity-and-inclusion|title=About Smith - Toward Equity and Inclusion|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n====Houses====\n{{See also|Smith College Housing}}\n[[File:Ginkgo tree on Smith College campus, Northampton, MA - January 2015.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Ginkgo tree near arboretum]]\nSmith College has many different houses serving as dormitories. Each house is self-governing. While many students remain in the same house for the entirety of their four years at Smith, they are not obligated to do so, and may move to different houses on campus as space allows. While houses previously collected dues, in the 2019-2020 school year they were eradicated to avoid placing financial pressure on low-income students or students who were otherwise unable to pay without sacrificing funding for the House.\n\nHouses are found in four main regions of campus: Upper and Lower Elm Street, Green Street, Center Campus, and the Quadrangle. Each region can, in turn, be divided into smaller areas to more precisely provide the location of the house in question. In 2019, the college shifted from officially recognizing the four main areas of campus to instead categorizing houses in four neighborhoods: Ivy, Paradise, Mountain, and Garden. This change was largely internal, and categorizes houses by size rather than location.\n\n=====Green Street Houses=====\n* Hubbard House \u2013 Hubbard House is the residence of fictional President [[Selina Meyer]] from the HBO Show [[Veep]]. [[Julia Child]] resided in this house during her time at Smith.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Julia Child Rules: Lessons On Savoring Life|last=Karbo|first=Karen|publisher=Globe Pequot Press: Morris Publishing Group|year=2013|isbn=9780762783090|location=Guilford, Connecticut|pages=[https://archive.org/details/juliachildrulesl0000karb/page/47 47\u201348]|url=https://archive.org/details/juliachildrulesl0000karb/page/47}}</ref>\n* Lawrence House\n* Morris House \u2013 Morris was built in 1891, with its sister house Lawrence to help accommodate the growing student body. It is named after Kate Morris Cone, Smith College class of 1879.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kimball Union Archives ~ Kate Eugenia Morris (Cone), Class of 1875|url=http://kimballunionarchives.com/2012/02/08/kate-eugenia-morris-cone-class-of-1875/|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222064615/http://kimballunionarchives.com/2012/02/08/kate-eugenia-morris-cone-class-of-1875/|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Smith College Residence Life \u2013 Morris House|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_morris.php|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222224804/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_morris.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Tyler House\n* Washburn House - As of 2017, Washburn is closed due to the construction of the new Neilson Library.\n* 44 Green Street\n* 54 Green Street\n* Chapin House \u2013 Author [[Margaret Mitchell]] lived here. Chapin's staircase served as the inspiration for the staircase of Scarlett O'Hara's Tara in ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone With the Wind]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2018-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104143010/https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====Center Campus Houses=====\n* Cutter House\n* Haven/Wesley Houses\n* Hopkins House\n* Park Complex\n**Park Annex - one of two new Affinity houses at Smith College, houses that cater to minority identities on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/student-life/residence-life/houses/park-annex|title=Student Life - Res Life - Smith Houses - Center Campus - Park Annex|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n* Sessions Complex\n* Tenney House\n* Ziskind House\n\n=====Upper Elm Street Houses=====\n[[File:The Botanic Garden of Smith College.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|The Botanic Gardens at Smith College]]\n* Capen House \u2013 Built in 1825 by Samuel Howe, the founder of [[Northampton Law School]], it became part of the Capen School in 1883 and was willed to the college by the school's founder in 1921. It is designed in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Classical Revival]] style.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lincoln |first=Eleanor T. |title=This, The House We Live In |date=1983 |location=Northampton, MA |isbn=0-87391-030-3 |pages=112\u2013115}}</ref> It is named after the founder of the Capen School, Bessie Talbot Capen. \n* Gillett House \u2013 Connected to Northrop house via a breezeway, Gillett houses the only vegan/vegetarian dining hall on campus.\n* Lamont House \u2013 Built in 1955, Lamont House was the first house constructed after the construction of the Quad houses in 1936. Named for alumna Florence Corliss Lamont, who earned her A.B. in 1893 and later an M.A. from Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_lamont.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222224752/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_lamont.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> She married Harvard graduate and future Smith Trustee Thomas Lamont and had four children. Through her life she would continue to give generously to her alma mater. Lamont House is just across Elm Street, tucked behind Northrop and Gillett Houses. Lamont houses 83 students.<ref>[http://sophia.smith.edu/blog/smithipedia/houses/lamont-house/ Lamont House \u00ab Smithipedia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204214913/http://sophia.smith.edu/blog/smithipedia/houses/lamont-house/ |date=2013-12-04 }}. Sophia.smith.edu (2010-06-22). Retrieved on 2014-04-12.</ref>\n* Northrop House\n* Parsons Complex\n**Parsons Annex - one of two new Affinity houses at Smith College, houses that cater to minority identities on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/student-life/residence-life/houses/parsons-annex|title=Student Life - Res Life - Smith Houses - Green Street - Parsons Annex|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n* Talbot House \u2013 Built in 1909 as part of the Capen School, it was willed to the college in 1921. Its mascot is the moose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_talbot.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222225006/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_talbot.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> US First Lady Nancy Reagan '43 lived here during her time at Smith.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} It is also named for Bessie Talbot Capen.\n\n=====Lower Elm Street Houses=====\n* Albright House\n* Baldwin House \u2013 U.S. Senator [[Tammy Baldwin]] ('84) was a Baldwin House resident during her time at Smith College.\n* Chase House\n* Conway House\n* Duckett House\n* 150 Elm Street\n\n=====East Quadrangle Houses=====\n* Cushing House\n* Emerson House\n* Jordan House, built in 1922 and named for the longtime head of the Smith English Department, [[List of feminist rhetoricians#Mary Augusta Jordan|Mary Augusta Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Colton |title=Mary Augusta Jordan |url=http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/alumni/mary-augusta-jordan.html |work=Vassar Encyclopedia |accessdate=7 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222004549/http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/alumni/mary-augusta-jordan.html |archive-date=22 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* King House, named for Franklin King, who served as the superintendent of building and grounds at Smith for 50 years <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_king.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924120933/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_king.php|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Scales House, King's \"sister house,\" was named after Laura Woolsey Lord Scales, who graduated from Smith in 1901 and was the school's first dean of students <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_scales.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924120943/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_scales.php|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====West Quadrangle Houses=====\n* Comstock House\n* Gardiner House\n* Morrow House\n* Wilder House\n* Wilson House\n* Friedman Apartments\n\n====Campus folklore====\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\nSmith has numerous folk tales and ghost stories emerge from the histories of some of its historic buildings. One such tale holds Sessions House is inhabited by the ghost of Lucy Hunt, who died of a broken heart after being separated from her lover, General Burgoyne. Reports of a ghost in Sessions House predate its history as a campus house. Built in 1751 by the Hunt family, the house has a secret staircase where, according to legend, the Hunt's eldest daughter Lucy would rendezvous with her lover, [[John Burgoyne|General Burgoyne]]. The two were ultimately driven apart, and in the 1880s it was believed the ghost of a heartbroken Burgoyne haunted the staircase. Since Sessions House became part of college housing in the 20th century, the specter has taken on a decidedly feminine identity, and some former residents of Sessions claim to have seen Lucy's ghost in the stairwell.\n\n====Clubs, sports, and organizations====\nIn addition to the 11 varsity sports, there are currently more than 200 clubs and organizations that cater to Smith students\u2019 variety of interests. There are options that can be found based on academic, political, cultural, and athletic interests. If a student doesn't find an organization that fits their specific interest or need, they can create their own.\n\n=====Athletics=====\nSmith's athletic teams have been known as the Pioneers since 1986. The name expresses the spirit of Smith's students and the college's leadership role in women's athletics (the first women's basketball game was played at Smith in 1893).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/video/smith-first-new-game-basketball|title=A Smith First: The New Game of Basketball|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807101716/https://www.smith.edu/video/smith-first-new-game-basketball|archive-date=2019-08-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/smith-college-basketball-team-1904/|title=Flashback Photo: Smith College Basketball Team, 1904|date=2014-03-24|website=New England Historical Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708054411/http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/smith-college-basketball-team-1904/|archive-date=2019-07-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA new spirit mark was unveiled to the Smith community in December 2008. The new visual identity for Smith's sports teams marks the culmination of a yearlong project to promote visibility and enthusiasm for Smith's intercollegiate and club teams\u2014and to generate school spirit broadly. The spirit mark is used for athletics uniforms, casual apparel and promotional items for clubs and organizations. As Smith was the first women's college to join the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]], the new mark is seen as linking the college's pioneering alumnae athletes to their equally determined and competitive counterparts today.\n\nSmith College does not have college colors in the usual sense. Its official color is white, trimmed with gold, but the official college logo is blue and yellow (a previous logo was burgundy and white). NCAA athletic teams have competed in blue and white (or blue and yellow, in the case of the soccer, crew, swimming, and squash teams) uniforms since the 1970s, and selected Pioneers as the official name and mascot in 1986. Popular club sports are free to choose their own colors and mascot; both Rugby and Fencing have chosen red and black.\n\nSmith has a rotating system of class colors dating back to the 1880s, when intramural athletics and other campus competitions were usually held by class. Today, class colors are yellow, red, blue and green, with incoming first-year classes assigned the color of the previous year's graduating class; their color then \"follows\" them through to graduation. Alumnae classes, particularly at reunion, continue to identify with and use their class color thereafter.\n\n=====Cultural organizations=====\nThere are 11 chartered cultural organizations that fall under the UNITY title: the Asian Students\u2019 Association (ASA), Black Students\u2019 Alliance (BSA), Chinese Interregional Student Cultural Org (CISCO), South Asian Student Association of Smith (EKTA), Indigenous Smith Students and Allies (ISSA), International Students\u2019 Organization (ISO), Korean Students\u2019 Association (KSA), the Latin American Students\u2019 Organization (LASO), Multiethnic Interracial Smith College (MISC), Smith African and Caribbean Students\u2019 Association (SACSA), and the Vietnamese Students\u2019 Association (VSA). Smith College Website Multicultural Affairs The Black Students\u2019 Alliance is the oldest of all Unity organizations. In Fall 2012, as an effort to document the history of students of color on Smith campus, the Weaving Voices Archives Project was created.\n\n===Academic year events===\n'''[[Convocation]]''' signals the start of the fall semester. For new students it is the first chance to experience Smith College's tradition and spirit. Likewise, for some returning students, the annual event is like a big, welcome-home party as well as an occasion for celebration and an opportunity for creative attire. House communities develop imaginative themes for group fashion, and Smith seniors put special touches on favorite hats to create their own unique \"senior hats,\" to be worn for the first time at Convocation.\n\n'''[[Mountain Day]]''' is observed early in the fall semester. The President of the College selects a crisp, sunny, beautiful autumn day when the leaves are in full color, and announces the cancellation of classes by having bells rung on campus at 7:15 AM on the chosen day. The eager anticipation of Mountain Day leads to intense speculation meteorology by students in the weeks leading up to the surprise announcement. Traditional observance of Mountain Day by students might involve [[New England]] road trips or outdoor pursuits, and college dining services provides box lunches to be taken off-campus. Many of the Houses go apple picking together.\n\n'''[[Otelia Cromwell]] Day''', named for Smith's first African-American student, began in 1989 to provide students with an in-depth program specifically addressing issues of racism and diversity. Afternoon classes are cancelled, and students are invited to participate in lectures, workshops, symposia and cultural events focused on a different theme each year.\n\n'''Rally Day''' In February 1876, the College began an annual observance of [[George Washington]]'s birthday. In 1894, a rally became part of the day's events, and the focus of the celebration became primarily patriotic rather than exclusively social\u2014though always with a women's college twist. Students that year staged a mock debate on the subject, \"Does Higher Education Unfit a Man for Domestic Life?\" In 1906 the celebration was first referred to as '''Rally Day''' (although the name was not used officially by the College until 1992). In 1944, seniors made Rally Day the first public wearing of their graduation caps and gowns; since then, mortarboards have been replaced by wacky, often homemade hats. Today, the Rally Day Convocation is centered on a historical theme, and features a distinguished keynote speaker and the awarding of Smith College Medals to accomplished alumnae.\n\n===Reunions and Commencement events===\nThe Alumnae Association of Smith College hosts official class reunions every five years. All alumnae from all classes are welcome to return in any year; \"off-year\" alumnae attend campus-wide events as the \"Class of 1776.\"\n\nTraditional reunion and [[Graduation|Commencement]] events are linked, and celebrate the close ties between Smith's alumnae and its graduating seniors and their families. At the conclusion of final exams, most underclasswomen leave the campus, while seniors remain in their houses for a week to celebrate and prepare for Commencement. Alumnae arrive for reunions later in the week, and many alumnae arrange for official accommodations in the campus houses, right alongside senior residents.\n\n[[File:Smith College - Ivy Day Seniors.jpg|thumb|220px|Ivy Day]]\n\n'''[[Ivy stone|Ivy Day]]''', the day before Commencement, is the high point of reunion and a significant event for seniors as well. Junior ushers lead a parade through campus, carrying vines of ivy to be planted by the departing seniors as a symbol of their lifelong connection to the college. Alumnae (and, often, their children), dressed in white and wearing sashes in their class color, line up in reverse order by class along both sides of the route. Seniors line up nearest the end of the parade route, wearing traditional white outfits and each carrying a single red rose. All cheer each alumnae class as it marches past, then fall in to join the end of the parade. Many alumnae classes carry signs with humorous poems or slogans, or hold balloons or wear hats in their class color. Ivy Day festivities conclude in the Quad, where the seniors plant their ivy and speakers address alumnae on the progress of fundraising and the state of the college.\n\n'''Illumination Night''', beginning at dusk on the Saturday evening before Commencement, is a celebration of the campus and a send-off of sorts for graduating seniors. Throughout central campus, electric street lights are replaced for one night by multicolored Japanese-style paper lanterns, lit with real candles. These hang on both sides of every walking path and cast a soft glow over the buildings and lawns. Student a cappella singing groups and improv comedy troupes roam the campus, stopping occasionally to entertain the crowds. A jazz band, hired by the college, turns the science buildings' courtyard into a dance floor. Seniors, alumnae, faculty and their families spend the evening on walking tours of the illuminated campus and [[The Botanic Garden of Smith College|Botanic Gardens]]. The major official event of the night is the '''Senior Step Sing''': seniors gather on the steps of Neilson Library, where they are serenaded by members of the '''Sophomore Push''' committee, then are physically pushed off the stairs and \"into the real world.\"\n\nUntil the early 1990s, all alumnae reunions were held during Commencement weekend. However, as the number of returning alumnae grew beyond the capacity of the campus, reunions were split into Reunion I/Commencement Weekend and Reunion II, held the following weekend. \"Significant\" reunions (50-, 25- and 10- year, but also 2-year) and the earliest reunion classes (65-year and prior) are assigned to Reunion I; other reunions (5-, 15-, 20-, 30-year, and so on) are assigned to Reunion II.\n\nThere have been several controversies surrounding commencement over the years. See [[Smith College commencement controversies]] to learn more.\n\n==Environmental sustainability==\n[[File:Paradise Pond.jpg|thumb|Paradise Pond with portion of athletic fields visible (center left)]]\n\nSmith has taken numerous steps toward environmental sustainability, including a 30% reduction in energy use. Also, through a contract with Zipcar, the college has reduced the need for individually owned cars on campus. Complementing this effort, the college has also promoted sustainability through academics and through the arts.<ref name=\"smith.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/green/news.php |title=Smith College: Green Smith |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930235407/http://www.smith.edu/green/news.php |archive-date=2010-09-30 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn keeping with its sustainability efforts, all Smith dining locations have discontinued the use of \"to-go\" supplies which included paper cups and plates, as well as plastic utensils. They now encourage students to bring their own, reusable containers and utensils if they wish to bring food back to their rooms. Smith College provides all students with a reusable drink container at the beginning of each academic year. In past years, these containers have been variations on travel mugs, Sigg bottles, and nalgenes. Those dining halls that still offer \"To-Go\" options no longer provide paper bags, and instead use wax paper bags, [[biodegradable plastic]], and recyclable utensils made of vegetable cellulose. In the fall of 2017, Smith dining halls began to offer plastic tupperware containers students may borrow and return to the dining halls to be washed.\n\nFor Smith's efforts regarding sustainability, the institution earned a grade of \"A-\" on the \"College Sustainability Report Card 2010\" administered by the Sustainable Endowments Institute. Smith was lauded for many of the indicator categories, including student involvement, green building, and transportation, but was marked down for endowment transparency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/schools/smith-college |title=Smith College \u2013 Green Report Card 2010 |publisher=Greenreportcard.org |date=2008-06-30 |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620201946/http://greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/schools/smith-college |archive-date=2010-06-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumnae==\n<!--Please see Talk page discussion of notability criteria------------------------------------>\n<!--and the possibility of moving this section in its entirety to [[List of Smith College people]] or other page-->\n{{Main|List of Smith College people}}\n\nAmong the more notable of Smith College's alumnae in chronological order are:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* [[Otelia Cromwell]] (class of 1900): first African-American graduate of Smith college and the first African American woman to receive a doctorate from Yale\n* [[Eunice Carter]] (class of 1921): first female African-American assistant district attorney for the state of New York, active in the prosecution of mob boss Charles \"Lucky\" Luciano\n* [[Margaret Mitchell]] (class of 1922): author of ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]'', did not graduate from Smith\n* [[Julia Child]] (class of 1934): chef, author and television personality <ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Madeleine L'Engle]] (class of 1941): author\n* [[Betty Friedan]] (class of 1942): feminist and author of ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]''\n* [[Nancy Reagan]] (class of 1943): [[First Lady of the United States]] from 1981 to 1989\n* [[Penny Chenery]] (class of 1943): sportswoman, racehorse breeder and owner, horse racing advocate\n* [[Jean Harris]] (class of 1945): headmistress of the [[Madeira School]] who murdered her ex-lover [[Herman Tarnower]] in a jealous rage\n* [[Rhoda Dorsey]] (class of 1946): historian and first woman president of [[Goucher College]]\n* [[Barbara Bush]] (class of 1947): former [[First Lady of the United States]], did not graduate from Smith\n* [[Natalie Babbitt]] (class of 1954): notable illustrator and author of ''[[Tuck Everlasting]]''\n* [[Sylvia Plath]] (class of 1955): poet, novelist and short story author\n* [[Gloria Steinem]] (class of 1956): founder of ''[[Ms.]]'' magazine and noted feminist, activist, and journalist\n* [[Lynden B. Miller]] (class of 1960): public garden designer, park advocate and author\n* [[Jane Yolen]] (class of 1960): children's book author\n* [[Ng'endo Mwangi|Ng'endo (Florence) Mwangi]] (class of 1961): Kenya's first woman physician\n* [[Jane Harman]] (class of 1966): U.S. Representative for California's 36th Congressional District\n* [[Molly Ivins]] (class of 1966): journalist, political commentator, and humorist\n* [[Rochelle Lazarus|Shelly Lazarus]] (class of 1968): former CEO and Chairman of [[Ogilvy & Mather]]\n* [[Nikki Tsongas]] (class of 1968): U.S. Representative for Massachusetts' 3rd Congressional District\n* [[Catharine MacKinnon]] (class of 1968): notable proponent of [[radical feminism]], scholar, lawyer, teacher and activist\n* [[Laura D'Andrea Tyson]] (class of 1969): economist; Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|National Economic Council]]\n* [[Yolanda King]] (class of 1976): activist\n* [[Christine McCarthy]] (class of 1977): Chief Financial Officer of [[The Walt Disney Company]]\n* [[Ann M. Martin]] (class of 1978): author of ''[[The Babysitter's Club]]''\n* [[Phebe Novakovic]] (class of 1979): Chairman and CEO of [[General Dynamics]]\n* [[Ruth Ozeki]] (class of 1980): author of ''[[A Tale for the Time Being]]''\n* [[Margaret Edson]] (class of 1983): winner of a [[Pulitzer Prize]] for Drama\n* [[Tammy Baldwin]] (class of 1984): United States Senator\n* [[Tori Murden]] (class of 1985): the first woman to row solo across the Atlantic Ocean, and to ski to the geographic South Pole\n* [[Thelma Golden]] (class of 1987): Director and Chief Curator of [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]]\n* [[Durreen Shahnaz]] (class of 1989): founder of Impact Investment Exchange (IIX)\n* [[Piper Kerman]] (class of 1992): ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'' author, lived in Chapin House\n* [[Hanya Yanagihara]] (Class of 1995): author and editor\n* [[Luma Mufleh]] (class of 1997): founder and director of Fugees Family, Inc., a non-profit organization devoted to working with child survivors of war\n* [[Cass Bird]] (class of 1999): fashion photographer\n* [[Erin Morgenstern]] (class of 2000): ''[[The Night Circus]]'' author\n* [[Sara Haines]] (class of 2000): co-host of ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', [[ABC News]] correspondent\n* [[Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy]] (class of 2002): documentarian, winner of two [[Academy Awards]]\n* [[Julia Scott]] (class of 2002): [[NPR]] and ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' journalist\n* [[Kimberly Drew]] (class of 2012): art curator and cultural critic\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable staff==\n* [[Herbert Baxter Adams]] (1850\u20131901), educator, historian, and cofounder of the [[American Historical Association]] taught history at Smith from 1878 to 1881.<ref>\u201cProfessor Herbert Baxter Adams\u201d by B. J. Ramage in\nThe American Historical Magazine\nVol. 6, No. 4 (OCTOBER, 1901), pp. 363\u2013366</ref>\n* [[Louise Holland]] (1893\u20131990), academic, philologist and archaeologist, taught here from 1957 to 1964\n* In 1960, three Smith professors, one who had been there for 38 years, were fired or \"allowed to retire\" for being [[Homosexual|gay]]. This was chronicled in a book (''The Scarlet Professor\u2014[[Newton Arvin]]: A Literary Life Shattered by Scandal'' (Doubleday, 2001), by Barry Werth), and the PBS Independent Lens film, ''The Great Pink Scare''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/greatpinkscare/film.html|title=The Great Pink Scare|publisher=Independent Television Service (ITVS)|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013855/https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/greatpinkscare/film.html|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2002, Smith, the nation's largest liberal arts college for women, acknowledged a wrong from four decades earlier by creating a lecture series and a small scholarship\u2014the $100,000 Dorius/Spofford Fund for the Study of Civil Liberties and Freedom of Expression, and the Newton Arvin Prize in American Studies, a $500 annual stipend. But despite faculty appeals, there was no apology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/20/obituaries/20dorius.html|title=Joel Dorius, 87, Victim in Celebrated Anti-Gay Case, Dies|date=20 February 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929045016/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/20/obituaries/20dorius.html|archive-date=29 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Artist [[Leonard Baskin]] taught at Smith from 1953 to 1974.\n* During the 2000\u20132001 school year, noted author and satirist [[Kurt Vonnegut]] served as Writer-in-Residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/00-019.html|title=Acclaimed Satirist and Best-Selling Novelist to Give Public \"Performance\" at Smith|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2013-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904084948/http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/00-019.html|archive-date=2012-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Hale]], speech and drama teacher, and muse of [[T.S. Eliot]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cambridge School of Architecture and Landscape Architecture]]\n* [[College Archives (Smith College)]]\n* [[Tofu Curtain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [[Helen Lefkowitz Horowitz|Horowitz, Helen Lefkowitz]]. [https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0870238698&id=Z3qWLyDZ8PsC&pg=PP1 ''Alma Mater: Design and Experience in the Women's Colleges from Their Nineteenth-Century Beginnings to the 1930s''], Amherst: [[University of Massachusetts Press]], 1993 (2nd edition).\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Smith College}}\n{{Wikisource|Portal:Smith College|Smith College}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smith.edu/}}\n* [http://www.smithpioneers.com Official athletics website]\n* [http://www.thesmithsophian.com/ ''The Sophian''], Smith's student newspaper\n\n{{Smith College}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{CLAC}}\n{{Five Colleges}}\n{{Seven Sisters}}\n{{New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Current women's universities and colleges in the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Smith College| ]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Northampton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Seven Sister Colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish | William Smith College}}\n{{short description|Private women's liberal arts college in Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox university\n|image_name      = Smith College seal.svg\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         =\n|motto           = \u1f18\u03bd \u03c4\u1fc7 \u1f00\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u1fc7 \u03c4\u1f74\u03bd \u03b3\u03bd\u1ff6\u03c3\u03b9\u03bd ([[Greek language|Greek]])\n|mottoeng        = In Virtue [One Gains] Knowledge\n|established     = 1871 (opened 1875)\n|type            = [[Private school|Private]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]]<br>[[Women's colleges in the United States|Women's college]]\n|endowment       = $1.91 billion (2019)<ref>As of June 30, 2019. {{cite web |url=https://www.nacubo.org/-/media/Nacubo/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2019-NTSE-Endowment-Market-Values--FINAL-January-30-2020.ashx|title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2019 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2018 to FY 2019 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and TIAA |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|president       = [[Kathleen McCartney (college president)|Kathleen McCartney]]\n|faculty         = 285<ref name=\"justthefacts\">[http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php Just the Facts] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050512074309/http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |date=2005-05-12 }}, Smith College website.</ref>\n|students        = 2,903 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019>{{cite web |url= https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2018\u20132019 |publisher=Smith College |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227180325/http://www.smith.edu/ir/docs/Smith_College_CDS_2015-2016_Published_for_Distribution_incomplete.pdf |archivedate=2015-12-27 }}</ref>\n|undergrad       = 2,502 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019/>\n|postgrad        = 401 (Fall 2018)<ref name=CDS_2018-2019/>\n|city            = [[Northampton, Massachusetts|Northampton]]\n|state           = [[Massachusetts]]\n|country         = United States\n|coor            = {{Coord|42.318119|-72.638139|region:US_type:edu|display=inline, title}}\n|campus          = [[Town|Small-town]]\n|colors          = Blue with gold trim {{Color box|#002D62|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|#F1AB00|border=darkgray}}<ref name=Colors>{{cite web|title=Smith College:Visual Identity Program|url=http://www.smith.edu/vid/using.php|publisher=Smith College|accessdate=20 August 2012|year=2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520112207/http://www.smith.edu/vid/using.php|archive-date=20 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|nickname        = Pioneers\n|athletics       = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] \u2013 [[New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference|NEWMAC]]\n|affiliations    = [[National Association of Independent Colleges and Universities|NAICU]]<ref>[http://www.naicu.edu/member_center/members.asp NAICU \u2013 Member Directory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109231238/http://www.naicu.edu/member_center/members.asp |date=2015-11-09 }}</ref><br>[[Five Colleges (Massachusetts)|Five Colleges]]<br>[[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]]<br>[[Annapolis Group]]<br>[[Oberlin Group]]<br>[[Consortium of Liberal Arts Colleges|CLAC]]\n|website         = [http://www.smith.edu/ smith.edu]\n|logo = [[File:Smithcollege-logo.png|200px]]\n}}\n'''Smith College''' is a [[Private university|private]] [[Women's colleges in the United States|women's]] [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Northampton, Massachusetts]]. Although its undergraduate programs are open to women only, its graduate and certificate programs are also open to men. It is the largest member of the [[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters]]. Smith is also a member of the [[Five Colleges Consortium]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fivecolleges.edu |title=Five Colleges, Incorporated: Home |publisher=Fivecolleges.edu |accessdate=2016-09-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913145340/https://www.fivecolleges.edu/ |archive-date=2016-09-13 |url-status=live }}</ref> which allows its students to attend classes at four other [[Pioneer Valley]] institutions: [[Mount Holyoke College]], [[Amherst College]], [[Hampshire College]], and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]].<ref>[http://www.fivecolleges.edu] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216091104/https://www.fivecolleges.edu/ |date=2019-12-16 }} Five College Consortium website. \"Accessed July 9, 2009\"</ref> ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' ranks it 11th best among National Liberal Arts Colleges.<ref name=USNWR/> Smith is one of the few women's colleges that offers an engineering degree in four years.\n\n==History==\nThe college was chartered in 1871 by a bequest of [[Sophia Smith]] and opened its doors in 1875 with 14 students and 6 faculty.<ref>[https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/smith-history/sophia-smith \"Sophia Smith\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211124848/https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/smith-history/sophia-smith |date=2016-12-11 }}, Smith College website.</ref> When she inherited a fortune from her father at age 65, Smith decided leaving her inheritance to found a women's college was the best way for her to fulfill the moral obligation she expressed in her will:\n\n<blockquote>I hereby make the following provisions for the establishment and maintenance of an Institution for the higher education of young women, with the design to furnish for my own sex means and facilities for education equal to those which are afforded now in our colleges to young men.<ref>[http://www.smith.edu/about_smithtradition.php smith.edu] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226230052/http://www.smith.edu/about_smithtradition.php |date=2009-02-26 }}, Smith College Web site</ref></blockquote>\n\nBy 1915\u201316, the student enrollment was 1,724, and the faculty numbered 163. Today, with some 2,600 undergraduates on campus, and 250 students studying elsewhere,<ref name=\"smith1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |title=Smith College: Just the Facts |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527115157/http://www.smith.edu/about_justthefacts.php |archive-date=2010-05-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> Smith is the largest privately endowed college for women in the country.<ref>{{cite book|title=Peterson's Four-year Colleges 2008 |publisher=Peterson |year=2007 |page=2226 |isbn=978-0-7689-2400-8}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Naval Reserve Midshipmen's School]] at Smith College in [[Northampton, Massachusetts]], was training grounds for junior officers of the [[WAVES|Women's Reserve of the U.S. Naval Reserve (WAVES)]] and was nicknamed \"USS Northampton\". On August 28, 1942, a total of 120 women reported to the school for training.<ref name=\"smith-waryears\">{{cite web |url=http://lmliberty.us/2011/08/28/naval-history-aug-28/#axzz1YkXn9YQa |title=Naval History \u2013 August 28 |accessdate=September 19, 2011 |publisher=Lake Minnetonka Liberty, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402203740/http://lmliberty.us/2011/08/28/naval-history-aug-28/#axzz1YkXn9YQa |archivedate=April 2, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:\"Lt.(jg.) Harriet Ida Pickens and Ens. Frances Wills, first Negro Waves to be commissioned. They were members of the fin - NARA - 520670.tif|thumb|right|200px|[[Lieutenant (junior grade)|LTJG]] Harriet Ida Pickens and [[Ensign (rank)|ENS]] Frances Wills, first African-American [[WAVES]] to be commissioned. They were members of the final graduating class at USNR Midshipmen's School (WR) Northampton, Massachusetts on December 21, 1944.]]\n\nSmith has been led by 11 presidents and two acting presidents. ([[Elizabeth Cutter Morrow]] was the first acting president of Smith College and the first female head of the college, but she did not use the title of president.) For the 1975 centennial, the college inaugurated its first woman president, [[Jill Ker Conway]], who came to Smith from [[Australia]] by way of [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and the [[University of Toronto]]. Since President Conway's term, all Smith presidents have been women, with the exception of John M. Connolly's one-year term as acting president in the interim after President Simmons left to lead [[Brown University]].\n* [[Laurenus Clark Seelye]] 1875\u20131910\n* [[Marion LeRoy Burton]] 1910\u20131917\n* [[William Allan Neilson]] 1917\u20131939\n* [[Elizabeth Cutter Morrow]] 1939\u20131940 (acting president)\n* [[Herbert Davis]] 1940\u20131949\n* Benjamin Fletcher Wright 1949\u20131959\n* [[Thomas C. Mendenhall (historian)|Thomas Corwin Mendenhall]] 1959\u20131975\n* [[Jill Ker Conway]] 1975\u20131985\n* [[Mary Maples Dunn]] 1985\u20131995\n* [[Ruth Simmons]] 1995\u20132001\n* John M. Connolly 2001\u20132002 (acting president)\n* [[Carol T. Christ]] 2002\u20132013\n* [[Kathleen McCartney (college president)|Kathleen McCartney]] 2013\u2013present\n\nOn December 10, 2012, the Board of Trustees announced Kathleen McCartney had been selected as the 11th president of Smith College effective July 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newpresident/|title=The 11th President of Smith|accessdate=January 17, 2013|publisher=Smith College, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115002436/http://www.smith.edu/newpresident/|archive-date=January 15, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elm Tree at Smith College, Northampton, MA June 2012.jpg|thumb|right|One of the oldest American Elm trees on the Smith campus.<ref name=\"100years\" />]]The campus was planned and planted in the 1890s as a [[botanical garden]] and [[arboretum]], designed by [[Frederick Law Olmsted]].<ref name=\"100years\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/news/2002/OldTrees.html |title=100 Years And Counting, If These Trees Could Talk |website=Smith College website (News & Events) |date=2002-03-01 |accessdate=2014-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226020058/http://www.smith.edu/news/2002/OldTrees.html |archive-date=2014-12-26 |url-status=live }}</ref> The campus landscape now encompasses {{convert|147|acre}} and includes more than 1,200 varieties of trees and shrubs.\n[[File:Camperdown Elm at Smith College campus, Northampton, MA - January 2015.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Camperdown Elm tree near arboretum.]]\n\nIn April 2015, the faculty adopted an [[open-access policy]] to make its scholarship [[open access|publicly accessible]] online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://roarmap.eprints.org/832/ |title=Smith College |work=[[ROARMAP]]: Registry of Open Access Repository Mandates and Policies |publisher=[[University of Southampton]] |location=UK |accessdate=2018-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713063743/http://roarmap.eprints.org/832/ |archive-date=2017-07-13 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nSmith College has 285 professors in 41 academic departments and programs, for a faculty:student ratio of 1:9.<ref name=\"smith1\"/> It was the first women's college in the United States to grant its own undergraduate degrees in [[engineering]]. The Picker Engineering Program offers a single [[ABET]] accredited [[Bachelor of Science]] in engineering science, combining the fundamentals of multiple engineering disciplines.\n\nSmith has joined the [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States#SAT optional movement|SAT optional movement]] for undergraduate admission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/metrowest/republican/index.ssf?/base/news-14/1211786427249410.xml&coll=1|title=Smith drops SATs|last=Contrada|first=Fred|date=May 26, 2008|publisher=MassLive.com|accessdate=October 10, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625004817/http://www.masslive.com/metrowest/republican/index.ssf?%2Fbase%2Fnews-14%2F1211786427249410.xml&coll=1|archivedate=June 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSmith runs its own junior year abroad (JYA) programs in four European cities: [[Paris]], [[Hamburg]], [[Florence]] and [[Geneva]].<ref>[http://www.smith.edu/studyabroad/jya.php Smith College: Study Abroad] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120719145941/http://www.smith.edu/studyabroad/jya.php# |date=2012-07-19 }}. Smith.edu. Retrieved on 2013-09-07.</ref> These programs are notable for requiring all studies to be conducted in the language of the host country (with both Paris and Geneva programs conducted in French). In some cases students live in homestays with local families. Nearly half of Smith's juniors study overseas, either through Smith JYA programs or at more than 40 other locations around the world.\n\nJunior math majors from other undergraduate institutions are invited to study at Smith College for one year through the [[Center for Women in Mathematics]]. Established in the fall of 2007 by Professors [[Ruth Haas]] and Jim Henle, the program aims to allow young women to improve their mathematical abilities through classwork, research and involvement in a department centered on women. The [[Center for Women in Mathematics|Center]] also offers a post-baccalaureate year of math study to women who either did not major in mathematics as undergraduates or whose mathematics major was not strong.<ref>[http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/NAM/newsletter/NAM38.1.pdf \"Smith College Women in Mathematics Program\" National Association of Mathematicians, Spring 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910095330/http://www.math.buffalo.edu/mad/NAM/newsletter/NAM38.1.pdf |date=2008-09-10 }}. Retrieved 3 September 2008.</ref>\n\nThe Louise W. and Edmund J. Kahn Liberal Arts Institute supports collaborative research without regard to the traditional boundaries of academic departments and programs. Each year the Institute supports long-term and short-term projects proposed, planned and organized by members of the Smith College faculty. By becoming Kahn Fellows, students get involved in interdisciplinary research projects and work alongside faculty and visiting scholars for a year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/kahninstitute/ |title=Smith College: Kahn Liberal Arts Institute |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701234250/http://www.smith.edu/kahninstitute/ |archive-date=2010-07-01 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStudents can develop leadership skills through Smith's two-year Phoebe Reese Lewis Leadership Program. Participants train in public speaking, analytical thinking, teamwork strategies and the philosophical aspects of leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialleadership.php |title=Smith College: Academic Programs |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527184341/http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialleadership.php |archivedate=2010-05-27 }}</ref>\n\nThrough Smith's internship program, \"Praxis: The Liberal Arts at Work,\" every undergraduate is guaranteed access to one college funded internship during her years at the college. This program enables students to access interesting self-generated internship positions in social welfare and human services, the arts, media, health, education, and other fields.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialpraxis.php |title=Smith College: Academic Programs |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101010171913/http://www.smith.edu/acad_specialpraxis.php |archivedate=2010-10-10 }}</ref>\n\n===Admissions===\nThe 2019 annual ranking of ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'' categorizes Smith as 'most selective'.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209 |title=U.S. News Best Colleges Rankings: Smith College |year=2019 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=July 2, 2019 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702140454/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209 |archive-date=July 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFor the Class of 2022 (enrolling fall 2018), Smith received 5,780 applications, accepted 1,789 (31.0%) and enrolled 613.<ref name=CDS>{{cite web |url=https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |title=Common Data Set 2018\u20132019, Part C |publisher=Smith College |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105231541/https://www.smith.edu/sites/default/files/media/Office%20Images/Institutional-Research/Smith%20College_Common%20Data%20Set%202018-2019_Version%201.pdf |archive-date=2019-01-05 |url-status=live }}</ref> The middle 50% range of [[SAT scores]] was 670\u2013750 for critical reading and 670\u2013770 for math, while the middle 50% range for the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] composite score was 31\u201334 for enrolled first year students.<ref name=CDS/>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes   = 81\n| USNWR_LA = 11\n| Wamo_LA  = 28\n| THE_WSJ  = 41\n}}\n\n[[File:SmithCollege Seelye Hall.jpg|thumb|right|Seelye Hall]]\n\n''U.S. News & World Report'''s 2020 rankings placed Smith tied for the 11th best liberal arts college in the nation.<ref name=USNWR>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209/overall-rankings |title=Smith College Rankings |year=2020 |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |access-date=November 5, 2019 |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124141821/https://www.usnews.com/best-colleges/smith-college-2209/overall-rankings |archive-date=November 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same publication's rankings of liberal arts colleges, Smith is rated 5th for \"Best Value\" and tied for 11th in \"Most Innovative Schools\".<ref name=USNWR/> In 2019, ''[[Forbes]]'' rated Smith 81st overall in its America's Top Colleges ranking of 650 military academies, national universities, and liberal arts colleges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/top-colleges/list/ |magazine=Forbes |title=America's Top Colleges |date=August 15, 2019 |access-date=September 12, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810053444/http://www.forbes.com/top-colleges/list/ |archive-date=August 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Kiplinger's Personal Finance]]'' places Smith 16th in its 2019 ranking of 149 best value liberal arts colleges in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-best-college-values-college-finder/index.php#Table | magazine=Kiplinger's Personal Finance | title=Kiplinger's Best College Values | date=July 2019 | access-date=2019-08-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823230821/https://www.kiplinger.com/tool/college/T014-S001-best-college-values-college-finder/index.php#Table | archive-date=2019-08-23 | url-status=live }}</ref>  For 2019, ''[[Washington Monthly]]'' ranked Smith 28th among 214 liberal arts colleges in the U.S. based on its contribution to the public good, as measured by social mobility, research, and promoting public service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://washingtonmonthly.com/2019college-guide/liberalarts |title=2019 Liberal Arts College Rankings |magazine=Washington Monthly |access-date=November 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927151745/https://washingtonmonthly.com/2019college-guide/liberalarts |archive-date=September 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Ada Comstock Scholars Program===\nThe '''Ada Comstock Scholars Program''' is an undergraduate degree program that serves Smith students of [[Non-traditional student|nontraditional college age]]. The program accommodates approximately 100 women ranging in age from mid-twenties to over sixty. Ada Comstock Scholars attend the same classes as traditional undergraduates, either full or part-time, and participate fully in a variety of extracurricular activities. They may live on or off campus. Financial aid is available to each Ada Comstock Scholar with demonstrated need.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/admission/ada.php|title=Smith College: For Nontraditional Students|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419185939/http://www.smith.edu/admission/ada.php/|archive-date=2015-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1968, with the approval of the Committee on Educational Policy, Smith College initiated a trial program loosely titled ''The Continuing Education Degree'' for several women of non-traditional age who were looking to complete their unfinished degrees. Their successes inspired President [[Thomas C. Mendenhall (historian)|Thomas C. Mendenhall]] and Dean Alice Dickinson to officially expand the program. In January 1975, the '''Ada Comstock Scholars Program''' was formally established under President [[Jill Ker Conway]] and in the fall of that year forty-five women were enrolled. The students range in ages, backgrounds, and geographical locations. The growth of the program peaked just over 400 students in 1988.\n\nThe program is named for [[Ada Comstock|Ada Louise Comstock Notestein]] (1876\u20131973), an 1897 Smith graduate, professor of English and dean of Smith from 1912\u201323, and president of [[Radcliffe College]] from 1923\u201343. Ada Comstock Notestein devoted much of her life to the academic excellence of women. Considering education and personal growth to be a lifelong process, she stayed actively involved in women's higher education until her death at the age of 97.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/classdeans/adas_history.php|title=Smith College: Class Deans|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419014932/http://www.smith.edu/classdeans/adas_history.php|archive-date=2015-04-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate degrees and study options===\nSmith offers men and women graduate work leading to the degrees of master of arts in teaching (elementary, middle or high school), master of fine arts, master of education of the deaf, master of science in biological sciences, master of science in exercise and sport studies and master and Ph.D. in social work. In special one-year programs, international students may qualify for a certificate of graduate studies or a diploma in American studies. Each year approximately 100 men and women pursue advanced graduate work at Smith.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/degrees.php |title=Smith College: Graduate Study |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615153802/http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/degrees.php |archive-date=2010-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlso offered in a non-degree studies program is the Diploma in American Studies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/nondegree.php |title=Smith College: Graduate Study |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615144512/http://www.smith.edu/gradstudy/nondegree.php |archive-date=2010-06-15 |url-status=live }}</ref> This is a highly competitive one-year program open only to international students of advanced undergraduate or graduate standing. It is designed primarily, although not exclusively, for those who are teaching or who plan to teach some aspect of American culture and institutions.\n\nThe [[Smith College School for Social Work]] is nationally recognized for its specialization in clinical social work and puts a heavy emphasis on direct field work practice. The program is accredited by the [[Council on Social Work Education]]. The school offers a Master of Social Work (M.S.W.) degree as well as a Ph.D. program designed to prepare MSWs for leadership positions in clinical research education and practice.\n\nThe college has a limited number of other programs leading to Ph.D.s, and is part of a cooperative doctoral program co-administered by [[Amherst College]], [[Hampshire College]], [[Mount Holyoke College]] and the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]].\n\n==Traditions==\n\n===Residential culture and student life===\nSmith requires most undergraduate students to live in on-campus houses unless they reside locally with their family. This policy is intended to add to the camaraderie and social cohesion of its students. Unlike most institutions of its type, Smith College does not have dorms, but rather 36 separate houses, ranging in architectural style from 18th-century to contemporary. It is rumored the architecture of Chapin House was the inspiration for the Tara Plantation House in ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]''. (Author [[Margaret Mitchell]] went to Smith for one year and lived in Chapin.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2017-07-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104143010/https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref> A novelty of Smith's homelike atmosphere is the continuing popularity of Sophia Smith's recipe<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clio.fivecolleges.edu/smith/sophia/fun/fun.htm |title=Sophia Through the Years |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2017-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309173039/http://clio.fivecolleges.edu/smith/sophia/fun/fun.htm |archive-date=2018-03-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> for molasses cookies. These are often served at the traditional Friday afternoon tea held in each house, where students, faculty and staff members and alumnae socialize.<ref name=\"justthefacts\" />\n\nTwo cultural spaces on campus, used by students of color to build their community, include the Mwangi Cultural Center and Unity House. Mwangi originally opened as the Afro-American Cultural Center in 1968, but was later renamed in honor of the first female physician in Kenya, and Smith alum, Dr. Ng\u2019endo Mwangi 61\u2019. After loaning Mwangi to the other cultural organizations on campus for four years, the Black Students\u2019 Alliance decided to reclaim Mwangi in April 1990. [https://sophia.smith.edu/weaving-voices-archives/1990/04/26/black-students-alliance-bsa-unanimously-votes-to-reclaim-mwangi-center/ Reclaiming Cultural Center Smith College] Leaders, members and supporters of cultural organizations got together to form a group called UNITY, in October of the same year, to demand a space for other cultural organizations. [https://sophia.smith.edu/weaving-voices-archives/1990/10/26/unity-orgs-hold-rally-college-hall-sit-in-to-protest-for-space/ Weaving Voices Archive UNITY] Today, Unity House serves as a home to the 11 cultural organizations on campus. [https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/multicultural-affairs/cultural-spaces Cultural Spaces Smith College]\n\nTwo recent additions to the campus, both of which enhance its sense of community, are the architecturally dramatic Campus Center <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/campuscenter/ |title=Smith College: Office of Student Engagement |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724043800/http://www.smith.edu/campuscenter/ |archive-date=2010-07-24 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the state-of-the-art Olin Fitness Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/news/2003-04/OlinOpening.html |title=Smith College: News |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720045318/http://www.smith.edu/news/2003-04/OlinOpening.html |archive-date=2011-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, construction was also completed on Ford Hall, a new science and engineering facility. According to the Smith College website, Ford Hall is a \"...facility that will intentionally blur the boundaries between traditional disciplines, creating an optimum environment for students and faculty to address key scientific and technological developments of our time.\" The building was officially dedicated on October 16, 2009.<ref>Ford Hall: http://www.smith.edu/fordhall/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305171516/http://www.smith.edu/fordhall/ |date=2010-03-05 }}</ref>\n\nThe campus also boasts a botanic garden that includes a variety of specialty gardens including a rock garden and historic glass greenhouses dating back to 1895. The botanic garden formerly featured a Japanese tea hut, which was removed in October 2015 following concerns over \"issues of safety and vandalism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/news/announcement.php?id=26939|title=Smith College: Grecourt Gate Announcement|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2016-10-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012153347/https://www.smith.edu/news/announcement.php?id=26939|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSmith offers \"panel discussions and seminars for lesbian, bisexual, and transgender students on subjects such as coming out as transgender at work.\"<ref>April 8, 2007 article, Boston Globe, http://www.boston.com/news/globe/magazine/articles/2007/04/08/when_she_graduates_as_he/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090127062345/http://www.boston.com/news/globe/magazine/articles/2007/04/08/when_she_graduates_as_he/ |date=2009-01-27 }}</ref> In 2003, Smith students voted to remove pronouns from the language of the Student Government Association constitution, in order to make that document inclusive of transgender students who don't identify with the pronouns \"she\" and \"her.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/oid/gender_faq.php |title=Smith College: Office of Institutional Diversity |publisher=Smith.edu |accessdate=2010-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110128180340/http://www.smith.edu/oid/gender_faq.php |archivedate=2011-01-28 }}</ref>\n\nUntil 2013, transgender women were not allowed to attend Smith unless all their legal documentation consistently stated they were female. This policy came to public attention in March 2013 when Smith rejected the application of a [[trans woman]] named Calliope Wong. In the rejection letter, Smith's Dean of Admission Debra Shaver wrote \"Your [[FAFSA]] indicates your gender as male. Therefore, Smith cannot process your application.\" This policy was changed in 2013 to only require all non legal application materials to indicate a female identity, including references. Not satisfied with the change, students as well as various alumni formed the group Q&A (\"Queers and Allies\") to advocate for more trans-inclusive policies.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Drew|first=Sophie|date=|title=Challenging Gender at a Women\u2019s Institution:\nTransgender Admission and Inclusion at Smith College|url=|journal=Women Leading Change \u00a9 Newcomb College Institute|volume=3|pages=25-36|via=}}</ref> Q&A subsequently protested the policy on [[Facebook]] and other [[social media]] websites, as well as staging protests on campus that garnered significant media attention.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/krystieyandoli/students-at-smith-protest-the-colleges-refusal-to-admit-tran|title=Students At Smith Protest The College's Refusal To Admit Transgender Women|last=Yandoli|first=Krystie Lee|website=BuzzFeed|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2014, Smith formed an Admissions Policy Study Group, co-chaired by Daphne Lamothe and Audrey Smith, who at the time were associate professor of Afro-American studies and vice president for enrollment, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/president-kathleen-mccartney/letters/2014-15/admission-policy|title=President - Letters - Admission Policy Study Group|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> The group recommended that to be considered for admission to Smith, applicants live and/or identify as a woman, check the \"female\" box when applying, and that the President establish a working group to support all [[Transgender|trans]] and [[Non-binary gender|non-binary]] students at Smith.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/about.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> These recommendations went to the faculty<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/about.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and the Board of Trustees<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/05/04/living/smith-college-transgender-women-feat/index.html|title=Smith College to admit transgender women|first=Brandon |last=Griggs|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and in 2015, Smith announced a [[Transgender admissions policies at women's colleges|new policy]] that only required female identification on the common application.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jaschik |first1=Scott |title=Tipping Point for Trans Admissions? |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/04/smith-college-will-accept-transgender-applicants-who-identify-women |website=Inside Higher Ed |accessdate=5 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706213758/https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/04/smith-college-will-accept-transgender-applicants-who-identify-women |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the policy, [[transgender men]] and non-binary or [[genderqueer]] applicants are not eligible for admission.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/studygroup/faq.php|title=Smith College: Admission Policy Study Group FAQ|last=|first=|date=|website=www.smith.edu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> This new policy also affirms that any student who, once admitted, transitions to another identity other than \"female\" and, who completes the college\u2019s graduation requirements, will be awarded a Smith degree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/gender-identity-expression|title=Offices - Diversity - Gender Identity & Expression|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129052732/https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/gender-identity-expression|archive-date=2019-11-29|url-status=live}}</ref> The Resource Center for Sexuality and Gender; The Office for Equity and Inclusion and its Trans/Non-binary Working Group; Transcending Gender, a student group focused on support and education; and the Transgender Support Group run by Counseling Services work to support trans and non-binary students at Smith across the [[gender identity]] spectrum.  \n\nIn the fall of 2018, students at Smith protested after a Smith employee called the police on a black student working at Smith over the summer, when the employee saw her in a common space. Organized by the Black Students\u2019 Alliance and the Smith African & Caribbean Students Association, students protested and walked out of the annual Smith [[convocation]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2018/09/05/protests-mark-start-new-semester-smith-college/RCtAtCTdwGV28AhdWxygcM/story.html|title=Protests mark start of new semester at Smith College - The Boston Globe|last=Fern|first=Deirdre|last2=|first2=|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=September 5|last4=2018|last5=Comments|first5=10:14 p m Email to a Friend Share on Facebook Share on TwitterPrint this Article View}}</ref> While the incident received national attention and news coverage, Smith conducted an independent investigation and investigators found that there was no [[bias]] in the incident.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/10/30/investigation-finds-no-policy-violations-when-police-were-called-black-student|title=Investigation finds no policy violations when police were called on a black student|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In response to the incident, Smith hosted an Inclusion and Diversity Conference on April 10th, 2019, featuring workshops and presenters run by various members of the Smith community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/president-kathleen-mccartney/letters/2018-19/inclusion-diversity-conference|title=President - Letters - Inclusion and Diversity Conference on April 10|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> However, during that time another controversy arose: the hiring of [[Mount Holyoke College]] and Smith's joint police chief, Daniel Hect. Students from both campuses brought to their administrators' attention the fact that Hect had \"liked\" far-right tweets on [[Twitter]], such as [[Donald Trump]] tweeting \"Build that Wall!\" and a tweet from the [[National Rifle Association]], before deleting his account once the conflict with students began.Tensions came to a head at the conference, when students protested a presentation from the campus police, including Hect, about policing in a diverse community. Protests continued the next day when hundreds of students participated in a [[sit-in]] organized by the group Students for Social Justice and Institutional Change, or SSJIC, outside of John M. Greene Hall. The group was originally formed to advocate for undocumented students, but expanded to a broad coalition of marginalized students, including [[students of color]], [[Low income|low-income]] and trans students. The coalition presented a broad list of demands to the administration, proposing reform to many sectors of campus life, including curriculum, health and counseling services, accessibility, policing, admissions policies and affinity housing.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gazettenet.com/Smith-College-students-protest-against-racism-new-police-chief-24764370|title=As students protest, Smith and Mount Holyoke colleges put new joint chief of police on leave|last=Christensen|first=Dusty|date=2019-04-11|website=Daily Hampshire Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In response to the demands, Smith launched a working group charged with identifying key themes in response to the day of inclusion and ensuing protests<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/equity-inclusion/inclusion-in-action/working-group-report|title=Offices - Diversity - Inclusion Conference - Working Group Report|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> and revamped the Office of Equity and Inclusion, adding programmatic changes, new or modified positions, training and development opportunities and new events to promote inclusion and equity.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/toward-equity-and-inclusion|title=About Smith - Toward Equity and Inclusion|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> \n\n====Houses====\n{{See also|Smith College Housing}}\n[[File:Ginkgo tree on Smith College campus, Northampton, MA - January 2015.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Ginkgo tree near arboretum]]\nSmith College has many different houses serving as dormitories. Each house is self-governing. While many students remain in the same house for the entirety of their four years at Smith, they are not obligated to do so, and may move to different houses on campus as space allows. While houses previously collected dues, in the 2019-2020 school year they were eradicated to avoid placing financial pressure on low-income students or students who were otherwise unable to pay without sacrificing funding for the House.\n\nHouses are found in four main regions of campus: Upper and Lower Elm Street, Green Street, Center Campus, and the Quadrangle. Each region can, in turn, be divided into smaller areas to more precisely provide the location of the house in question. In 2019, the college shifted from officially recognizing the four main areas of campus to instead categorizing houses in four neighborhoods: Ivy, Paradise, Mountain, and Garden. This change was largely internal, and categorizes houses by size rather than location.\n\n=====Green Street Houses=====\n* Hubbard House \u2013 Hubbard House is the residence of fictional President [[Selina Meyer]] from the HBO Show [[Veep]]. [[Julia Child]] resided in this house during her time at Smith.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Julia Child Rules: Lessons On Savoring Life|last=Karbo|first=Karen|publisher=Globe Pequot Press: Morris Publishing Group|year=2013|isbn=9780762783090|location=Guilford, Connecticut|pages=[https://archive.org/details/juliachildrulesl0000karb/page/47 47\u201348]|url=https://archive.org/details/juliachildrulesl0000karb/page/47}}</ref>\n* Lawrence House\n* Morris House \u2013 Morris was built in 1891, with its sister house Lawrence to help accommodate the growing student body. It is named after Kate Morris Cone, Smith College class of 1879.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kimball Union Archives ~ Kate Eugenia Morris (Cone), Class of 1875|url=http://kimballunionarchives.com/2012/02/08/kate-eugenia-morris-cone-class-of-1875/|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222064615/http://kimballunionarchives.com/2012/02/08/kate-eugenia-morris-cone-class-of-1875/|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Smith College Residence Life \u2013 Morris House|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_morris.php|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222224804/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_morris.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Tyler House\n* Washburn House - As of 2017, Washburn is closed due to the construction of the new Neilson Library.\n* 44 Green Street\n* 54 Green Street\n* Chapin House \u2013 Author [[Margaret Mitchell]] lived here. Chapin's staircase served as the inspiration for the staircase of Scarlett O'Hara's Tara in ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone With the Wind]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|website=www.smith.edu|access-date=2018-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104143010/https://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_green_chapin.php|archive-date=2018-01-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====Center Campus Houses=====\n* Cutter House\n* Haven/Wesley Houses\n* Hopkins House\n* Park Complex\n**Park Annex - one of two new Affinity houses at Smith College, houses that cater to minority identities on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/student-life/residence-life/houses/park-annex|title=Student Life - Res Life - Smith Houses - Center Campus - Park Annex|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n* Sessions Complex\n* Tenney House\n* Ziskind House\n\n=====Upper Elm Street Houses=====\n[[File:The Botanic Garden of Smith College.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|The Botanic Gardens at Smith College]]\n* Capen House \u2013 Built in 1825 by Samuel Howe, the founder of [[Northampton Law School]], it became part of the Capen School in 1883 and was willed to the college by the school's founder in 1921. It is designed in the [[Neoclassical architecture|Classical Revival]] style.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lincoln |first=Eleanor T. |title=This, The House We Live In |date=1983 |location=Northampton, MA |isbn=0-87391-030-3 |pages=112\u2013115}}</ref> It is named after the founder of the Capen School, Bessie Talbot Capen. \n* Gillett House \u2013 Connected to Northrop house via a breezeway, Gillett houses the only vegan/vegetarian dining hall on campus.\n* Lamont House \u2013 Built in 1955, Lamont House was the first house constructed after the construction of the Quad houses in 1936. Named for alumna Florence Corliss Lamont, who earned her A.B. in 1893 and later an M.A. from Columbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_lamont.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222224752/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_lamont.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> She married Harvard graduate and future Smith Trustee Thomas Lamont and had four children. Through her life she would continue to give generously to her alma mater. Lamont House is just across Elm Street, tucked behind Northrop and Gillett Houses. Lamont houses 83 students.<ref>[http://sophia.smith.edu/blog/smithipedia/houses/lamont-house/ Lamont House \u00ab Smithipedia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204214913/http://sophia.smith.edu/blog/smithipedia/houses/lamont-house/ |date=2013-12-04 }}. Sophia.smith.edu (2010-06-22). Retrieved on 2014-04-12.</ref>\n* Northrop House\n* Parsons Complex\n**Parsons Annex - one of two new Affinity houses at Smith College, houses that cater to minority identities on campus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/student-life/residence-life/houses/parsons-annex|title=Student Life - Res Life - Smith Houses - Green Street - Parsons Annex|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n* Talbot House \u2013 Built in 1909 as part of the Capen School, it was willed to the college in 1921. Its mascot is the moose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_talbot.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2014-02-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222225006/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_upperelm_talbot.php|archive-date=2014-02-22|url-status=live}}</ref> US First Lady Nancy Reagan '43 lived here during her time at Smith.{{Citation needed|date=January 2019}} It is also named for Bessie Talbot Capen.\n\n=====Lower Elm Street Houses=====\n* Albright House\n* Baldwin House \u2013 U.S. Senator [[Tammy Baldwin]] ('84) was a Baldwin House resident during her time at Smith College.\n* Chase House\n* Conway House\n* Duckett House\n* 150 Elm Street\n\n=====East Quadrangle Houses=====\n* Cushing House\n* Emerson House\n* Jordan House, built in 1922 and named for the longtime head of the Smith English Department, [[List of feminist rhetoricians#Mary Augusta Jordan|Mary Augusta Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Colton |title=Mary Augusta Jordan |url=http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/alumni/mary-augusta-jordan.html |work=Vassar Encyclopedia |accessdate=7 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222004549/http://vcencyclopedia.vassar.edu/alumni/mary-augusta-jordan.html |archive-date=22 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* King House, named for Franklin King, who served as the superintendent of building and grounds at Smith for 50 years <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_king.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924120933/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_king.php|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Scales House, King's \"sister house,\" was named after Laura Woolsey Lord Scales, who graduated from Smith in 1901 and was the school's first dean of students <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_scales.php|title=Smith College: Residence Life|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2015-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924120943/http://www.smith.edu/reslife/houses_eastquad_scales.php|archive-date=2015-09-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====West Quadrangle Houses=====\n* Comstock House\n* Gardiner House\n* Morrow House\n* Wilder House\n* Wilson House\n* Friedman Apartments\n\n====Campus folklore====\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2017}}\nSmith has numerous folk tales and ghost stories emerge from the histories of some of its historic buildings. One such tale holds Sessions House is inhabited by the ghost of Lucy Hunt, who died of a broken heart after being separated from her lover, General Burgoyne. Reports of a ghost in Sessions House predate its history as a campus house. Built in 1751 by the Hunt family, the house has a secret staircase where, according to legend, the Hunt's eldest daughter Lucy would rendezvous with her lover, [[John Burgoyne|General Burgoyne]]. The two were ultimately driven apart, and in the 1880s it was believed the ghost of a heartbroken Burgoyne haunted the staircase. Since Sessions House became part of college housing in the 20th century, the specter has taken on a decidedly feminine identity, and some former residents of Sessions claim to have seen Lucy's ghost in the stairwell.\n\n====Clubs, sports, and organizations====\nIn addition to the 11 varsity sports, there are currently more than 200 clubs and organizations that cater to Smith students\u2019 variety of interests. There are options that can be found based on academic, political, cultural, and athletic interests. If a student doesn't find an organization that fits their specific interest or need, they can create their own.\n\n=====Athletics=====\nSmith's athletic teams have been known as the Pioneers since 1986. The name expresses the spirit of Smith's students and the college's leadership role in women's athletics (the first women's basketball game was played at Smith in 1893).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smith.edu/video/smith-first-new-game-basketball|title=A Smith First: The New Game of Basketball|website=Smith College|language=en|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807101716/https://www.smith.edu/video/smith-first-new-game-basketball|archive-date=2019-08-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/smith-college-basketball-team-1904/|title=Flashback Photo: Smith College Basketball Team, 1904|date=2014-03-24|website=New England Historical Society|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708054411/http://www.newenglandhistoricalsociety.com/smith-college-basketball-team-1904/|archive-date=2019-07-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA new spirit mark was unveiled to the Smith community in December 2008. The new visual identity for Smith's sports teams marks the culmination of a yearlong project to promote visibility and enthusiasm for Smith's intercollegiate and club teams\u2014and to generate school spirit broadly. The spirit mark is used for athletics uniforms, casual apparel and promotional items for clubs and organizations. As Smith was the first women's college to join the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]], the new mark is seen as linking the college's pioneering alumnae athletes to their equally determined and competitive counterparts today.\n\nSmith College does not have college colors in the usual sense. Its official color is white, trimmed with gold, but the official college logo is blue and yellow (a previous logo was burgundy and white). NCAA athletic teams have competed in blue and white (or blue and yellow, in the case of the soccer, crew, swimming, and squash teams) uniforms since the 1970s, and selected Pioneers as the official name and mascot in 1986. Popular club sports are free to choose their own colors and mascot; both Rugby and Fencing have chosen red and black.\n\nSmith has a rotating system of class colors dating back to the 1880s, when intramural athletics and other campus competitions were usually held by class. Today, class colors are yellow, red, blue and green, with incoming first-year classes assigned the color of the previous year's graduating class; their color then \"follows\" them through to graduation. Alumnae classes, particularly at reunion, continue to identify with and use their class color thereafter.\n\n=====Cultural organizations=====\nThere are 11 chartered cultural organizations that fall under the UNITY title: the Asian Students\u2019 Association (ASA), Black Students\u2019 Alliance (BSA), Chinese Interregional Student Cultural Org (CISCO), South Asian Student Association of Smith (EKTA), Indigenous Smith Students and Allies (ISSA), International Students\u2019 Organization (ISO), Korean Students\u2019 Association (KSA), the Latin American Students\u2019 Organization (LASO), Multiethnic Interracial Smith College (MISC), Smith African and Caribbean Students\u2019 Association (SACSA), and the Vietnamese Students\u2019 Association (VSA). Smith College Website Multicultural Affairs The Black Students\u2019 Alliance is the oldest of all Unity organizations. In Fall 2012, as an effort to document the history of students of color on Smith campus, the Weaving Voices Archives Project was created.\n\n===Academic year events===\n'''[[Convocation]]''' signals the start of the fall semester. For new students it is the first chance to experience Smith College's tradition and spirit. Likewise, for some returning students, the annual event is like a big, welcome-home party as well as an occasion for celebration and an opportunity for creative attire. House communities develop imaginative themes for group fashion, and Smith seniors put special touches on favorite hats to create their own unique \"senior hats,\" to be worn for the first time at Convocation.\n\n'''[[Mountain Day]]''' is observed early in the fall semester. The President of the College selects a crisp, sunny, beautiful autumn day when the leaves are in full color, and announces the cancellation of classes by having bells rung on campus at 7:15 AM on the chosen day. The eager anticipation of Mountain Day leads to intense speculation meteorology by students in the weeks leading up to the surprise announcement. Traditional observance of Mountain Day by students might involve [[New England]] road trips or outdoor pursuits, and college dining services provides box lunches to be taken off-campus. Many of the Houses go apple picking together.\n\n'''[[Otelia Cromwell]] Day''', named for Smith's first African-American student, began in 1989 to provide students with an in-depth program specifically addressing issues of racism and diversity. Afternoon classes are cancelled, and students are invited to participate in lectures, workshops, symposia and cultural events focused on a different theme each year.\n\n'''Rally Day''' In February 1876, the College began an annual observance of [[George Washington]]'s birthday. In 1894, a rally became part of the day's events, and the focus of the celebration became primarily patriotic rather than exclusively social\u2014though always with a women's college twist. Students that year staged a mock debate on the subject, \"Does Higher Education Unfit a Man for Domestic Life?\" In 1906 the celebration was first referred to as '''Rally Day''' (although the name was not used officially by the College until 1992). In 1944, seniors made Rally Day the first public wearing of their graduation caps and gowns; since then, mortarboards have been replaced by wacky, often homemade hats. Today, the Rally Day Convocation is centered on a historical theme, and features a distinguished keynote speaker and the awarding of Smith College Medals to accomplished alumnae.\n\n===Reunions and Commencement events===\nThe Alumnae Association of Smith College hosts official class reunions every five years. All alumnae from all classes are welcome to return in any year; \"off-year\" alumnae attend campus-wide events as the \"Class of 1776.\"\n\nTraditional reunion and [[Graduation|Commencement]] events are linked, and celebrate the close ties between Smith's alumnae and its graduating seniors and their families. At the conclusion of final exams, most underclasswomen leave the campus, while seniors remain in their houses for a week to celebrate and prepare for Commencement. Alumnae arrive for reunions later in the week, and many alumnae arrange for official accommodations in the campus houses, right alongside senior residents.\n\n[[File:Smith College - Ivy Day Seniors.jpg|thumb|220px|Ivy Day]]\n\n'''[[Ivy stone|Ivy Day]]''', the day before Commencement, is the high point of reunion and a significant event for seniors as well. Junior ushers lead a parade through campus, carrying vines of ivy to be planted by the departing seniors as a symbol of their lifelong connection to the college. Alumnae (and, often, their children), dressed in white and wearing sashes in their class color, line up in reverse order by class along both sides of the route. Seniors line up nearest the end of the parade route, wearing traditional white outfits and each carrying a single red rose. All cheer each alumnae class as it marches past, then fall in to join the end of the parade. Many alumnae classes carry signs with humorous poems or slogans, or hold balloons or wear hats in their class color. Ivy Day festivities conclude in the Quad, where the seniors plant their ivy and speakers address alumnae on the progress of fundraising and the state of the college.\n\n'''Illumination Night''', beginning at dusk on the Saturday evening before Commencement, is a celebration of the campus and a send-off of sorts for graduating seniors. Throughout central campus, electric street lights are replaced for one night by multicolored Japanese-style paper lanterns, lit with real candles. These hang on both sides of every walking path and cast a soft glow over the buildings and lawns. Student a cappella singing groups and improv comedy troupes roam the campus, stopping occasionally to entertain the crowds. A jazz band, hired by the college, turns the science buildings' courtyard into a dance floor. Seniors, alumnae, faculty and their families spend the evening on walking tours of the illuminated campus and [[The Botanic Garden of Smith College|Botanic Gardens]]. The major official event of the night is the '''Senior Step Sing''': seniors gather on the steps of Neilson Library, where they are serenaded by members of the '''Sophomore Push''' committee, then are physically pushed off the stairs and \"into the real world.\"\n\nUntil the early 1990s, all alumnae reunions were held during Commencement weekend. However, as the number of returning alumnae grew beyond the capacity of the campus, reunions were split into Reunion I/Commencement Weekend and Reunion II, held the following weekend. \"Significant\" reunions (50-, 25- and 10- year, but also 2-year) and the earliest reunion classes (65-year and prior) are assigned to Reunion I; other reunions (5-, 15-, 20-, 30-year, and so on) are assigned to Reunion II.\n\nThere have been several controversies surrounding commencement over the years. See [[Smith College commencement controversies]] to learn more.\n\n==Environmental sustainability==\n[[File:Paradise Pond.jpg|thumb|Paradise Pond with portion of athletic fields visible (center left)]]\n\nSmith has taken numerous steps toward environmental sustainability, including a 30% reduction in energy use. Also, through a contract with Zipcar, the college has reduced the need for individually owned cars on campus. Complementing this effort, the college has also promoted sustainability through academics and through the arts.<ref name=\"smith.edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.smith.edu/green/news.php |title=Smith College: Green Smith |publisher=Smith.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930235407/http://www.smith.edu/green/news.php |archive-date=2010-09-30 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn keeping with its sustainability efforts, all Smith dining locations have discontinued the use of \"to-go\" supplies which included paper cups and plates, as well as plastic utensils. They now encourage students to bring their own, reusable containers and utensils if they wish to bring food back to their rooms. Smith College provides all students with a reusable drink container at the beginning of each academic year. In past years, these containers have been variations on travel mugs, Sigg bottles, and nalgenes. Those dining halls that still offer \"To-Go\" options no longer provide paper bags, and instead use wax paper bags, [[biodegradable plastic]], and recyclable utensils made of vegetable cellulose. In the fall of 2017, Smith dining halls began to offer plastic tupperware containers students may borrow and return to the dining halls to be washed.\n\nFor Smith's efforts regarding sustainability, the institution earned a grade of \"A-\" on the \"College Sustainability Report Card 2010\" administered by the Sustainable Endowments Institute. Smith was lauded for many of the indicator categories, including student involvement, green building, and transportation, but was marked down for endowment transparency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/schools/smith-college |title=Smith College \u2013 Green Report Card 2010 |publisher=Greenreportcard.org |date=2008-06-30 |accessdate=2010-09-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620201946/http://greenreportcard.org/report-card-2010/schools/smith-college |archive-date=2010-06-20 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumnae==\n<!--Please see Talk page discussion of notability criteria------------------------------------>\n<!--and the possibility of moving this section in its entirety to [[List of Smith College people]] or other page-->\n{{Main|List of Smith College people}}\n\nAmong the more notable of Smith College's alumnae in chronological order are:\n\n{{div col|colwidth=40em}}\n* [[Otelia Cromwell]] (class of 1900): first African-American graduate of Smith college and the first African American woman to receive a doctorate from Yale\n* [[Eunice Carter]] (class of 1921): first female African-American assistant district attorney for the state of New York, active in the prosecution of mob boss Charles \"Lucky\" Luciano\n* [[Margaret Mitchell]] (class of 1922): author of ''[[Gone with the Wind (novel)|Gone with the Wind]]'', did not graduate from Smith\n* [[Julia Child]] (class of 1934): chef, author and television personality <ref name=\":0\" />\n* [[Madeleine L'Engle]] (class of 1941): author\n* [[Betty Friedan]] (class of 1942): feminist and author of ''[[The Feminine Mystique]]''\n* [[Nancy Reagan]] (class of 1943): [[First Lady of the United States]] from 1981 to 1989\n* [[Penny Chenery]] (class of 1943): sportswoman, racehorse breeder and owner, horse racing advocate\n* [[Jean Harris]] (class of 1945): headmistress of the [[Madeira School]] who murdered her ex-lover [[Herman Tarnower]] in a jealous rage\n* [[Rhoda Dorsey]] (class of 1946): historian and first woman president of [[Goucher College]]\n* [[Barbara Bush]] (class of 1947): former [[First Lady of the United States]], did not graduate from Smith\n* [[Natalie Babbitt]] (class of 1954): notable illustrator and author of ''[[Tuck Everlasting]]''\n* [[Sylvia Plath]] (class of 1955): poet, novelist and short story author\n* [[Gloria Steinem]] (class of 1956): founder of ''[[Ms.]]'' magazine and noted feminist, activist, and journalist\n* [[Lynden B. Miller]] (class of 1960): public garden designer, park advocate and author\n* [[Jane Yolen]] (class of 1960): children's book author\n* [[Ng'endo Mwangi|Ng'endo (Florence) Mwangi]] (class of 1961): Kenya's first woman physician\n* [[Jane Harman]] (class of 1966): U.S. Representative for California's 36th Congressional District\n* [[Molly Ivins]] (class of 1966): journalist, political commentator, and humorist\n* [[Rochelle Lazarus|Shelly Lazarus]] (class of 1968): former CEO and Chairman of [[Ogilvy & Mather]]\n* [[Nikki Tsongas]] (class of 1968): U.S. Representative for Massachusetts' 3rd Congressional District\n* [[Catharine MacKinnon]] (class of 1968): notable proponent of [[radical feminism]], scholar, lawyer, teacher and activist\n* [[Laura D'Andrea Tyson]] (class of 1969): economist; Director of the [[National Economic Council (United States)|National Economic Council]]\n* [[Yolanda King]] (class of 1976): activist\n* [[Christine McCarthy]] (class of 1977): Chief Financial Officer of [[The Walt Disney Company]]\n* [[Ann M. Martin]] (class of 1978): author of ''[[The Babysitter's Club]]''\n* [[Phebe Novakovic]] (class of 1979): Chairman and CEO of [[General Dynamics]]\n* [[Ruth Ozeki]] (class of 1980): author of ''[[A Tale for the Time Being]]''\n* [[Margaret Edson]] (class of 1983): winner of a [[Pulitzer Prize]] for Drama\n* [[Tammy Baldwin]] (class of 1984): United States Senator\n* [[Tori Murden]] (class of 1985): the first woman to row solo across the Atlantic Ocean, and to ski to the geographic South Pole\n* [[Thelma Golden]] (class of 1987): Director and Chief Curator of [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]]\n* [[Durreen Shahnaz]] (class of 1989): founder of Impact Investment Exchange (IIX)\n* [[Piper Kerman]] (class of 1992): ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'' author, lived in Chapin House\n* [[Hanya Yanagihara]] (Class of 1995): author and editor\n* [[Luma Mufleh]] (class of 1997): founder and director of Fugees Family, Inc., a non-profit organization devoted to working with child survivors of war\n* [[Cass Bird]] (class of 1999): fashion photographer\n* [[Erin Morgenstern]] (class of 2000): ''[[The Night Circus]]'' author\n* [[Sara Haines]] (class of 2000): co-host of ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'', [[ABC News]] correspondent\n* [[Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy]] (class of 2002): documentarian, winner of two [[Academy Awards]]\n* [[Julia Scott]] (class of 2002): [[NPR]] and ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' journalist\n* [[Kimberly Drew]] (class of 2012): art curator and cultural critic\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable staff==\n* [[Herbert Baxter Adams]] (1850\u20131901), educator, historian, and cofounder of the [[American Historical Association]] taught history at Smith from 1878 to 1881.<ref>\u201cProfessor Herbert Baxter Adams\u201d by B. J. Ramage in\nThe American Historical Magazine\nVol. 6, No. 4 (OCTOBER, 1901), pp. 363\u2013366</ref>\n* [[Louise Holland]] (1893\u20131990), academic, philologist and archaeologist, taught here from 1957 to 1964\n* In 1960, three Smith professors, one who had been there for 38 years, were fired or \"allowed to retire\" for being [[Homosexual|gay]]. This was chronicled in a book (''The Scarlet Professor\u2014[[Newton Arvin]]: A Literary Life Shattered by Scandal'' (Doubleday, 2001), by Barry Werth), and the PBS Independent Lens film, ''The Great Pink Scare''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/greatpinkscare/film.html|title=The Great Pink Scare|publisher=Independent Television Service (ITVS)|access-date=2017-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107013855/https://www.pbs.org/independentlens/greatpinkscare/film.html|archive-date=2017-11-07|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2002, Smith, the nation's largest liberal arts college for women, acknowledged a wrong from four decades earlier by creating a lecture series and a small scholarship\u2014the $100,000 Dorius/Spofford Fund for the Study of Civil Liberties and Freedom of Expression, and the Newton Arvin Prize in American Studies, a $500 annual stipend. But despite faculty appeals, there was no apology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/20/obituaries/20dorius.html|title=Joel Dorius, 87, Victim in Celebrated Anti-Gay Case, Dies|date=20 February 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=23 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929045016/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/20/obituaries/20dorius.html|archive-date=29 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Artist [[Leonard Baskin]] taught at Smith from 1953 to 1974.\n* During the 2000\u20132001 school year, noted author and satirist [[Kurt Vonnegut]] served as Writer-in-Residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/00-019.html|title=Acclaimed Satirist and Best-Selling Novelist to Give Public \"Performance\" at Smith|publisher=Smith College|access-date=2013-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904084948/http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/00-019.html|archive-date=2012-09-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Emily Hale]], speech and drama teacher, and muse of [[T.S. Eliot]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cambridge School of Architecture and Landscape Architecture]]\n* [[College Archives (Smith College)]]\n* [[Tofu Curtain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [[Helen Lefkowitz Horowitz|Horowitz, Helen Lefkowitz]]. [https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0870238698&id=Z3qWLyDZ8PsC&pg=PP1 ''Alma Mater: Design and Experience in the Women's Colleges from Their Nineteenth-Century Beginnings to the 1930s''], Amherst: [[University of Massachusetts Press]], 1993 (2nd edition).\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Smith College}}\n{{Wikisource|Portal:Smith College|Smith College}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.smith.edu/}}\n* [http://www.smithpioneers.com Official athletics website]\n* [http://www.thesmithsophian.com/ ''The Sophian''], Smith's student newspaper\n\n{{Smith College}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{CLAC}}\n{{Five Colleges}}\n{{Seven Sisters}}\n{{New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Current women's universities and colleges in the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Smith College| ]]\n[[Category:1871 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Northampton, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1871]]\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Seven Sister Colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Hampshire County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Women's universities and colleges in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResidential culture and student life:Fixed cite errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smith_College"}
{"title_page": "Jim Arnold (politician)", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Senator \n| name=Jim Arnold\n| image name=\n| state_senate=Indiana\n| state=Indiana\n| district=8th\n| term_start=March 25, 2007\n| term_end=November 9, 2016\n| preceded=Anita Olga Albu Bowser<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/|title=Offices|date=2015-03-03|website=Capitol & Washington|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n| succeeded=Mike Bohacek\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|1950|12|2}} \n| birth_place=[[Michigan City, Indiana]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Valparaiso University]], [[Indiana University]]\n| profession=[[sheriff]]\n| spouse=Lauren Arnold\n| residence=[[LaPorte, Indiana]]\n| religion=\n|}}\n\n'''Jim Arnold''' is a former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Indiana Senate]], representing the 8th District since his appointment in March 2007. \n\n== Early Life ==\nArnold grew up in Michigan City and graduated from Elston High School in 1962.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldargus.com/news/jim-arnold-finds-new-way-to-serve/article_dbe560d0-2cfe-53f2-b305-b3bf70217d4c.html|title=Jim Arnold finds new way to serve|last=Herrold|first=PHIL|date=30 December 2018|website=Herald Argus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He attended Western Michigan University for one semester before joining the Air Force.<ref name=\":0\" /> He later completed a bachelor's degree in political science at [[Valparaiso University]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nArnold worked in law enforcement for 32 years, four years in the La Porte County Prosecutor's Office, and eight as LaPort County Sheriff.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2007, Arnold retired as LaPorte County Sheriff.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfyi.org/news/articles/sen-jim-arnold-will-not-seek-re-election-next-year|title=Sen. Jim Arnold Will Not Seek Re-Election Next Year|date=2016-01-13|website=WFYI Public Media|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> In March 2007, he began representing District 8 in the state legislature.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2012, Arnold was named Legislator of the Year by the Disabled American Veterans.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn January 2016, Arnold announced that he would not't seek re-election.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn November 2018, Arnold was nominated to Indiana's Motor Vehicles Sales Advisory Board and was sworn in on December 13, 2018.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.in.gov/legislative/senate_democrats/homepages/s8/ State Senator Jim Arnold] ''official Indiana State Legislature site''\n<!-- *[] ''official campaign website'' -->\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=70834 | fec= | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=9049 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* -->\n{{Indiana State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Jim}}\n[[Category:Indiana state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Valparaiso University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n\n\n{{Indiana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Senator \n| name=Jim Arnold\n| image name=\n| state_senate=Indiana\n| state=Indiana\n| district=8th\n| term_start=March 25, 2007\n| term_end=November 9, 2016\n| preceded=Anita Olga Albu Bowser<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/|title=Offices|date=2015-03-03|website=Capitol & Washington|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n| succeeded=Mike Bohacek\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|1950|12|2}} \n| birth_place=[[Michigan City, Indiana]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Valparaiso University]], [[Indiana University]]\n| profession=[[sheriff]]\n| spouse=Lauren Arnold\n| residence=[[LaPorte, Indiana]]\n| religion=\n|}}\n\n'''Jim Arnold''' is a former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Indiana Senate]], representing the 8th District since his appointment in March 2007. \n\n== Early Life ==\nArnold grew up in Michigan City and graduated from Elston High School in 1962.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldargus.com/news/jim-arnold-finds-new-way-to-serve/article_dbe560d0-2cfe-53f2-b305-b3bf70217d4c.html|title=Jim Arnold finds new way to serve|last=Herrold|first=PHIL|date=30 December 2018|website=Herald Argus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> He attended Western Michigan University for one semester before joining the Air Force.<ref name=\":0\" /> He later completed a bachelor's degree in political science at [[Valparaiso University]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nArnold worked in law enforcement for 32 years, four years in the La Porte County Prosecutor's Office, and eight as LaPort County Sheriff.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn January 2007, Arnold retired as LaPorte County Sheriff.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wfyi.org/news/articles/sen-jim-arnold-will-not-seek-re-election-next-year|title=Sen. Jim Arnold Will Not Seek Re-Election Next Year|date=2016-01-13|website=WFYI Public Media|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> In March 2007 he began representing District 8 in the state legislature.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2012, Arnold was named Legislator of the Year by the Disabled American Veterans.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn January 2016, Arnold announced that he wouldn't seek re-election.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nIn November 2018, Arnold was nominated to Indiana's Motor Vehicles Sales Advisory Board and was sworn in on December 13, 2018.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.in.gov/legislative/senate_democrats/homepages/s8/ State Senator Jim Arnold] ''official Indiana State Legislature site''\n<!-- *[] ''official campaign website'' -->\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=70834 | fec= | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=9049 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* -->\n{{Indiana State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Jim}}\n[[Category:Indiana state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Valparaiso University alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n\n\n{{Indiana-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hiabc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Arnold_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "The Amazing Adventures of Morph", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Amazing Adventures of Morph\n| genre                    = [[Animation]]<br>[[Family]]<br>[[Comedy]]<br>[[Science fiction]]\n| creator                  = [[Aardman Animations]]<br>[[Peter Lord]]<br>[[David Sproxton]]\n| director                 = [[Peter Lord]]<br>[[David Sproxton]]\n| screenplay               = [[Peter Lord]]<br>[[David Sproxton]]\n| narrated                 = [[Tony Hart]]\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_episodes             = 26\n| executive_producer       = [[Peter Lord]]<br>[[David Sproxton]]<br>[[Nick Park]]<br>[[Tony Hart]]\n| producer                 = [[Patrick Dowling (producer)|Patrick Dowling]]\n| runtime                  = 5 minutes\n| company                  = [[Aardman Animations]]<br>Tony Hart Productions, Inc.\n| distributor              = [[BBC]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1980|10|13}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|1981|05|18}}\n| followed_by              = [[The Morph Files]] (1995)\n| related                  = spun off from [[Take Hart]] (1977)\n| website                  = \n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n| channel                  = BBC\n}}\n\n'''''The Amazing Adventures of Morph''''' is a British [[stop motion|stop-motion]] [[clay animation]] television show created by [[Aardman Animations]] which ran from 1980 to 1981. It featured the character [[Morph (franchise)|Morph]] and his cream-coloured best friend [[Morph (franchise)|Chas]].\n\n==Production==\nThe character of Morph first appeared on the children's art-themed TV show [[Take Hart]] with Tony Hart in 1977. This series served as a spin-off to Take Hart and a showcase for Morph.<ref name=\"msn\">{{cite web |url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/features/knightmare-itv-cult-kids-classic-to-be-shown-on-youtube?page=4 |title=1980s kids faves: The Amazing Adventures of Morph - Knightmare: ITV cult kids classic to be shown on YouTube |accessdate=2014-01-14 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116075851/http://tv.uk.msn.com/features/knightmare-itv-cult-kids-classic-to-be-shown-on-youtube?page=4 |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> The character had become so popular that the [[BBC]] commissioned 26 5-min episodes featuring the character.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Who's who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-winning and Legendary Animators|author=Lenburg, J.|year=2006|publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema Books|isbn=9781617746604|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVShFCjVzvIC|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nAs well Morph and his cream-coloured best friend Chas from previous appearances,  the show incorporated various additional characters; Folly (a female tinfoil figure), Gillespie (large, blue and dim-witted), GrandMorph (an elderly grey-bearded version of Morph with a skateboard and a knack for inventing things), Delilah (a blonde female in a yellow dress and glasses who serves as a [[Straight man|straight]] character) Nailbrush (a nailbrush dog), Gobbledygook (a green alien) and The Very Small Creatures. Early versions of Folly and Gillespie had previously made a brief appearance in Take Hart.<ref>https://amazingmorph.com/history/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Tony Hart]] as Narrator (voice)\n\n*[[Morph (animation)|Morph]] as himself\n\n==Episodes==\n# How It All Began\n# The Day Nothing Happened\n# Morph Plays Golf\n# Morph's Birthday Party\n# The Day Morph Was Ill\n# Morph's Forgotten Dream\n# Morph the Weakling\n# The Dog Show\n# The Two Mountaineers\n# The Double Decker Boot\n# The Cowboys\n# The Day Morph Went Skiing\n# The Abominable Snowman\n# The Invisible Morph\n# Anyone for Cricket?\n# A Swimming Pool in the Garden\n# The Strange Visitor\n# A Game of Chess\n# The Very Small Creature, Green\n# GrandMorph's Beard\n# The Babysitters\n# Morph Sticks With It\n# Gobbledygook the Burglar\n# GrandMorph's Home Movies\n# Morph and the Swoggle Flange\n# The Magic Wand\n\n==Online re-release==\n\nFrom 20 March to 2 October, 2015, [[High-definition television|HD]] restored versions of all 26 episodes of the series had appeared on [[YouTube]].\n==Critical reception==\n''[[MSN|MSN UK]]'' said \"It would be fantastic to see this show back on terrestrial TV - it was entertaining and original.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1981\n| Patrick Dowling\n| [[BAFTA TV Award]] for 'Harlequin' (Drama/Light Entertainment)\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"imdb2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0435939/awards|title=The Amazing Adventures of Morph - Awards - IMDb|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|0435939}}\n\n{{Aardman Animations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amazing Adventures of Morph}}\n[[Category:1980s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:1980 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1981 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:British animated television programmes featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:British children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Clay animation television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Aardman Animations]]\n[[Category:British television series with live action and animation]]\n\n{{UK-tv-prog-stub}}\n{{animation-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Amazing Adventures of Morph\n| genre                    = [[Animation]]<br>[[Family]]<br>[[Comedy]]<br>[[Science fiction]]\n| creator                  = Aardman Animations\n| director                 = [[Peter Lord]]<br>[[David Sproxton]]\n| narrated                 = [[Tony Hart]]\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English\n| num_episodes             = 26\n| producer                 = [[Patrick Dowling (producer)|Patrick Dowling]]\n| runtime                  = 5 minutes\n| company                  = [[Aardman Animations]]\n| distributor              = [[BBC]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1980|10|13}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|1981|05|18}}\n| followed_by              = [[The Morph Files]] (1995)\n| related                  = spun off from [[Take Hart]] (1977)\n| website                  = \n| website_title            = \n| production_website       = \n| production_website_title = \n| channel                  = BBC\n}}\n\n'''''The Amazing Adventures of Morph''''' is a British [[stop motion|stop-motion]] [[clay animation]] television show created by [[Aardman Animations]] which ran from 1980 to 1981. It featured the character [[Morph (franchise)|Morph]] and his cream-coloured best friend [[Morph (franchise)|Chas]].\n\n==Production==\nThe character of Morph first appeared on the children's art-themed TV show [[Take Hart]] with Tony Hart in 1977. This series served as a spin-off to Take Hart and a showcase for Morph.<ref name=\"msn\">{{cite web |url=http://tv.uk.msn.com/features/knightmare-itv-cult-kids-classic-to-be-shown-on-youtube?page=4 |title=1980s kids faves: The Amazing Adventures of Morph - Knightmare: ITV cult kids classic to be shown on YouTube |accessdate=2014-01-14 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116075851/http://tv.uk.msn.com/features/knightmare-itv-cult-kids-classic-to-be-shown-on-youtube?page=4 |archivedate=16 January 2014 }}</ref> The character had become so popular that the [[BBC]] commissioned 26 5-min episodes featuring the character.<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Who's who in Animated Cartoons: An International Guide to Film & Television's Award-winning and Legendary Animators|author=Lenburg, J.|year=2006|publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema Books|isbn=9781617746604|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVShFCjVzvIC|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nAs well Morph and his cream-coloured best friend Chas from previous appearances,  the show incorporated various additional characters; Folly (a female tinfoil figure), Gillespie (large, blue and dim-witted), GrandMorph (an elderly grey-bearded version of Morph with a skateboard and a knack for inventing things), Delilah (a blonde female in a yellow dress and glasses who serves as a [[Straight man|straight]] character) Nailbrush (a nailbrush dog), Gobbledygook (a green alien) and The Very Small Creatures. Early versions of Folly and Gillespie had previously made a brief appearance in Take Hart.<ref>https://amazingmorph.com/history/</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Tony Hart]] as Narrator (voice)\n\n*[[Morph (animation)|Morph]] as himself\n\n==Episodes==\n# How It All Began\n# The Day Nothing Happened\n# Morph Plays Golf\n# Morph's Birthday Party\n# The Day Morph Was Ill\n# Morph's Forgotten Dream\n# Morph the Weakling\n# The Dog Show\n# The Two Mountaineers\n# The Double Decker Boot\n# The Cowboys\n# The Day Morph Went Skiing\n# The Abominable Snowman\n# The Invisible Morph\n# Anyone for Cricket?\n# A Swimming Pool in the Garden\n# The Strange Visitor\n# A Game of Chess\n# The Very Small Creature, Green\n# GrandMorph's Beard\n# The Babysitters\n# Morph Sticks With It\n# Gobbledygook the Burglar\n# GrandMorph's Home Movies\n# Morph and the Swoggle Flange\n# The Magic Wand\n\n==Online re-release==\n\nFrom 20 March to 2 October, 2015, [[High-definition television|HD]] restored versions of all 26 episodes of the series had appeared on [[YouTube]].\n==Critical reception==\n''[[MSN|MSN UK]]'' said \"It would be fantastic to see this show back on terrestrial TV - it was entertaining and original.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1981\n| Patrick Dowling\n| [[BAFTA TV Award]] for 'Harlequin' (Drama/Light Entertainment)\n| {{nom}}<ref name=\"imdb2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0435939/awards|title=The Amazing Adventures of Morph - Awards - IMDb|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb title|0435939}}\n\n{{Aardman Animations}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amazing Adventures of Morph}}\n[[Category:1980s British animated television series]]\n[[Category:1980s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:1980 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1981 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:British animated television programmes featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:British children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:British children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:Clay animation television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series by Aardman Animations]]\n[[Category:British television series with live action and animation]]\n\n{{UK-tv-prog-stub}}\n{{animation-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2804:214:8288:84c1:1:2:c4e7:41f2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Wow)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Amazing_Adventures_of_Morph"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Massachusetts, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts\n| location        = [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| first_case      = [[Boston]]\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| arrival_date    = February 1, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=1|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| confirmed_cases = 28,163<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\">{{cite web | title = COVID-19 Cases, Quarantine and Monitoring | url = https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-cases-quarantine-and-monitoring | website = Massachusetts Department of Public Health | access-date = April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  = 5,402<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-cases-quarantine-and-monitoring|title=COVID-19 Cases, Quarantine, and Monitoring|access-date = April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 957 as of April 13, 2020\n| website         = https://mass.gov/covid-19\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts''' is part of an [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|ongoing pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the US state of [[Massachusetts]]. The first confirmed case was reported on February 1, 2020, and the number of cases began increasing rapidly on March 5. [[Governor of Massachusetts|Governor]] [[Charlie Baker]] declared a state of emergency on March 10. By March 12, over 100 people had tested positive for the virus. Most early cases were traceable to a company meeting held in [[Boston]] in late February by the [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]]-based biotechnology firm [[Biogen]]. {{As of|2020|04|14|df=US}}, Massachusetts had 28,163 cases and 957 deaths due to COVID-19. Massachusetts was also 3rd in the US for overall number of cases statewide.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Massachusetts medical cases chart}}\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== February ===\n[[File:Marriott Long Wharf hotel; west and south sides; Boston, MA; 2020-03-14.jpg|thumb|right|Marriott Long Wharf hotel in Boston, the site of the [[Biogen]] company meeting to which most early COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts were traced]]\n\nThe first case of COVID-19 was confirmed by state health officials on February 1. Massachusetts became the third state in America to report a case of COVID-19. The individual, a [[University of Massachusetts Boston]] student, had returned to Boston from [[Wuhan]], China. Upon returning to Boston he began experiencing symptoms and sought medical care. University of Massachusetts Boston Interim Chancellor [[Katherine Newman]] addressed the situation in a campus-wide email, assuring students and faculty that they were at low risk.<ref name=\"Wertheim\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/04/08/boston-braces-for-the-surge|title=Boston Braces For 'The Surge'|last=Adam|first=Reilly|date=April 8, 2020|website=[[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n175 executives of Biogen, a biotechnology company based in Cambridge, held a two-day leadership conference from February 26\u201328 at the Boston Marriott Long Wharf hotel.<ref name=\"Arsenault\">{{Cite news | last = Arsenault | first = Mark | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/11/nation/how-biogen-leadership-conference-boston-spread-coronavirus/ | title = How the Biogen leadership conference in Boston spread the coronavirus | date = March 10, 2020 | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Rosen | first2 = Andy | last3 = Krueger | first3 = Hanna | last4 = Lazar | first4 = Kay | last5 = Saltzman | first5 = Jonathan | last6 = Kowalczyk | first6 = Liz}}</ref> On February 29, a [[Biogen]] executive began to develop symptoms and sought treatment at a Boston area hospital. Suspecting COVID-19 was the cause of the illness, the executive requested a test, but was told by hospital staff that it was not necessary.<ref name=\"Arsenault\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/coronavirus-outbreak-biogen-conference-superspreading | title = Single Conference Linked To Most Mass. Coronavirus Cases Looks Like A 'Superspreading Event' | date= March 12, 2020 | first= Carey | last = Goldberg |website = [[WBUR-FM]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/boston-biogen-meeting-coronavirus-warning/2089438/ |date= March 11, 2020 | first= Philip |last= Marcelo |first2=Matt |last2=O'Brien| publisher = NBC Boston | title = Biogen Meeting Tied to Coronavirus Cases Serves as Warning}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n\n==== March 2\u20133 ====\nOn March 2, the second confirmed case in Massachusetts was reported. The patient was a woman in her 20s from [[Norfolk County, Massachusetts|Norfolk County]]. She had recently traveled to Italy with a school group from [[Saint Raphael Academy]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], [[Rhode Island]].  She was the third person from the trip to test positive.<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" />\n\n==== March 4\u20135 ====\nOn March 4, staff from Biogen contacted the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] (MDPH) to report that two executives who had recently traveled from Europe to Boston and had attended the February employee meeting had tested positive for [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] upon returning home. The same day, a \"significant number\" of Biogen employees asked to be tested for the virus at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] (MGH), which had not been informed that anyone at the company had been exposed. The state police announced Shattuck Street would be closed because a group of 60 individuals were being transported along the route to [[Brigham and Women's Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cotter | first = Sean Philip | url = https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/03/06/bio-hazard-60-head-to-hospital-for-coronavirus-testing-in-boston/ | title = Coronavirus in Boston: 60 head to Brigham and Women's Hospital for testing | date = March 9, 2020 | work = [[Boston Herald]] | access-date = March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, Biogen reported that three individuals who had attended a company event in Boston the previous week had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Fortier | first = Marc | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/3-who-attended-biogen-meeting-in-boston-test-positive-for-coronavirus/2086462/ | title = 3 Who Attended Biogen Meeting in Boston Test Positive for Coronavirus | date = March 6, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Rosenfield | first2 = Marc}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/3-who-attended-biogen-meeting-in-boston-test-positive-for-coronavirus/2086462/ | title = 3 Who Attended Biogen Meeting in Boston Test Positive for Coronavirus | last = Fortier | first = Marc | date = March 5, 2020 | website = [[WBTS-CD|WBTS]] | access-date = March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 6\u20139 ====\nOn March 6, public health officials reported five new cases bringing the state total to eight.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" /><ref>{{Cite news | last = Fortier | first = Marc | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-coronavirus-cases-linked-to-biogens-boston-meeting/2086974/ | title = Coronavirus Cases Linked to Biogen Boston Meeting: What We Know | date = March 11, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Four cases were in [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], three in [[Norfolk County, Massachusetts|Norfolk County]], and one in [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]]. Two cases were associated with travel to Italy and one to Wuhan. All five new cases were associated with the Biogen meeting.<ref name=\"Boston-25\">{{Cite news | url = https://www.boston25news.com/more/blog-latest-coronavirus-cases-news-massachusetts/XZXJA7P3J5ENZFXLRG2YUFWTSI/ | title = Boston closes Eliot School as number of COVID-19 cases in Mass. rise | work = Boston 25 News | access-date = March 13, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308003947/https://www.boston25news.com/more/blog-latest-coronavirus-cases-news-massachusetts/XZXJA7P3J5ENZFXLRG2YUFWTSI/ | archive-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/workers-who-attended-boston-biogen-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus/31252079 | title = Workers who attended Boston Biogen meeting test positive for coronavirus | date = March 6, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 11, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200307124523/https://www.wcvb.com/article/workers-who-attended-boston-biogen-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus/31252079 | archive-date = March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Sheridan\">{{Cite news | last = Sheridan | first = Kate | url = https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/06/biogen-workers-test-positive-for-coronavirus-transmission-linked-to-leadership-meeting/ | title = Top Biogen execs were at meeting where attendees had Covid-19 | date = March 6, 2020 | work = STAT | access-date = March 9, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308154652/https://www.statnews.com/2020/03/06/biogen-workers-test-positive-for-coronavirus-transmission-linked-to-leadership-meeting/ | archive-date = March 8, 2020 | last2 = Feuerstein | first2 = Adam | last3 = Herper | first3 = Matthew}}</ref> [[Northeastern University]], which had already closed satellite campuses in San Francisco and Seattle, hesitated to close their main campus for fear of international students losing their [[F visa]] status, and publicly called on the [[Department of Homeland Security]] to grant clemency for international students so the university could close.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/president-aouns-letter-to-the-u-s-department-of-homeland-security-on-f-1-student-visas/ | title = President Aoun's letter to the U.S. Department of Homeland Security on F-1 student visas | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | date = March 6, 2020 | website = Northeastern University}}</ref> On March 7, five more presumptive positive cases of COVID-19 were reported, bringing the total to 13.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/07/coronavirus-cases-massachusetts-rises-12-presumptive-1-confirmed/ | title = Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts Rise To 12 Presumptive, 1 Confirmed | date = March 7, 2020 | work = CBS Boston | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Among those cases was the [[index case]] in [[Berkshire County]], a man in his 60s from [[Clarksburg, Massachusetts|Clarksburg]] whose infection could not be traced.<ref name=\"WHDH-Berkshire-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://whdh.com/news/berkshire-county-is-now-being-considered-the-big-question-mark-when-it-comes-to-coronavirus-in-massachusetts/ | publisher = WHDH | date= March 11, 2020 | title = Berkshire County is now being considered the big question mark when it comes to coronavirus in Massachusetts}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, the MDPH reported 15 more presumptive cases of COVID-19,<ref name=\"Sheridan\" /> all of which were individuals present at the Biogen conference,<ref name=\"Boston-25\" /> bringing the total to 28.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" /> In response to the outbreak, Biogen ordered all its employees to work from home.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Linnane | first = Ciara | url = https://www.marketwatch.com/story/biogen-orders-employees-to-work-from-home-after-employees-at-boston-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-03-08 | title = Biogen orders employees to work from home after employees at Boston meeting test positive for coronavirus | date = March 9, 2020 | work = MarketWatch | access-date = March 11, 2020 | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200308231025/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/biogen-orders-employees-to-work-from-home-after-employees-at-boston-meeting-test-positive-for-coronavirus-2020-03-08 | archive-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref> The fifteen new presumptive cases included five from Suffolk County, five from Middlesex County, four from Norfolk County, and one whose county of residence was unknown.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-health-officials-announce-15-new-presumptive-coronavirus-cases-all-connected-to-biogen-conference/31274340 | title = Mass. announces 15 new presumptive coronavirus cases; all connected to Biogen conference | date = March 8, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 8, 2020}}</ref> Officials in North Carolina reported that five residents of Wake County tested positive for COVID-19; all five were participants in the previous week's Biogen meeting in Boston.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Brown | first = Joell | url = https://abc11.com/5997924/ | title = 5 Wake County residents test positive for coronavirus after attending Biogen conference connected to 2 dozen cases | date = March 9, 2020 | work = abc11.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) announced that all large lectures would be held online only.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-to-undergraduates/|title=Update to Undergraduate Students|date=March 9, 2020|website=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Fernandes | first = Deidre | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/09/business/mit-says-all-large-classes-will-be-taught-online-amid-coronavirus-fears/ | title = MIT says all large classes will be taught online amid coronavirus fears | date = March 9, 2020 | work = [[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>\n\n==== March 10\u201311 ====\n[[File:Out of stock at CVS on March 10, 2020.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Items out of stock at a [[CVS Pharmacy]] in [[Westford, Massachusetts]]]]\n\nOn March 10, the first evidence of [[community transmission]], also known as community spread, was found in a handful of cases in the [[Berkshires]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Murphy |first1=Matt |last2=Young |first2=Colin A. |title=[UPDATE] With gov's state of emergency declaration, MA adopts new coronavirus strategy |url=https://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20200310/update-with-govs-state-of-emergency-declaration-ma-adopts-new-coronavirus-strategy |accessdate=April 5, 2020 |work=[[South Coast Today]] |agency=State House News Service |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> [[Harvard University]] announced that its classes would be online-only for the rest of the spring semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2020/3/11/harvard-coronavirus-classes-cancelled/ | title = Harvard Moves Classes Online, Asks Students Not to Return After Spring Break in Response to Coronavirus | date = March 11, 2020 | work = [[The Harvard Crimson]] | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Carraggi | first = Mike | url = https://patch.com/massachusetts/boston/harvard-asks-students-not-return-break-amid-virus-fears | title = Harvard, Others Ask Students Not To Return From Break, Go Virtual | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston, MA Patch | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | title = Update from President L. Rafael Reif to the MIT Community | last = Reif | first = L. Rafael | date = March 10, 2020 | website = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | url-status = live | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200311023015/https://web.mit.edu/covid19/update-from-president-l-rafael-reif-to-the-mit-community/ | archive-date = March 11, 2020 | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> The University of Massachusetts Boston informed faculty that they should prepare to teach remotely.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Aliyu | first = Wale | url = https://www.boston25news.com/news/umass-boston-preparing-roll-out-online-classes-coronavirus-concerns-grow/76QRLNDDDRB2VGXAKLFU3OPNCU/ | title = UMass Boston preparing to roll out online classes as coronavirus concerns grow | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Boston 25 News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Amherst College]], located in [[Western Massachusetts]], instructed students on spring break to not return to campus, and moved all classes online for the remainder of the semester.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/coronavirus-prompts-amherst-college-to-move-to-remote-learning-for-rest-of-semester/31307851 | title = Coronavirus prompts Amherst College to move to remote learning for rest of semester | date = March 10, 2020 | work = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Emerson College]], [[Tufts University]], [[Babson College]], [[Smith College]], and [[Wheaton College (Massachusetts)|Wheaton College]] all canceled in-person classes and moved classes online.<ref name=\"Corrado\">{{Cite news | last = Corrado | first = Kerri | url = https://whdh.com/news/which-mass-colleges-are-making-changes-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title = Which Mass. colleges are making changes amid coronavirus outbreak? | date = March 11, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020 | last2 = Connolly | first2 = Brynne}}</ref> A man in [[Sudbury, Massachusetts|Sudbury]] tested presumptive positive for COVID-19,<ref>{{Cite news | last = McNamara | first = Neal | url = https://patch.com/massachusetts/sudbury/sudbury-resident-tests-positive-coronavirus | title = Sudbury Resident Tests Positive For Coronavirus | date = March 10, 2020 | work = Sudbury, MA Patch | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> and the first case in [[Essex County, Massachusetts|Essex County]] was also reported.<ref name=\"Tribune-Essex-1st\">{{cite web|url=https://www.eagletribune.com/news/merrimack_valley/baker-important-to-start-taking-more-aggressive-actions/article_9da811ab-d265-5a93-8e7c-37b035f27e17.html|title=Baker: 'Important to start taking more aggressive actions'|author=Christian M. Wade|date=March 10, 2020|publisher=Eagle Tribune}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, several schools were closed including Hopkinton Public Schools, Loker Elementary and [[Wayland Middle School]], and Clark Avenue Middle School.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cho | first = Diane | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/coronavirus-concerns-shut-down-hopkinton-wayland-schools-wednesday/2089034/ | title = Multiple Mass. Schools Closed Wednesday Over Coronavirus Outbreak | date = March 11, 2020 | work = NBC Boston | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> Northeastern University and [[Boston University]] moved all classes online.<ref name=\"Corrado\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/coronavirus/university-messages/advancing-our-mission-in-a-time-of-uncertainty/ | title = Advancing our Mission in a Time of Uncertainty | last = Aoun | first = Joseph E. | website = Northeastern University | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bu.edu/articles/2020/bu-all-classes-online-coronavirus/ | title = Updated: BU Moves All Classes Online Due to Coronavirus \u2014 Questions and Answers | last = Most | first = Doug | date = March 11, 2020 | website = BU Today | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Williams College]] announced it would end in-person classes on Friday, March 13 and move to remote learning beginning Monday, April 6.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.williams.edu/coronavirus/ | title = Coronavirus (COVID-19) | website = [[Williams College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Boston College]] moved all classes online, and all students were told to vacate their dorms by March 15.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bc.edu/content/bc-web/sites/updates/coronavirus.html | title = Coronavirus Updates | website = [[Boston College]] | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> All [[University of Massachusetts]] classes moved online until at least April 3.<ref name=\"Corrado\" />\n\n==== March 12\u201313 ====\nOn March 12, there were 108 people in Massachusetts with confirmed or presumptive cases of COVID-19. Among those cases, 82 (75% of the total) were associates or employees of Biogen.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-march-12-2020/download | title = Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Cases in MA | date = March 12, 2020 | website = Massachusetts Department of Public Health | format = PDF | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200313200733/https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-march-12-2020/download | archive-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> Governor Baker noted that the state had tested over 200 patients and had the capacity to test up to 5,000.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Becker | first = Deborah | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/massachusetts-coronavirus-testing | title = State: Massachusetts Has Tested More Than 200 People For Coronavirus | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = CommonHealth}}</ref> The Boston Marriott Long Wharf hotel, which had hosted the Biogen company gathering, closed temporarily. In a letter to their guests, the hotel said it made the decision in cooperation with the [[Boston Public Health Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Goldberg | first = Carey | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/coronavirus-outbreak-biogen-conference-superspreading | title = Single Conference Linked To Most Mass. Coronavirus Cases Looks Like A 'Superspreading Event' | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = CommonHealth}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Borchers | first = Callum | url = https://www.wbur.org/bostonomix/2020/03/12/marriott-hotel-closed-biogen-coronavirus | title = Hotel That Hosted Biogen Gathering Tied To Coronavirus Outbreak Will Close Temporarily | date = March 12, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | department = Bostonomix}}</ref> [[Acton-Boxborough]] announced school closures from March 13 until March 20.<ref>{{Cite tweet | number = 1238185986603003905 | user = ABschools | title = AB Schools will be closed 3/13 \u2013 3/20. See letter below for complete details. We are experiencing issues with our mass messaging system and are requesting this be shared. | author = ABRSSD | date = March 12, 2020 | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, the [[Boston Marathon]] was postponed from April 20 until September 14.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Ruckstuhl | first1 = Laney | title = In A First, Boston Marathon Is Officially Postponed Until September | url = https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/13/boston-marathon-coronavirus-fears-postponed | date= March 13, 2020 |access-date = March 13, 2020 | work = [[WBUR-FM]]}}</ref> A few hours later, Governor Baker prohibited gatherings of more than 250 people. The measure was targeted at large events and exempted most workplaces, transit buildings, polling locations, government buildings, and schools.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Mitchell | first1 = Jack | title = Baker Bans All Gatherings Of 250 Or More People in Mass. | url = https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/13/baker-bans-all-gatherings-of-250-or-more-people-in-mass | access-date = March 13, 2020 |date= March 13, 2020| work = [[WBUR-FM]]}}</ref> [[Se\u00e1n Patrick O'Malley|Cardinal O'Malley]], the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Boston|Roman Catholic Archbishop of Boston]], announced that all daily and Sunday masses and other religious services would be suspended in the Archdiocese of Boston until further notice.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/archdiocese-of-boston-suspends-all-daily-sunday-masses-and-religious-services/31488459 | title = Archdiocese of Boston suspends all daily, Sunday Masses and religious services | date = March 13, 2020 | website = WCVB}}</ref> [[Mayor of Boston|Boston Mayor]] [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]] announced that [[Boston Public Schools]] would be closed starting on March 17 until April 27.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/boston-mayor-marty-walsh-coronavirus-update/2090828/ | title = Boston Public Schools to Close for Over a Month Starting Tuesday Over Coronavirus | date = March 13, 2020 | website = NBC Boston}}</ref> [[Woburn, Massachusetts|Woburn]] announced that a presumptive positive case in the city had been confirmed as negative.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.woburnma.gov/news/2020/03/coronavirus-covid-19/ | title = Coronavirus (COVID-19)-City of Woburn | date = March 13, 2020 | website = City of Woburn}}</ref>\n\n==== March 14\u201315 ====\nOn March 14, [[Cape Cod]] ([[Barnstable County]]) confirmed its first case,<ref name=\"Barnstable-1st\">{{cite web | last1 = Treffeisen | first1 = Beth | title = Cape's first case of COVID-19 confirmed | url = https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200314/capes-first-case-of-covid-19-confirmed | website = [[Cape Cod Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = First case of COVID-19 on Cape | url = https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/03/14/first-case-covid-19-cape/ | website = [[The Martha's Vineyard Times]] | date = March 14, 2020}}</ref> a man in his 60s from [[Sandwich, Massachusetts|Sandwich]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200314/sandwich-man-first-cape-case-of-covid-19 | title = Sandwich man first Cape case of COVID-19 | first = Beth | last = Treffeisen | website = [[Cape Cod Times]]}}</ref> Officials in [[Worcester, Massachusetts|Worcester]] and [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] both announced their respective cities' first confirmed case of COVID-19, both linked to Biogen.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-coronavirus-covid-19-testing-update-march-14-2020/31552452 | title = 1st coronavirus cases in Cape Cod, Worcester among 15 new cases in Mass. | date = March 15, 2020 | website = WCVB}}</ref><ref name=\"Worcester-1st\">{{cite web | url = http://www.worcesterma.gov/announcements/covid-19-update-for-march-14-first-positive-case | title = COVID-19 Update for March 14; First Positive Case | website = City of Worcester, MA}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet | user = TheCityOfMalden | number = 1238842398475800576 | date = March 14, 2020 | title = The Malden Health Department has been notified by the Mass Department of Public Health that a Malden resident has tested positive for Coronavirus.}}</ref> Of the state's 138 cases, 104 (75%) could be traced to employees or contacts of Biogen.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />\n\nA 59-year-old Worcester man died on a flight from Dubai to Boston, sparking speculation that he had died from COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web | last = Becker | first = Kaitlin McKinley | title = Massachusetts Man Who Died Aboard Flight From Dubai to Boston Will Be Tested for COVID-19 | website = NBC Boston | date = March 14, 2020 | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-man-who-died-aboard-flight-from-dubai-to-boston-will-be-tested-for-covid-19/2091214/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> He had been sick with gastrointestinal problems and was in cardiac arrest during the flight.  On March 16, [[Massachusetts State Police]] said that an autopsy revealed he did not have COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web | title = Passenger who died on flight from Dubai to Boston did not have coronavirus, state police say | website = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020 | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/passenger-died-on-international-flight-no-coronavirus-state-police-say/31674048 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Baker ordered all public and private schools in Massachusetts to close for three weeks, from March 17 through April 7. The same day, he also banned eating at restaurants, banned gatherings of over 25 people, relaxed unemployment claim requirements, and enacted other interventions to try to slow the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Becker\">{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/26-new-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts-164-total/2091478/ | title = Gov. Baker Closes Schools, Bans Mid-Size Gatherings, Eating at Restaurants | author = Kaitlin McKinley Becker | date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]] and [[Plymouth County, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] counties had their first cases.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" /> Plymouth County's first case, in [[Hanover, Massachusetts|Hanover]], resulted from travel.<ref name=\"Plymouth-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://www.hanover-ma.gov/home/news/town-of-hanover-covid-19-update-31520 | title = Town of Hanover COVID-19 Update 3/15/20 |website=Hanover, MA |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Hampden County's first case tested positive at [[Baystate Medical Center]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts|Springfield]]; the hospital noted an additional 23 suspected cases.<ref name=\"Hampden-1st\">{{cite web | url = https://www.wwlp.com/news/health/coronavirus-local-impact/baystate-medical-center-confirms-first-case-of-covid-19/ | title = First case of COVID-19 locally confirmed at Baystate Medical Center | first = Katrina | last = Kincade | date = March 14, 2020 | publisher = [[WWLP]]}}</ref>\n\n==== March 16\u201317 ====\n[[File:MBTA_signs_showing_coronavirus-related_schedule_changes.jpg|thumb|alt=Three digital signs in a below-ground subway station. Left sign reads \"Current status: Reduced service. Red line, orange line, green line, blue line. Saturday schedule\". Center sign reads \"Current status: Reduced service. Bus, silver line, commuter rail.\" Right sign reads: \"Current status: No service. Ferry\" All signs have a link at the bottom to MBTA.com/coronavirus|Digital signs in a [[MBTA]] subway station displaying reduced hours and cancelled service due to the coronavirus pandemic]]\nOn March 16, a student at Northeastern University tested positive for COVID-19, one day after the university informed students they would need to vacate their dormitories by 5:00&nbsp;p.m. on March 17.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/15/coronavirus-northeastern-university-student-tests-positive/ | title = Northeastern University Student Tests Positive For Coronavirus | date = March 15, 2020 | website = CBS Boston | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-northeastern-unversitity-students-must-leave-dorms-by-tuesday/ | title = Northeastern Reverses Decision, Says Students Must Leave Dorms For Coronavirus Prevention | date = March 14, 2020 | first = Jim | last = Smith | publisher = CBS Boston}}</ref> Up to this point students were taking online classes but allowed to remain on University property.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://news.northeastern.edu/2020/03/14/northeastern-requests-that-students-move-out-of-dorms-by-tuesday-at-5-p-m-citing-public-health-guidance/ | title = Northeastern requests that students move out of dorms by Tuesday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m., citing public health guidance | website = [[Northeastern University]] | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]] announced its first case, and the mayor declared a state of emergency for the city.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.enterprisenews.com/news/20200316/brockton-mayor-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-city-declares-state-of-emergency | title = Brockton mayor confirms first case of coronavirus in city; declares state of emergency | last = Larocque | first = Marc | website = The Enterprise, Brockton, MA | access-date = March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBoston Mayor Marty Walsh ordered construction projects to shut down by March 23, maintaining only minimal staff for security. He also announced that all branches of the [[Boston Public Library]] would close beginning that night.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/16/nation/latest-thing-shut-down-due-coronavirus-construction-boston/ | title = Ordinary life in MA is over for now: Walsh orders construction shutdown, tally of cases statewide rises to 197 | website = [[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]] (MBTA) announced that starting March 17, it would run the subway and buses at Saturday levels of service during the week, with express buses still running, ferries not running, and [[MBTA Commuter Rail|commuter rail]] running on a modified schedule.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/16/metro/memo-mbta-planning-service-changes-response-coronavirus/ | title = MBTA to reduce train and bus service, close ferry \u2013 The Boston Globe | website = [[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> The next day, service was increased on the [[Blue Line (MBTA)|Blue Line]], [[Green Line \"E\" Branch|Green Line \"E\" branch]] (which serves [[Longwood Medical and Academic Area|Longwood Medical Area]]), and some bus lines to reduce crowding. Frequency on [[Massport]] shuttles to [[Logan International Airport]] was reduced or canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/18/metro/t-trying-balance-unhealthy-crowding-with-fewer-cars/|title=T trying to balance unhealthy crowding with fewer cars \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Department of Public Health revised the criteria for recording COVID-19 cases based on guidance from the CDC, and began to categorize all confirmed or presumptive positive cases as positive.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />\n\nBiogen announced that it would donate $10 million to support global response efforts and communities around the world affected by the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://investors.biogen.com/news-releases/news-release-details/biogen-foundation-commits-10-million-support-covid-19-relief|title=Biogen Foundation Commits $10 Million to Support COVID-19 Relief Efforts in the U.S. and Around the World|website=Biogen|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of hospitalized patients with suspected or known infections quadrupled to 53 between March 16 and 17. Major hospitals began reusing protective gear or asking the public for donations of masks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/18/metro/hospitalizations-covid-19-escalate-greater-boston/|title=Hospitalizations for coronavirus escalate in Greater Boston|date=March 17, 2020|website=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref>\n\n==== March 18\u201321 ====\nThe number of cases where initial exposure was under investigation began to rise rapidly, whereas cases tracked to Biogen attendees and household contacts continued an overall mild decline.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-18\" /> On March 19, Governor Baker activated up to 2,000 [[Massachusetts National Guard]] to assist in the management of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last=McDonald |first=Danny |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/19/nation/baker-activates-national-guard-coronavirus-crisis-grows/ |title=Baker activates National Guard as coronavirus crisis grows |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> The number of cases increased by 72, putting the total at 328, with 119 in [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-328-up-72-in-one-day/2094075/|title=Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases See Largest 1-Day Spike Yet|website=NBC Boston|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> [[Franklin County, Massachusetts|Franklin]] and [[Hampshire County, Massachusetts|Hampshire]] counties\u2014both in Western Massachusetts and the last non-island counties\u2014had their first confirmed cases of COVID-19.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" /> The [[Boston Celtics]] announced that shooting guard [[Marcus Smart]] had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 and was in isolation while in treatment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-celtics/2020/03/19/celtics-coronavirus-test-results| date= March 19, 2020 | first = Nicole | last = Yang| title=Marcus Smart has tested positive for coronavirus|website=Boston.com|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Massachusetts experienced its first death due to COVID-19. The fatality was an 87-year-old man from [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk County]], who was hospitalized and who had preexisting health conditions.<ref name=\"Boston-Herald\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/03/20/first-massachusetts-coronavirus-death-in-elderly-man-from-suffolk-county/|title=First Massachusetts coronavirus death is an elderly man from Suffolk County|date=March 20, 2020|website=[[Boston Herald]]|first=Alex | last= Cohan |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Boston-GLobe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/20/nation/1st-coronavirus-death-is-reported-massachusetts/|title=Winthrop man, 87, is 1st coronavirus death in Massachusetts as case tally rises to more than 400 \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=[[The Boston Globe]] |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Martha's Vineyard]] in [[Dukes County, Massachusetts|Dukes County]] had its first case, a 50-year-old man in [[Tisbury, Massachusetts|Tisbury]].<ref name=\"MVTimes-Tisbury\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mvtimes.com/2020/03/20/confirmed-covid-case/|title=Update: Tisbury resident 'positive' for COVID-19|first=Brian|last=Dowd|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tisbury press release for COVID-19|publisher=Town of Tisbury, office of the Board of Health|url=https://www.tisburyma.gov/sites/tisburyma/files/uploads/press_release_covid-19.pdf|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> This was the thirteenth of 14 counties in Massachusetts to report a case of COVID-19.<ref name=\"NBC-Boston-Number\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/number-of-massachusetts-coronavirus-cases-jumps-to-413/2094757/|title=Number of Massachusetts Coronavirus Cases Jumps to 413|date=March 20, 2020|website=NBC Boston|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> [[Harvard University]] declared that its 369th Commencement Exercises would be postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/coronavirus-live-blog-msp-warning-about-covid-19-thefts/WUF4Z3XGGVDVBES6E3WMOCJYRQ/|title=Coronavirus live blog: Confirmed cases jumps to 413, state not planning shelter-in-place order|website=WFXT|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The cities of [[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville]] and [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] closed non-essential businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.somervillema.gov/departments/programs/novel-coronavirus-preparedness-and-information|title=SomervilleMA.gov Novel Coronavirus Preparedness and Information|access-date=March 21, 2020|website=SomervilleMA.gov|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175543/https://www.somervillema.gov/departments/programs/novel-coronavirus-preparedness-and-information|archive-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cambridgema.gov:443/en/news/2020/03/temporaryemergencyorderontheclosureofseveralbusinessesactivities|title=Cambridge City Manager and Commissioner of Public Health Issue Temporary Emergency Order on the Closure of Several Businesses and Activities|website=www.cambridgema.gov}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Social distancing in a Trader Joe's line in Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts March 21, 2020.jpg|thumb|[[Social distancing]] in a [[Trader Joe's]] line in [[Cambridgeport, Cambridge, Massachusetts]] on March 21, 2020]]\n[[File:Closed picnic area Natick Turnpike rest area on I-90 during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts.jpg|thumb|Closed picnic area at the Natick Service Plaza]]\nOn March 21, the [[Massachusetts Department of Corrections]] (DOC) announced the first confirmed case of COVID-19 among its inmate population. According to officials at [[Massachusetts Treatment Center|MTC Bridgewater,]] a male inmate who was serving a life sentence tested positive.  Massachusetts DOC noted this was the only known case of COVID-19 in its inmate population.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/inmate-at-bridgewater-prison-massachusetts-treatment-center-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-officials-say/31846456|title=Inmate at local prison tests positive for coronavirus, officials say|date=March 21, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>  Governor Baker announced that 5,207 people had been tested for COVID-19 in Massachusetts through state and commercial laboratories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-21-2020/31849021|title=Total coronavirus cases climb over 500 in Mass.; includes first on Martha's Vineyard|date=March 21, 2020|website=WCVB}}</ref> That night the state announced its second death due to COVID-19, a woman from [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]] in her 50s who had a preexisting health condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/second-covid-19-related-death-massachusetts-announced/RELZ7F5NWREGBHC7HOJ5QWGXMY/|title=Second COVID-19 related death in Massachusetts announced|website=WFXT}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Croteau |first1=Scott |title=Coronavirus: Ayer woman is second COVID-19 death in Massachusetts, health officials confirm |url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-ayer-woman-is-second-covid-19-death-in-massachusetts-health-officials-confirm.html |access-date=March 22, 2020 |publisher=MassLive |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Nantucket County, the last county to have no cases of the virus, reported its first COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"McCormich\">{{cite web|url=https://www.capecodtimes.com/news/20200320/virus-cases-multiply-on-cape-cod-vineyard|title=Virus cases multiply on Cape Cod, Vineyard|last=McCormick|first=Cynthia|website=capecodtimes.com|language=en|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> In order to reduce contact between drivers and customers, the MBTA began rear-door boarding on above-ground stops for buses, the [[Green Line (MBTA)|Green Line]], and the [[Ashmont\u2013Mattapan High-Speed Line|Mattapan Trolley]], except for passengers with disabilities who need to use the front door.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mbta.com/news/2020-03-20/mbta-announces-service-update-effective-saturday-march-21|title=MBTA Announces Service Update Effective Saturday, March 21 &#124; News &#124; MBTA|website=www.mbta.com}}</ref>\n\n==== March 22\u201325 ====\n\nOn March 22, Nantucket issued a [[Shelter in place|shelter-in-place order]], to start March 23 and end on April 6. Exceptions were made for essential services to remain open.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/coronavirus-live-blog-second-mass-resident-dies-covid-19-525-total-cases-across-state/WUF4Z3XGGVDVBES6E3WMOCJYRQ/|title=Coronavirus live blog: Second Mass. resident dies from COVID-19; 525 total cases across state|website=WFXT|language=en-US|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Governor Baker instructed people in mainland Massachusetts with second homes in Nantucket and Dukes County to stay on the mainland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/mass-gov-baker-to-provide-update-on-coronavirus-response/2095463/|title='Stay on Mainland,' Gov. Baker Tells Residents With 2nd Homes on Nantucket, Vineyard|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Three new deaths were reported by Massachusetts DPH, two men, both in their 70s, from [[Hampden County, Massachusetts|Hampden]] and [[Berkshire County, Massachusetts|Berkshire]] counties, and a man in his 90s from Suffolk County.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-22\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/121-new-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts-total-jumps-to-646/2095586/|title=Massachusetts Reports 3 More Coronavirus Deaths as Cases Reach 646 Statewide|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced a stay-at-home advisory effective from March 24 until April 7. Nonessential businesses were ordered to close physical workplaces, and restaurants and bars were restricted to offering takeout and delivery. People were told they could go out to obtain essential goods and services, such as groceries and medicine, but should follow [[social distancing]] protocols.<ref name=\"Feuer\">{{cite news |last1=Feuer |first1=William |title=Massachusetts under \"stay-at-home\" order until April 7, Gov. Baker announces |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/massachusetts-under-stay-at-home-order-until-april-7-gov-baker-announces.html |access-date=March 23, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, the number of cases jumped by 382 to 1,159, with two new deaths attributed to COVID-19.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-03-24\">https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-24-2020/download</ref> This unusually large jump in cases (49%, versus 20-28% in the previous five days) was attributable to [[Quest Diagnostics]] processing 3,843 tests in one day, yielding 267 of the state's 382 new positive results.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />\n\nOn March 25, Governor Baker extended school closures until May 4.<ref name=\"NBC-Boston\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/gov-baker-to-provide-coronavirus-update/2096962/|title=Baker Extends School and Day Care Closures|website=NBC Boston|language=en-US|access-date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Commissioner of Public Health issued emergency regulations for grocery stores and pharmacies, requiring them to designate a daily shopping hour for senior citizens and provide checkout line distancing markers, hand washing and sanitizer for employees, disinfecting wipes for customers to use on carts. A ban on reusable bags became mandatory, overriding local bans on single-use plastic bags and eliminating fees for store-provided bags. Self-service food stations were ordered to be closed, and regular sanitization was required.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/doc/grocery-and-pharmacy-store-order/download|title=Order of the Commissioner of Public Health, March 25}}</ref>\n\n==== March 26\u201331 ====\nOn March 27, the state extended the tax filing deadline to July 15 and announced new travel guidelines.<ref>{{cite web | title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Travel Guidelines and New Health Care Resources To Support COVID-19 Response | website=Mass.gov | date=March 27, 2020 | url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-travel-guidelines-and-new-health-care-resources-to | access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Massachusetts Announces State Income Tax Filing Deadline Being Extended to July 15 | website=Mass.gov | date=March 27, 2020 | url=https://www.mass.gov/news/massachusetts-announces-state-income-tax-filing-deadline-being-extended-to-july-15 | access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Mass. coronavirus cases jump by more than 800, with 10 new related deaths; Baker asks travelers to self-quarantine | website=[[The Boston Globe]] | date=March 27, 2020 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/27/metro/baker-asks-all-travelers-arriving-mass-self-quarantine/ | access-date=March 27, 2020}}</ref> State officials announced that the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] Commissioner, Monica Bharel, had tested positive for SARS-CoV-19, and that she had mild symptoms planned to recover at home.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.patriotledger.com/news/20200327/massachusetts-department-of-public-health-commissioner-tests-positive-for-coronavirus |title=Massachusetts Department of Public Health commissioner tests positive for coronavirus \u2013 News \u2013 The Patriot Ledger, Quincy, MA \u2013 Quincy, MA |publisher=Patriotledger.com |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the state announced that it had conducted almost 43,000 tests of Massachusetts residents, with Quest Diagnostics having conducted 21,321 (almost half) of the total tests administered.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-03-30\">https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-30-2020/download</ref> A potential cluster of COVID-19 cases was reported in [[Holyoke, Massachusetts]] at [[Soldiers' Home in Holyoke|Soldiers' Home]], a nursing facility for military veterans. Eleven residents had recently died, and another eleven residents along with several staff members had tested positive for SARS-CoV-19.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lisinski |first=Chris |url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/holyoke-soldiers-home-superintendent-placed-on-leave-effective-immediately/ |title=11 veterans dead, several residents, staff exposed to COVID-19 at Holyoke Soldiers' Home |publisher=WWLP |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> Later that evening, the MBTA announced that 18 transit workers had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/30/metro/mbta-unions-looking-more-ways-slow-spread-coronavirus/|title=MBTA, unions looking for more ways to slow the spread of coronavirus \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref> In addition, the [[Boston Police Department]] confirmed that 19 officers and three civilian employees had all tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://twitter.com/Tom_Winter/status/1244788245721997315 |title=Tom Winter on Twitter: \"NEW: Boston Police spokesperson John Boyle says 22 BPD members have tested positive for COVID-19, 19 uniformed and 3 civilians. This updates an earlier tweet.\" |publisher=Twitter.com |date=March 27, 2009 |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n==== April 1\u20133 ====\nGovernor Baker appointed an independent investigator to examine the outbreak of COVID-19 at the Soldiers' Home nursing facility in Holyoke.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/04/coronavirus-gov-charlie-baker-appoints-independent-investigator-to-examine-holyoke-soldiers-home-in-wake-of-covid-19-deaths.html|title=Coronavirus: Gov. Charlie Baker appoints independent investigator to examine Holyoke Soldiers' Home in wake of COVID-19 deaths|date=April 1, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref> Holyoke Mayor [[Alex Morse]] accused the nursing facility of mismanagement and lack of transparency in the events surrounding the outbreak and its resulting twelve fatalities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-alex-morse-says-lack-of-urgency-and-mismangement-at-facility-where-as-many-as-12-have-died.html|title=Coronavirus at Holyoke Soldiers' Home: Alex Morse says mismanagement at facility where as many as 12 have died|date=March 31, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-family-members-say-they-were-left-in-the-dark-as-sickness-spread.html|title=Family members say they were left in the dark as COVID-19 spread at Holyoke Soldiers Home|date=March 31, 2020|website=masslive}}</ref> The Archdiocese of Boston announced that eight priests had tested positive for the disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/metro/seven-catholic-priests-test-positive-covid-19-boston-archdiocese/|title=Eight Catholic priests from Boston Archdiocese test positive for coronavirus \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref> State authorities announced plans to convert the [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] (BCEC) into a field hospital to assist in treating patients suffering from COVID-19 <ref>https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-boston-convention-center-field-hospital-bcec/</ref>\n\nOn April 2, more than 500 healthcare workers in Boston hospitals were reported to have tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mikesacconetv/status/1245511498790768640|title=NEW: Holyoke Soldiers' Home Superintendent Bennett Walsh releases a statement denying any wrongdoing as 2 more veterans die, bringing total number of deaths to 15. 6 have tested positive for COVID-19. The test results for 6 others are pending. 2 tested negative & 1 unknown.pic.twitter.com/suDyGx2Zdi|first=Mike|last=Saccone|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/employee-infections-largest-massachusetts-hospitals-nearly-triple-week/|title=Near tripling of employee coronavirus infections in largest Massachusetts hospitals in past week \u2013 The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mikesacconetv/status/1244736042273583105|title=BREAKING: More than 500 healthcare workers in Massachusetts have tested positive for COVID-19, according to a tally I've been keeping. The 5 hospitals with the most cases are listed below. #Boston25pic.twitter.com/pz8wo0Wmlf|first=Mike|last=Saccone|date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> Three more residents of Holyoke Soldiers' Home died, bringing that outbreak's total number of deaths to 18.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwlp.com/news/local-news/hampden-county/18-veterans-now-confirmed-dead-at-soldiers-home-in-holyoke/|title=18 veterans now confirmed dead at Soldiers' Home in Holyoke|date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:A medic with the Massachusetts National Guard takes a nasal swab that will be used to test for COVID-19 with a resident of the Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley Littleton Mass. April 3 2020.jpg|thumb|A medic with the [[Massachusetts National Guard]] and a resident of the [[Life_Care_Centers_of_America#Littleton,_Massachusetts_COVID-19_Outbreak|Life Care Center]] of Nashoba Valley nursing home handle a nasal swab that will be used to test for COVID-19]]\nOn April 3, [[Holyoke Medical Center]] announced that a total of 21 residents of the Soldier's Home in Holyoke had died, at least 15 of whom tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Mike Saccone |url=https://twitter.com/mikesacconetv/status/1246140619883413509 |title=BREAKING: 21 veteran residents at the Holyoke Soldiers' Home have died. 15 had tested positive for coroanvirus. 59 veterans at the home have tested positive for coronavirus & 160 have tested negative. #Boston |publisher=Twitter.com |date=April 12, 2009 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> According to officials, a total of 59 residents had tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Markos |first=Mary |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/03/21-veterans-die-at-holyoke-soldiers-home-15-confirmed-for-coronavirus/ |title=21 veterans die at Holyoke Soldiers' Home, 15 confirmed for coronavirus \u2013 Boston Herald |publisher=Bostonherald.com |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/03/nation/years-understaffing-mismanagement-set-deadly-stage-coronavirus-outbreak-holyoke-soldiers-home-employees-say/ |title=Years of understaffing, mismanagement set deadly stage for coronavirus outbreak at Holyoke Soldiers' Home, employees say |website=Boston Globe |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Officials in [[Norwood, Massachusetts]] announced that at least fifteen people had died at the Charlwell House Health and Rehabilitation Center with at least seven of them having tested positive for COVID-19. Officials with the nursing facility acknowledged that only twenty of the more than 200 residents and staff at the facility had been able to be tested for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Szaniszlo |first=Marie |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/03/deaths-at-nursing-homes-in-norwood-littleton-linked-to-coronavirus/ |title=Seven people who died at Norwood nursing home tested positive for COVID-19 |publisher=Bostonherald.com |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> AdviniaCare, a nursing facility located in [[Wilmington, Massachusetts]] which had been slated to be converted to temporary recovery center for COVID-19 patients, announced that 51 of 98 residents had tested positive for the virus, and that it would temporarily halt plans to transition its facilitates into a recovery center. AdviniaCare had been selected to become a recovery center for Boston-area COVID-19 patients who were still contagious but had recovered sufficiently to be discharged out of the intensive care units of Boston area hospitals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/03/metro/51-residents-positive-coronavirus-wilmington-nursing-home-despite-having-no-symptoms/ |title=51 residents positive for coronavirus at Wilmington nursing home, despite having no symptoms |website=Boston Globe |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== April 4\u20139 ====\n[[File:Closed Playground in Salem.jpg|thumb|Closed playground in [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] on April 4, 2020]]\nOn April 5, Boston Mayor Walsh announced a voluntary city-wide [[curfew]] for non-emergency workers in Boston from 9{{Nbsp}}p.m. to 6{{Nbsp}}a.m.,<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/04/05/watch-live-walsh-to-give-update-on-boston-coronavirus-response |title=WATCH: Walsh Announces 21:00 Curfew To Help Slow The Spread Of Coronavirus |date=April 5, 2020| website=WGBH News}}</ref> and asked all Bostonians to wear face coverings in public.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/05/nation/read-mayor-walshs-statement-recommended-curfew-other-coronavirus-guidelines-announced-sunday/ Read Mayor Walsh's statement on the recommended curfew for Boston]</ref>\n\nOn April 9, the city of Boston announced that African Americans seem to be disproportionately impacted by COVID-19; although they only account for 25% of the city population, almost 40% of cases in the City of Boston were among African Americans.<ref>https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/04/09/early-boston-data-shows-disturbing-racial-disparities-in-covid-19-infections</ref> Massachusetts Institute of Technology published a preliminary study of sewage samples in the Boston area, taken on March 25, in an effort to determine how many actual people may be infected from COVID-19, a figure that is unknown due to lack of testing. Based on concentrations of the virus found in the samples, the study suggested that in an area of Boston containing 2.3 million people, approximately 115,000 people were truly infected. On March 25, at the time of sampling, Massachusetts only had 646 confirmed cases in the area.<ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/09/massachusetts-scientists-probe-nations-sewage-for-coronavirus-clues/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/08/massachusetts-sewage-suggests-more-than-100k-coronavirus-cases-in-state-mit-lab/</ref>\n\n==== April 10\u201312 ====\n\nOn April 10, the US Attorney's office in Boston announced that it would be opening a federal investigation into whether the Holyoke Soldiers' Home nursing home violated the rights of its patients by failing to provide them adequate medical care and protection during the COVID-19 outbreak. Officials with the Massachusetts DPH announced that in the past month, 35 residents of the Holyoke nursing home had died, with 30 of them testing positive for [[COVID-19]].<REF>https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/10/us/holyoke-soldiers-home-us-attorney-investigation/index.html</ref>  Starting the evening of Friday April 10, the [[Massachusetts Department of Conservation and Recreation]] closed some parkways to vehicle traffic to allow recreational pedestrians to spread out, and reduced parking availability at some state parks. The city of Boston also reduced parking near the [[Arnold Arboretum]].<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/pedestrians-take-over-parkways-boston-watertown-while-parking-spots-are-cut-arbortum/ Pedestrians to take over parkways in Boston and Watertown while parking spots are cut at Arboretum]</ref> The Massachusetts Education Commissioner canceled [[Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System|MCAS]] standardized tests for the first time, taking advantage of a federal waiver.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/mass-finally-cancels-mcas-exams/ Mass. cancels MCAS exams]</ref> The Massachusetts Department of Public Health released figures showing 491 new cases at long-term care facilities, bringing the total number of infected patients at the state's long-term care facilities to 2,124.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/city-cambridge-broad-institute-test-all-staff-residents-city-nursing-homes/</ref> The [[Life Care Centers of America|Life Care Center]] of [[Nashoba Valley]] in [[Littleton, Massachusetts|Littleton]], where 10 residents have died, reported that 75 of its 204 employees were out sick and that at least 14 of them have tested positive for SARS-CoV-2.<ref>Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley in Littleton, where 10 residents with the virus have died, its parent company said Friday that 75 of its 204 employees were out sick and that 14 have been infected with COVID-19.</ref>\n\nOn April 11, the state department of public health released new data regarding the impact of COVID-19 in the longterm care facilities in the state. According to the Massachusetts Department of Public Health, 306 out of the 686 victims of COVID-19 were patients who died in long-term care facilities in the sate of Massachusetts.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/city-cambridge-broad-institute-test-all-staff-residents-city-nursing-homes/</ref> State officials also announced that 190 long-term care facilities had at least one case of COVID-19.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-cases-quarantine-and-monitoring</ref> Officials at the Life Care Center of Nashoba Valley announced that Maria Krier, a nurse who had spoken out about improper training at the nursing home, had died. She had told reporters that she believed management had no experience with infectious disease and that that had contributed to the spread of COVID-19 at the facility.<ref>https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/us/whistleblower-nurse-who-spoke-out-about-littleton-nursing-home-dies-of-covid-19/ar-BB12uxHD</ref> Officials announced that 37 residents of the Soldiers' Home in Holyoke have died of COVID-19. In addition, 70 of the nursing and facilities staff have tested positive.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/dozens-deaths-massachusetts-nursing-home-veterans-prompts-federal-investigation-n1181226</ref>\n\nOn April 12, there were 25,475 total cases, with 2,615 new cases, putting Massachusetts as the state with the third-most cases in the United States, only behind New York and New Jersey.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-april-12-2020/download</ref> Massachusetts officials warned of ebb and flow of the spread of COVID-19.<ref>https://www.enterprisenews.com/news/20200411/brockton-coronavirus-cases-drop-for-first-time-in-weeks-officials-warn-of-ebb-and-flow</ref> Officials with JGS Lifecare in [[Longmeadow, Massachusetts]] announced in a letter to benefactors that 21 residents of the facility have died of COVID-19 and that 93 residents have tested positive for COVID-19.  In addition to residents, officials announced that 43 staff members have tested positive for COVID-19. <ref>https://www.bostonherald.com/2020/04/12/coronavirus-in-massachusetts-21-residents-of-nursing-home-die-93-test-positive/</ref> <ref>https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/11/21-residents-dead-jgs-lifecare-senior-home</ref>\n\n==== April 13\u201314 ====\n\nOn April 13, Mass. DPH announced they would be releasing data on a 24-hour basis, from 10:00 to 10:00 the next day.<ref>https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-april-13-2020/download</ref>\n\nOn April 14, Mass. DPH announced that there were 1,296 new cases of COVID-19 in Massachusetts raising the state total to 28,163.  In addition, 113 new deaths were reported raising the state total to 957. <ref>https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/massachusetts-reports-113-more-coronavirus-deaths-nearing-1000-in-total/2107597/</ref>  State officials announced that a total of 44 residents of Soldier's Home in Holyoke have died since late March.  Officials acknowledged that the fatalities have almost doubled from 21 on April 3 to 44 fatalities on April 13. Soldier's Home is now the subject of a federal investigation pertaining to patient mismanagement in regards to the COVID-19 pandemic. <ref>https://abcnews.go.com/US/40-veterans-died-massachusetts-holyoke-veterans-home-facing/story?id=70138817</ref>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n=== Initial exposures and spread ===\nThe index case of COVID-19 in Massachusetts was reported on February 1, 2020 in Boston.  The patient, a University of Massachusetts Boston student in his 20s, had recently returned to Boston from Wuhan, China.<ref name=\"Wertheim\" /> The second confirmed case in Massachusetts was reported on March 2. The patient was a woman in her 20s from Norfolk County, who had recently traveled to Italy with a school group from Saint Raphael Academy in Pawtucket, Rhode Island.<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" />  After a month of stasis, cases began growing rapidly on March 5, with most traceable to a Biogen employee meeting held in at the Marriott Long Wharf hotel in Boston from February 26\u201328.<ref group=\"note\">See [[#Cases by category|Cases by category]] table.</ref>\n\nExposure clusters were reported from mid to late March. Local [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] began being reported on March 16, slightly exceeding cases related to travel.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-16\" />  An outbreak cluster of untraced origin in the [[Berkshire Medical Center]] in Western Massachusetts was briefly tracked from March 11 through March 15. Cases that had been [[contact tracing|contact-traced]] to Biogen plateaued on March 13, and were surpassed by local transmissions on March 23. Cases of unknown exposure surpassed those of known exposure on March 19, then grew rapidly. When the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]] ceased updating statistics on exposure on March 27, there were 99 cases traced to Biogen, 163 cases of local transmission, 93 cases related to travel, and 2,885 cases where initial exposure was under investigation.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":MDPH-3-27\" />\n\nThe disease went undetected after entering Boston in Suffolk County in early February. It then re-emerged in early March and spread to the state's remaining 13 counties within three weeks. Suffolk County had its first reported case on February 1,<ref name=\"Wertheim\" /> Norfolk County on March 2,<ref name=\"WBUR-2nd\" /> Middlesex County on March 6,<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-13\" /> Berkshire County on March 7,<ref name=\"WHDH-Berkshire-1st\" /> Essex County on March 10,<ref name=\"Tribune-Essex-1st\" /> Barnstable and Worcester counties on March 14,<ref name=\"Barnstable-1st\" /><ref name=\"Worcester-1st\" /> Hampden and Plymouth counties on March 15,<ref name=\"Hampden-1st\" /><ref name=\"Plymouth-1st\" /> Franklin and Hampshire counties on March 19,<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-18\" /> Dukes County on March 20,<ref name=\"MVTimes-Tisbury\" /> and Nantucket County on March 21.<ref name=\"McCormich\" />\n\n=== Tests ===\nMassachusetts has performed 108,776 tests for COVID-19 {{As of|2020|04|11|lc=y}}. Tests were conducted by the Massachusetts State Public Health Laboratory and over 25 other organizations.<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />\n\n=== Hospitalizations ===\nBetween 6% and 14% of COVID-19 cases in Massachusetts were known to be hospitalized.<ref group=\"note\">See \"[[#Diagrams|Cases by percent hospitalized\" diagram]].</ref>  The first four [[hospitalization]]s were reported on March 9.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-12\" />  The number of hospitalizations surpassed 10 on March 12,<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-3-9\" /> 100 on March 25,<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-03-30\" /> and 500 on March 31.<ref group=\"note\" name=\"MDPH-03-31\">https://www.mass.gov/doc/covid-19-cases-in-massachusetts-as-of-march-31-2020/download</ref>  The number of cases with unknown hospitalization status exceeded those with a known status on March 23.<ref group=\"note\" name=\":MDPH-3-28\" />\n\n=== Deaths ===\nDeaths due to COVID-19 have been concentrated among the elderly. {{As of|2020|04|5|alt=As of April 5}}, 192 of 231 (83%) COVID-19 deaths in Massachusetts were in patients aged 70 or older.<ref group=\"note\">See \"[[#Diagrams|Deaths by age group]]\" chart.</ref>  The state's first death due to COVID-19 was on March 20. The patient was a 87-year-old man from Suffolk County, hospitalized and with preexisting health conditions.<ref name=\"Boston-Herald\" /><ref name=\"Boston-GLobe\" />\n\n=== Cases by category ===\nThe Massachusetts Department of Public Health began publishing daily updates on COVID-19 in Massachusetts on March 6, 2020.  Local media and the state also published intermittent reports beforehand.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-datatable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right; font-size: 0.9em;\"\n! colspan=\"21\" | Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Massachusetts<ref name=\"MDPH-Cases\" />\n|-\n! |\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Total\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Exposure\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Tests\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Hospitalization\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | Deaths\n!Recoveries <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/info-details/covid-19-cases-quarantine-and-monitoring|title=COVID-19 Cases, Quarantine and Monitoring|website=Mass.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:70px; border-right:2px solid #888;\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsort