0\n| 2649\n| 2024\n| 5359\n| 2032\n| 373\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":33\" group=\"note\" />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | April 13\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |502\n| 355\n| 1394\n| 21\n| 3413\n| 148\n| 1694\n| 224\n| 5983\n| 2838\n| 2141\n| 5579\n| 2128\n| 447\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |<ref name=\":34\" group=\"note\" />\n|-\n ! style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | Date\n ! {{vert header|Barnstable}}\n ! {{vert header|Berkshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Bristol}}\n ! {{vert header|Dukes and Nantucket}}\n ! {{vert header|Essex}}\n ! {{vert header|Franklin}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampden}}\n ! {{vert header|Hampshire}}\n ! {{vert header|Middlesex}}\n ! {{vert header|Norfolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Plymouth}}\n ! {{vert header|Suffolk}}\n ! {{vert header|Worcester}}\n ! {{vert header|Unknown}}\n ! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |Source\n|-\n| style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" | <strong>County <br /> pop <br /> (2020)</strong>\n| {{vert header|213,413}}\n| {{vert header|126,348}}\n| {{vert header|564,022}}\n| {{vert header|28,679}}\n| {{vert header|790,638}}\n| {{vert header|70,963}}\n| {{vert header|470,406}}\n| {{vert header|161,355}}\n| {{vert header|1,614,714}}\n| {{vert header|705,388}}\n| {{vert header|518,132}}\n| {{vert header|807,252}}\n| {{vert header|830,839}}\n|\n| style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.massachusetts-demographics.com/counties_by_population |access-date = April 6, 2020 | title = Massachusetts Counties by Population | website= Massachusetts Demographics}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Government response ==\n[[File:ASM show at BCEC.agr.jpg|thumb|Interior of the [[Boston Convention and Exposition Center]] (BCEC), pictured during a 2016 conference. The BCEC will be converted to a [[field hospital]].]]\n\nCiting the rapid increase in cases, Governor Charlie Baker declared a [[state of emergency]] for Massachusetts on March 10.<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/governor-charlie-baker-declares-state-of-emergency-coronavirus-3-10-2020/31356404 | title = Gov. Baker declares state of emergency as Mass. coronavirus cases more than double | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | last = Locke | first = Kaitlyn | url = https://www.wgbh.org/news/local-news/2020/03/10/baker-declares-state-of-emergency-92-total-coronavirus-cases-in-massachusetts | title = Baker Declares State Of Emergency; 92 Total Coronavirus Cases in Massachusetts | date = March 10, 2020 | publisher = WGBH News | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> During a press conference on March 14, 2020, Governor Baker established an emergency command center and promised to expand statewide lab testing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/14/metro/baker-sets-up-virus-command-center/|title=State figures on testing raise questions about efforts to contain outbreak |website=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker banned all public gatherings of over 25 people, closed all K\u201312 public schools from March 17 through April 7, and banned on-site service at bars and restaurants for the same period.<ref>{{cite news | title = Gov. Baker bans gatherings of over 25 people, orders school closure, restaurants take-out only | url = https://www.wcvb.com/article/gov-charlie-baker-massachusetts-covid-19-coronavirus-update-march-15-2020/31647097 | access-date = March 17, 2020 | publisher = WCVB | date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, Governor Baker ordered all schools and childcare services to be closed through May 4, extending the original closure by three weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-announces-extension-of-school-and-non-emergency-child-care-program|title=Baker-Polito Administration Announces Extension of School and Non-Emergency Child Care Program Closures and Steps to Ensure Housing Stability To Support COVID-19 Response|author= Office of Governor Charlie Baker and Lt. Governor Karyn Polito|publisher=Mass.gov|date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Governor Baker announced a stay-at-home advisory to be effective from March 24 until April 7. On March 31 the advisory which was extended to May 4.<ref name=\"Feuer\" /> Starting March 31, hotels, motels and online rentals like [[Airbnb]] were ordered to close to recreational travelers so they could be used to house essential workers and displaced residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mass.gov/news/baker-polito-administration-extends-non-essential-business-closures-and-executive-branch|title=Baker-Polito Administration Extends Non-Essential Business Closures and Executive Branch Employee Guidance|publisher=Mass.gov}}</ref> The [[Boston Convention and Exhibition Center]] is being prepared as a 1,000-bed [[field hospital]] for COVID-19 patients, including 500 beds for infected homeless patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/04/02/1000-beds-planned-for-boston-convention-center-to-treat-coronavirus-patients|title=1,000 Beds Planned For Boston Convention Center To Treat Coronavirus Patients|date=April 2, 2020|first=Ally|last=Jarmanning|publisher=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[DCU Center]] in Worcester was set up as a field hospital for recovering COVID-19 patients, overseen by [[UMass Memorial Medical Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/31/dcu-arena-covid-19-field-hospital|title=Worcester's DCU Center Will Become 250-Bed Field Hospital For Stable COVID-19 Patients|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Governor Baker asked travelers from out of state to avoid Massachusetts or to self-quarantine upon arrival for 14 days. Electronic highway signs were activated, and travelers arriving at [[Logan International Airport]], [[Worcester Regional Airport]], and [[South Station]] were given flyers.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/03/27/baker-out-of-state-quarantine|title=Baker Asks Visitors To Self-Isolate For Two Weeks \u2014 Or Not Come At All|publisher=www.wbur.org}}</ref> Medical students were graduated early, and emergency orders were issued giving some nurses with more than two years of experience authority to write prescriptions, and granting incoming medical residents and interns 90-day medical licenses.<ref name=\"WBUR-Baker\" />\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Registry of Motor Vehicles]] moved to an appointment-only system to avoid overcrowding, and the state extended deadlines for many renewals by 60 days to reduce the need for in-person transactions. With visits down about 90%, eight of the 30 RMV branches closed completely. The National Association of Government Employees, representing customer service employees at the RMV, asked that the remaining offices be closed for worker safety, but the Secretary of Transportation said essential workers needed the RMV to continue operating.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/10/metro/rmv-workers-union-calls-agency-shutter-all-branches/ RMV workers union calls for agency to shutter all branches]</ref>\n\n== Economic and social effects ==\nThe sudden surge of cases in Massachusetts during the week of March 9 led many organizations to order employees to work from home, and prompted museums and libraries to close. This led to a noticeable decline in Boston's rush hour traffic; in some cases, drive times for major highways dropped by 30 to 50 percent.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/11/boston-traffic-coronavirus | title = Coronavirus: Here's how much Boston's rush hour traffic has dropped &#124; Boston.com | website = Boston.com}}</ref> [[Panic buying]], especially since the week of March 11, led to shortages of some products, and there were crowds and long lines at grocery stores as early in the day as 7:00{{Nbsp}}a.m.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/store-shelves-picked-clean-people-panic-buy-goods-local-supermarkets/ | title = Store shelves picked clean as people panic-buy goods at local supermarkets |newspaper= The Boston Globe | access-date = April 6, 2020 | date= March 13, 2020 | first= Steve |last=Annear |first2=Janelle |last2=Nanos}}</ref> Some grocery retailers such as [[Stop & Shop]] adjusted their hours to allow employees more time to restock and to offer older and more vulnerable people a time where they can shop separately.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-stop-and-shop-senior-hours/ |title=Stop & Shop Creates Hours Only For Customers 60 And Older During Coronavirus Pandemic |date=March 16, 2020 |website=CBS Boston}}</ref> Later, grocery stores implemented stricter measures, including limiting the amount of people allowed inside stores at a time, and marking queues to maintain social distancing. <!--- https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/04/01/coronavirus-market-basket-social-distance/ ---> When people in parks were found to not be following social distancing resulted in many parks and playgrounds being closed. Some cities went as far as to remove or block off basketball hoops and other amenities to discourage people from gathering. <!--- https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2020/03/29/marty-walsh-boston-parks-coronavirus ---> Beaches and their parking lots were also ordered to close. <!--- https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/02/metro/parking-lots-state-beaches-are-closing/ ---> On April 5, 2020, Boston's mayor, Marty Walsh, issued a stay-at-home advisory for the city of Boston. All non-essential workers were ordered to stay home from 9:00{{Nbsp}}p.m. to 6:00{{Nbsp}}a.m., starting April 6. People were encouraged to wear masks when outside the home, but instructed to leave medical masks for essential workers and make their own if necessary. All baseball, tennis, and hockey fields in parks were ordered to be closed. Residents were instructed not to visit family or fields outside of their households. The restrictions are enforceable by fines.<ref name=\"WGBH-Curfew\" />\n\n{{As of|2020|04|10|df=US|alt=As of April 10}}, eight deaths have been reported at Jack Satter House in [[Revere, Massachusetts|Revere]], a nursing home run by Hebrew Senior Life. Other nursing homes are also reporting confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boston-area senior housing community with Jewish ties reports 6 coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.jta.org/quick-reads/boston-area-senior-housing-community-under-jewish-auspices-reports-6-coronavirus-deaths |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Jewish Telegraphic Agency}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases at senior centers and nursing homes in Massachusetts are rising: 'It's a hot zone' - The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/01/nation/covid-deaths-senior-centers-nursing-homes-rise/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=BostonGlobe.com |date=April 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hebrewseniorlife.org/about-us/covid-19-coronavirus-guidance/jack-satter-house-covid-19-update|title=Jack Satter House - COVID-19 Update|last=|first=|date=|website=Hebrew Senior Life|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== School closures ===\nSchool closures began in early March, when Massachusetts Institute of Technology announced on March 9 that it was moving to only-online classes for the remainder of the spring semester.<ref name=\"MIT-Update\" /> Also on March 9, two elementary schools in the [[Plainville, Massachusetts|Plainville]] school district and one in [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]] were closed for the day due to COVID-19 tests being conducted on two parents and one child.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Cuoco | first = John | url = https://whdh.com/news/multiple-massachusetts-schools-closed-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-rise/ | title = Multiple Massachusetts schools closed Monday as coronavirus cases continue to rise | date = March 9, 2020 | work = WHDH 7News | access-date = March 11, 2020}}</ref> School districts began closing on March 11. Within a week, many colleges and state school districts announced closures ranging from weeks to months in duration.<ref name=\"Williams-Update\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/massachusetts-coronavirus-update-schools-closing-or-changing-schedules-for-monday-march-16.html|title=Massachusetts coronavirus update: Schools closing or changing schedules for Monday, March 16|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 13, 2020|website=MassLive|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams-Colleges\">{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-and-massachusetts-updated-list-of-massachusetts-colleges-with-canceled-classes-plans-to-switch-to-online-instruction-march-13.html|title=Coronavirus and Massachusetts: Updated list of Massachusetts colleges with canceled classes, plans to switch to online instruction (March 13)|last=Williams|first=Michelle|date=March 14, 2020|publisher=MassLive}}</ref>\n\nWellesley and Framingham closed their public schools and libraries for two weeks on March 13.<ref>{{cite web | title = WPS Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/wps-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Town of Wellesley COVID-19 Update 3/13/2020 | website = Wellesley Public Schools | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://wellesleyps.org/blog/2020/03/13/town-of-wellesley-covid-19-update-3-13-2020/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=2023 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release | title = Framingham Library, Callahan Center, Loring Arena, and Public Schools to Close for a Minimum of Two Weeks Starting Friday, March 13 | website = Framingham, MA | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.framinghamma.gov/DocumentCenter/View/37162/Press-Release---COVID-19-Update-031320204265 | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 13, Boston announced that its public schools would close for six weeks from Tuesday, March 17 through April 26.<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Public Schools to close Tuesday, with plans to reopen April 27 | website = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = March 13, 2020 | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/13/nation/mayor-walsh-address-coronavirus-outbreak-friday-evening/ | access-date = March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Baker ordered all schools in Massachusetts closed for three weeks from March 17 through April 7.<ref name=\"Becker\" /> On March 25, he extended the closing through May 4.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baker: schools to open no sooner than May 4th |url=https://www.westernmassnews.com/news/baker-schools-to-open-no-sooner-than-may/article_dfa2979c-6ed0-11ea-8d2f-9f9402f5677e.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |publisher=www.westernmassnews.com |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of the state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12, and [[Major League Baseball]] canceled the remainder of spring training. On March 16, after the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] recommended restricting events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, the major league baseball season was postponed indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back | title = Opening of regular season to be pushed back | first = Mark | last = Feinsand | website = [[MLB.com]] | date = March 16, 2020 | access-date = March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games | title = Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days | date = March 12, 2020 | website = ESPN.com | access-date = March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[National Hockey League]] season was suspended indefinitely.<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> Boston Celtics player [[Marcus Smart]] announced on March 18 that he had tested positive for COVID-19, having been tested five days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wcvb.com/article/boston-celtics-player-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-team-confirms/31792637|title=Celtics' Marcus Smart tests positive for coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|website=WCVB|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe [[2020 Boston Marathon]], which was originally scheduled to take place on April 20, was postponed to September 14. This was the first postponement of the Boston Marathon since it was first held in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.espn.com/olympics/story/_/id/28897435/boston-marathon-postponed-sept-14-amid-coronavirus-concerns|title = Boston Marathon postponed until Sept. 14 amid coronavirus concerns|website = ESPN|date = March 13, 2020|accessdate = March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] canceled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n* [https://www.mass.gov/resource/information-on-the-outbreak-of-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[Massachusetts Department of Public Health]]\n* {{cite web | title=COVID-19 Information and Resources | website=[[Massachusetts Department of Elementary and Secondary Education]] | url=http://www.doe.mass.edu/sfs/emergencyplan/covid19.html }}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:2020 in Massachusetts|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Health in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Qwerty325", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 13\u201314:fixed grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Massachusetts"}
{"title_page": "Blood Road (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Blood Road\n| director       = Nicholas Schrunk\n| producer       = Sandra Kuhn\n| writer         = Mark Anders\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Rebecca Rusch]]|Huyen Nguyen|Don Duvall}}\n| music          = [[Keith Kenniff]]\n| cinematography = Ryan Young\n| editing        = Emad Hashim\n| studio         = Red Bull Media House\n| released       = March 15, 2017\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = [[Laos]], [[Vietnam]], [[Cambodia]], [[United States]]\n| language       = English, Vietnamese, Lao\n}}\n'''''Blood Road''''' is a 2017 [[documentary film]] directed by Nicholas Schrunk<ref>{{Cite web|first=Tom|last=Roston|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/06/17/blood-road-movie-documentary/|title=A daughter chases her father's ghost down the Ho Chi Minh trail|date=2017-06-17|website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and produced by [[Red Bull]]. It stars endurance mountain biker [[Rebecca Rusch]], Vietnamese cyclist Huyen Nguyen and cartographer Don Duvall. The film chronicles the journey of Rebecca Rusch traversing over {{convert|1200|mi|km}} on bicycle along the [[Ho Chi Minh trail]] to the site where her father, a [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]] F-4 fighter pilot, was shot down in [[Laos]] 40 years earlier. It won numerous best of festival awards and a [[News & Documentary Emmy Award]] in 2017.<ref name=\"imdbawards\">{{Cite web|title=Blood Road \u2013 Awards|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6900092/awards|website=[[IMDb]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nThe film was produced over two years, starting with an initial scout trip to Laos in December, 2014 with principal photography happening over 28 days in February/March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Andrew|last=Fish|url=https://ascmag.com/articles/blood-road-emotional-journey|title=Blood Road: Emotional Journey|website=[[American Cinematographer]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The production team of six members, four of which were ex-professional athletes themselves, were limited to traversing on Honda CRF 250cc dual-sport motorcycles.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Debra|last=Kaufman|url=https://www.studiodaily.com/2017/07/shooting-blood-road-vietnam-cambodia-laos-6k-red-weapon-epic/|title=Shooting Blood Road in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos in 6K with the Red Weapon and Epic|date=2017-07-06|website=Studio Daily|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Two crew members were injured in motorcycle accidents, one suffering a shoulder injury and another, a ruptured achilles tendon. The core production team collectively rode over 24,000 miles on motorcycle over the course of production.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nelson|first=Chris|date=January 2018|title=Blood Road|url=|journal=Iron & Air|volume=030|pages=99-102|via=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Andrew Fish of American Cinematographer, the team used a unique combination of RED digital cinema cameras and Cooke anamorphic lenses to capture the film. Subsequent modifications were made to other smaller format cameras such as GoPro's to modify the lenses to fit the anamorphic profile. \n\n== Release ==\nThe film premiered at the Sun Valley Film Festival in January 2017 where it received the audience choice award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bicycling.com/news/a23567413/rebecca-rusch-blood-road-emmy/|title=This Cycling Documentary Just Won an Emmy|last=Yeager|first=Selene|date=2018-10-02|website=[[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> It was released nationally with a US tour March 15th, 2017. It has since been translated into several different languages, including Vietnamese.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{Cite web|title=Blood Road|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6900092|website=[[IMDb]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Reception ===\nBlood Road was released to generally positive to mixed reviews holding a 67% on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{Cite web|title=Blood Road (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blood_road|website=Rotten Tomatoes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> and a 6.7/10 on IMDB.com based on 307 reviews.<ref name=\"imdb\" /> Kimber Myers of [[Los Angeles Times|The ''Los Angeles Times'']] had a positive review calling it a \"moving experience for both its subjects and the audience\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-blood-road-review-20170622-story.html|first=Kimber|last=Myers|title=Review: American and Vietnamese cyclists find common ground in moving documentary 'Blood Road'|date=2017-06-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Bayo Olukotun of ''[[HuffPost|The Huffington Post]]'' described the filmmaking as \"purposeful storytelling that transcends the action sports subset\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/blood-road-documentary-combines-cycling-with-meaningful_b_5a1349d9e4b08b00ba6732f5|title='Blood Road' Documentary Combines Cycling with Meaningful Storytelling|last=Olukotun|first=Bayo|date=2017-11-21|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> However, John DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' while praising the on-screen graphics criticized the storytelling noting that \"American's emotional closure matters more than the lasting damage done in the countries she has gone to visit\".<ref>{{Cite web|first= John|last=DeFore|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/blood-road-1016457|title='Blood Road': Film Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThe film was awarded numerous best of festival and audience awards at the [[Banff Mountain Film Festival]], [[Bentonville Film Festival]], [https://www.breckfilmfest.org/ Breckenridge Film Festival] and [https://sunvalleyfilmfestival.org/ Sun Valley Film Festival]. It was nominated for one [[Sports Emmy Award]] in 2017 and two [[News & Documentary Emmy Award]]s in 2017, winning for Outstanding Graphic Design & Art Direction. Additionally, it won a Shorty Award for social good for its business to business partnership with demining efforts in Laos.<ref name=\"imdbawards\" />\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nThe filmmakers partnered with [[Mines Advisory Group|MAG]], an organization that assists people affected by landmines and unexploded ordnance, to donate proceeds from the film to demining efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/champion-mountain-biker-faces-her-toughest-challenge-clearing-bombs-laos-n847171|title=A champion mountain biker faces her toughest challenge: clearing bombs from Laos|first=Michael|last=Downey|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> [[Laos]] is the most heavily bombed country in the world with over two million tons of ordnance dropped over 580,000 bombing missions during the [[Vietnam War|Vietnam war]] which was featured in the film's story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legaciesofwar.org/about-laos/secret-war-laos/|title=Secret War in Laos|website=Legacies of War|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The film's lead, [[Rebecca Rusch]] continues to travel to Laos to promote the clean-up and raise money and awareness for the cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmbhof.org/rebecca_rusch/|title=Rebecca Rusch|publisher=[[Mountain Bike Hall of Fame]]|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Blood Road\n| director       = Nicholas Schrunk\n| producer       = Sandra Kuhn\n| writer         = Mark Anders\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Rebecca Rusch]]|Huyen Nguyen|Don Duvall}}\n| music          = [[Keith Kenniff]]\n| cinematography = Ryan Young\n| editing        = Emad Hashim\n| studio         = Red Bull Media House\n| released       = March 15, 2017\n| runtime        = 96 minutes\n| country        = [[Laos]], [[Vietnam]], [[Cambodia]], [[United States]]\n| language       = English, Vietnamese, Lao\n}}\n'''''Blood Road''''' is a 2017 [[documentary film]] directed by Nicholas Schrunk<ref>{{Cite web|first=Tom|last=Roston|url=https://www.salon.com/2017/06/17/blood-road-movie-documentary/|title=A daughter chases her father's ghost down the Ho Chi Minh trail|date=2017-06-17|website=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and produced by [[Red Bull]]. It stars endurance mountain biker [[Rebecca Rusch]], Vietnamese cyclist Huyen Nguyen and cartographer Don Duvall. The film chronicles the journey of Rebecca Rusch traversing over {{convert|1200|mi|km}} on bicycle along the [[Ho Chi Minh trail]] to the site where her father, a [[United States Air Force|US Air Force]] pilot, was shot down in [[Laos]] 40 years earlier. It won numerous best of festival awards and a [[News & Documentary Emmy Award]] in 2017.<ref name=\"imdbawards\">{{Cite web|title=Blood Road \u2013 Awards|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6900092/awards|website=[[IMDb]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nThe film was produced over two years, starting with an initial scout trip to Laos in December, 2014 with principal photography happening over 28 days in February/March 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Andrew|last=Fish|url=https://ascmag.com/articles/blood-road-emotional-journey|title=Blood Road: Emotional Journey|website=[[American Cinematographer]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> The production team of six members, four of which were ex-professional athletes themselves, were limited to traversing on Honda CRF 250cc dual-sport motorcycles.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Debra|last=Kaufman|url=https://www.studiodaily.com/2017/07/shooting-blood-road-vietnam-cambodia-laos-6k-red-weapon-epic/|title=Shooting Blood Road in Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos in 6K with the Red Weapon and Epic|date=2017-07-06|website=Studio Daily|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Two crew members were injured in motorcycle accidents, one suffering a shoulder injury and another, a ruptured achilles tendon. The core production team collectively rode over 24,000 miles on motorcycle over the course of production.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nelson|first=Chris|date=January 2018|title=Blood Road|url=|journal=Iron & Air|volume=030|pages=99-102|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film premiered at the Sun Valley Film Festival in January 2017 where it received the audience choice award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bicycling.com/news/a23567413/rebecca-rusch-blood-road-emmy/|title=This Cycling Documentary Just Won an Emmy|last=Yeager|first=Selene|date=2018-10-02|website=[[Bicycling (magazine)|Bicycling]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> It was released nationally with a US tour March 15th, 2017. It has since been translated into several different languages, including Vietnamese.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{Cite web|title=Blood Road|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6900092|website=[[IMDb]]|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Reception ===\nBlood Road was released to generally positive to mixed reviews holding a 67% on Rotten Tomatoes<ref>{{Cite web|title=Blood Road (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blood_road|website=Rotten Tomatoes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> and a 6.7/10 on IMDB.com based on 307 reviews.<ref name=\"imdb\" /> Kimber Myers of [[Los Angeles Times|The ''Los Angeles Times'']] had a positive review calling it a \"moving experience for both its subjects and the audience\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-blood-road-review-20170622-story.html|first=Kimber|last=Myers|title=Review: American and Vietnamese cyclists find common ground in moving documentary 'Blood Road'|date=2017-06-20|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> Bayo Olukotun of ''[[HuffPost|The Huffington Post]]'' described the filmmaking as \"purposeful storytelling that transcends the action sports subset\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/blood-road-documentary-combines-cycling-with-meaningful_b_5a1349d9e4b08b00ba6732f5|title='Blood Road' Documentary Combines Cycling with Meaningful Storytelling|last=Olukotun|first=Bayo|date=2017-11-21|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> However, John DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' while praising the on-screen graphics criticized the storytelling noting that \"American's emotional closure matters more than the lasting damage done in the countries she has gone to visit\".<ref>{{Cite web|first= John|last=DeFore|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/blood-road-1016457|title='Blood Road': Film Review|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\nThe film was awarded numerous best of festival and audience awards at the [[Banff Mountain Film Festival]], [[Bentonville Film Festival]], [https://www.breckfilmfest.org/ Breckenridge Film Festival] and [https://sunvalleyfilmfestival.org/ Sun Valley Film Festival]. It was nominated for one [[Sports Emmy Award]] in 2017 and two [[News & Documentary Emmy Award]]s in 2017, winning for Outstanding Graphic Design & Art Direction. Additionally, it won a Shorty Award for social good for its business to business partnership with demining efforts in Laos.<ref name=\"imdbawards\" />\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nThe filmmakers partnered with [[Mines Advisory Group|MAG]], an organization that assists people affected by landmines and unexploded ordnance, to donate proceeds from the film to demining efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/champion-mountain-biker-faces-her-toughest-challenge-clearing-bombs-laos-n847171|title=A champion mountain biker faces her toughest challenge: clearing bombs from Laos|first=Michael|last=Downey|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> [[Laos]] is the most heavily bombed country in the world with over two million tons of ordnance dropped over 580,000 bombing missions during the [[Vietnam War|Vietnam war]] which was featured in the film's story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://legaciesofwar.org/about-laos/secret-war-laos/|title=Secret War in Laos|website=Legacies of War|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The film's lead, [[Rebecca Rusch]] continues to travel to Laos to promote the clean-up and raise money and awareness for the cause.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmbhof.org/rebecca_rusch/|title=Rebecca Rusch|publisher=[[Mountain Bike Hall of Fame]]|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:2010s documentary films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n", "name_user": "Venicenothing", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blood_Road_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Portrait of a Man (Signorelli)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file= Luca Signorelli - Portrait of an Old Man - Gem\u00e4ldegalerie Berlin.jpg\n| title=Portrait of a Man\n| artist=[[Luca Signorelli]]\n| year=c. 1492\n| medium=[[Tempera]] on panel\n| height_metric=50\n| width_metric=32\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Berlin]]\n| museum=[[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin|Gem\u00e4ldegalerie]]\n}}\n\nThe '''''Portrait of a Man''''' is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] Renaissance artist [[Luca Signorelli]], dated to c. 1492 and housed in the [[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin]].\n==History==\nIn 1490\u20131492 Signorelli was in [[Volterra]], a city under [[Republic of Florence|Florentine]] control, under the patronage of the [[House of Medici]]. Here he painted an ''[[Annunciation (Signorelli)|Annunciation]]'', a ''[[Virgin Enthroned with Saints (Signorelli)|Virgin Enthroned with Saints]]'', a ''[[Circumcision of Christ (Signorelli)|Circumcision of Christ]]'' and, perhaps, this painting, attributed to that period for its stylistic resemblance with those works.\n\n==Description==\nThe painting portrays an aged man from three-quarters, characterized by white hair and rich bourgeois garments, perhaps those of  a jurist, including a red beret and jacket, and a black scarf. The style is inspired to the works of [[Hans Memling]] and to some by [[Domenico Ghirlandaio]].\n\nThe background houses Roman ruins and some naked men, inspired to those in [[Piero della Francesca]]'s ''[[Death of Adam (Piero della Francesca)|Death of Adam]]'' in San Francesco at [[Arezzo]], and are also in other works by Signorelli, such as the ''[[Madonna with Child and Naked Men]]'' of the [[Uffizi Gallery|Uffizi]].\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|first=Antonio|last=Paolucci|title=Pittori del Rinascimento|chapter=Luca Signorelli|location=Florence|publisher=Scala}}\n\n[[Category:1490s paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Luca Signorelli]]\n[[Category:Paintings in the Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin]]\n[[Category:15th-century portraits]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Artwork\n| image_file= Luca Signorelli - Portrait of an Old Man - Gem\u00e4ldegalerie Berlin.jpg\n| title=Portrait of a Man\n| artist=[[Luca Signorelli]]\n| year=c. 1492\n| medium=[[Tempera]] on panel\n| height_metric=50\n| width_metric=32\n| metric_unit=cm\n| imperial_unit=in\n| city=[[Berlin]]\n| museum=[[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin|Gem\u00e4ldegalerie]]\n}}\n\nThe '''''Portrait of a Man''''' is a painting by the [[Italy|Italian]] Renaissance artist [[Luca Signorelli]], dated to c. 1492 and housed in the [[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin]].\n==History==\nIn 1490-1492 Signorelli was in [[Volterra]], a city under [[Republic of Florence|Florentine]] control, under the patronage of the [[House of Medici]]. Here he painted an ''[[Annunciation (Signorelli)|Annunciation]]'', a ''[[Virgin Enthroned with Saints (Signorelli)|Virgin Enthroned with Saints]]'', a ''[[Circumcision of Christ (Signorelli)|Circumcision of Christ]]'' and, perhaps, this painting, attributed to that period for its stylistic resemblance with those works.\n\n==Description==\nThe painting portrays an aged man from three-quarters, characterized by white hair and rich bourgeois garments, perhaps those of  a jurist, including a red beret and jacket, and a black scarf. The style is inspired to the works of [[Hans Memling]] and to some by [[Domenico Ghirlandaio]].\n\nThe background houses Roman ruins and some naked men, inspired to those in [[Piero della Francesca]]'s ''[[Death of Adam (Piero della Francesca)|Death of Adam]]'' in San Francesco at [[Arezzo]], and are also in other works by Signorelli, such as the ''[[Madonna with Child and Naked Men]]'' of the [[Uffizi Gallery|Uffizi]].\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|first=Antonio|last=Paolucci|title=Pittori del Rinascimento|chapter=Luca Signorelli|location=Florence|publisher=Scala}}\n\n[[Category:1490s paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Luca Signorelli]]\n[[Category:Paintings in the Gem\u00e4ldegalerie, Berlin]]\n[[Category:15th-century portraits]]\n", "name_user": "Ham II", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portrait_of_a_Man_(Signorelli)"}
{"title_page": "Zykovo, Kaduysky District, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zykovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0417\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|16|N|37|21|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zykovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 12 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 25&nbsp;km, to Boylovo is 6&nbsp;km. Marlykovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zykovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0417\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|16|N|37|21|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zykovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u044b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 12 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 25&nbsp;km, to Boylovo is 6&nbsp;km. Marlykovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zykovo,_Kaduysky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Victoriano Huerta", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican military officer and 35th President of Mexico}}\n{{Main|Mexican Revolution}}\n{{Distinguish|Adolfo de la Huerta}}\n{{Spanish name|Huerta|M\u00e1rquez}}\n{{Infobox president\n| name=Victoriano Huerta\n| nationality=Mexican\n| image=Victoriano Huerta.(cropped).jpg\n| order         = 35th\n| office        = President of Mexico\n| term_start    = 19 February 1913\n| term_end      = 15 July 1914\n| predecessor   = [[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]]\n| successor     = [[Francisco S. Carvajal]]\n| office2       = Secretary of the Interior of Mexico\n| term2         = 19 February 1913\n| predecessor2  = [[Rafael Lorenzo Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n| successor2    = [[Alberto Garc\u00eda Granados]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1850|12|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = Agua Gorda, [[Colotl\u00e1n]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1916|1|13|1850|12|22|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[El Paso, Texas]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Evergreen Cemetery (El Paso, Texas)\n| spouse        = Emilia \u00c1guila\n| party         = [[Independent politician|None]]\n| vicepresident =\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Mexico}}\n| branch        = {{army|Mexico}}\n| serviceyears  = 1877-1907\n| rank          = General\n| unit          =\n}}\n\n'''Jos\u00e9 Victoriano Huerta M\u00e1rquez''' ({{IPA-es|bikto\u02c8\u027ejano \u02c8we\u027eta}}; 22 December 1850{{efn|There is dispute about the date of birth and the maternal surname of Victoriano Huerta. Many sources, including ''Gobernantes de M\u00e9xico'' by Fernando Orozco Linares give a birthdate of 23 March 1854 and a maternal surname of Ortega. However, the parish register of Colotl\u00e1n, Jalisco as filmed by the [[Genealogical Society of Utah]] on film 0443681 v. 24 p. 237 shows a baptism date of 23 December 1850, a birth date of 22 December 1850 and his mother's name as Mar\u00eda L\u00e1zara del Refugio M\u00e1rquez. The marriage record dated 21 November 1880 at Santa Veracruz parrish in Mexico City as filmed by the Genealogical Society of Utah on film 0035853 confirms his mother's name as: Del Refugio M\u00e1rquez.}} \u2013 13 January 1916) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] military officer and 35th [[President of Mexico]], who came to power by coup.\n\nAfter a military career under President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], Huerta became a high-ranking officer under democratically-elected President [[Francisco I. Madero]] during the first phase of the [[Mexican Revolution]]. In February 1913 Huerta led a conspiracy against Madero, who entrusted him to control a minor revolt in Mexico City. The [[Ten Tragic Days]] saw the forced resignation of Madero and his vice president and their murders. The coup was backed by Britain, France, and Germany as well the U.S. under the [[William Howard Taft|Taft Administration]] but the succeeding [[Woodrow Wilson|Wilson administration]] refused to recognize the new regime and allowed arms sales to rebel forces.  Britain, France, and Germany did recognize the regime, but withdrew further support when revolutionary forces showed success against the regime and continued support threatened their relationship with the U.S. Huerta was forced to resign in July 1914 and flee the country with the aid of Germany, only 17 months into his presidency, after the federal army collapsed. While attempting to intrigue with German spies in the U.S. during [[World War I]] (1914-1918), Huerta was arrested in 1915 and died in U.S. custody.\n\nHis supporters were known as ''Huertistas'' during the Mexican Revolution. He is still vilified by modern-day Mexicans, who generally refer to him as ''El Chacal'' (\"The Jackal\") or ''El Usurpador'' (\"The Usurper\").<ref>McCartney, Laton. ''The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country'', Random House, Inc., 2008, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdHi6ilyqk8C&pg=RA1-PA1900&dq=Victoriano+Huerta+Jackal&cd=1#v=onepage&q=Victoriano%20Huerta%20Jackal&f=false p. 1901].</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVictoriano Huerta was born in the settlement of Agua Gorda within the municipality of [[Colotl\u00e1n|Colotl\u00e1n, Jalisco]], son of Jes\u00fas Huerta and Mar\u00eda L\u00e1zara del Refugio M\u00e1rquez. He identified himself as [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico|indigenous]], and both his parents are reported to have been ethnically [[Huichol people|Huichol]], although his father is said to have been [[Mestizo]].<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\">Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, p. 655, Chicago: Fitzroy Dearborn 1997.</ref> Huerta learned to read and write at a school run by the local priest, making him one of the relatively few literate people in Colotl\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, George \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pages 136-145 from ''The Americas'', Volume 21, No. 2 October  1964 page 136.</ref> He had decided upon a military career early on as the only way of escaping the poverty of Colotl\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 136.</ref> In 1869 he was employed by visiting Gen. [[Donato Guerra]] to serve as his personal secretary.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.136.</ref>  In that role he distinguished himself and, with Gen. Guerra's support, gained admission to the Mexican National Military Academy ([[Heroic Military Academy (Mexico)|Heroico Colegio Militar]]) at [[Chapultepec]] in [[Mexico City]] in 1872.<ref name=\"MexEncyclo\">\n{{cite book\n|last = Coerver\n|first = Don M.\n|title = Mexico: An Encyclopedia of Contemporary Culture and History\n|publisher = ABC-CLIO\n|year = 2004\n|isbn = 1-57607-132-4\n}}</ref> As a cadet, Huerta excelled at math, leading him to specialize in artillery and topography.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.137.</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n{{External Timeline|Template:Timeline of the Mexican Revolution|Timeline of the Mexican Revolution}}\n[[File:V_Huerta.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Victoriano Huerta (1850-1916), Mexican dictator (1913-1914).]]\n\nUpon graduating from the military academy in 1877, Huerta was commissioned into the Corps of Engineers.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> After entering the army as a lieutenant in the engineers in 1877, he was put in charge of improving the Loreto and Guadalupe forts in Puebla and the castle of Perote in Veracruz.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\".  ''The Americas'', Volume 21, No. 2 October 1964 p. 137.</ref> In January 1879 he was promoted to captain and assigned to the staff of the 4th Division in Guadalajara, in charge of engineering.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 136-145 </ref> The commander of the 4th Division was [[Manuel Gonz\u00e1lez Flores|Gen. Manuel Gonz\u00e1lez]], a close associate of President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]] and former president of Mexico (1880-84).<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 136-145</ref>  In the interim, Huerta's career prospered thanks to the patronage of Gonz\u00e1lez.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\", pp. 136-45.</ref> In Mexico City, he married Emilia \u00c1guila Moya, whom he met in Veracruz, on 21 November 1880.<ref>Genealogical Society of Utah, Film 0035853</ref> The marriage produced 11 children. The names of his children surviving him in 1916 were Jorge, Mar\u00eda Elisa, Victor, Luz, Elena, Dagoberto, Eva and Celia.<ref>''El Paso Times'' obituary</ref> Huerta participated in the \"pacification campaigns\" in [[Tepic]] and [[Sinaloa]], where he distinguished himself in combat.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> He was known for ensuring that his men always got paid, often resorting to finding the money in ruthless ways.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 138.</ref> Following a complaint from the Catholic Church that Huerta had plundered a church to sell off its gold and silver to pay his men, Huerta justified his actions on the grounds that \"Mexico can do without her priests, but cannot do without her soldiers\".<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.138.</ref> On another occasion, following a complaint from a bank that he emptied out one of its branches at gunpoint to get money to pay his men, Huerta pointed out he left a receipt and would pay back the bank what he had stolen when he received the necessary funds from Mexico City.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.138.</ref> Huerta then spent nine years of his military career undertaking [[topography|topographic]] studies in the states of [[Puebla]] and [[Veracruz]]. He traveled extensively to all parts of Mexico in this position.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> French cultural influence was very strong in 19th-century Mexico, and Huerta's hero was [[Napoleon]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.139.</ref> He supported Gen. D\u00edaz as the closest approximation to his Napoleonic ideal, believing that Mexico needed a \"strongman\" to prosper.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.139.</ref>     \n\nBy 1890 Huerta had reached the rank of Colonel of Engineers.  From 1890-95 Huerta lived in Mexico City, becoming a regular visitor to the presidential residence at [[Chapultepec Castle]], and was seen as part of D\u00edaz's \"court\".<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\", p.139.</ref> Through Huerta was well liked at the Chapultepec Castle, acquiring the persona of a trim, efficient office who was stern to his subordinates while displaying a courtly, polished manner towards his superiors, he began to suffer from severe insomnia and began drinking heavily during this time.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 139.</ref> In January 1895 he commanded a battalion of infantry against a rebellion in Guerrero led by Gen. [[Canuto Neri]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 140.</ref> The rebellion was ended when D\u00edaz brokered a deal with Neri, who surrendered in exchange for a promise to remove the unpopular state governor.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.140.</ref> Huerta confirmed his reputation for ruthlessness by refusing to take prisoners and continuing to attack the followers of Neri even after D\u00edaz had signed a ceasefire.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 140.</ref> In December 1900 Huerta commanded a successful military campaign against [[Yaqui]] Indians in [[Sonora]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 140-141.</ref> During the near-genocidal campaign against the Yaqui, Huerta was more concerned with mapping out the terrain of Sonora, but at times he commanded forces in the field against the Yaqui.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 140-141.</ref> From 12 April-8 September 1901 Huerta put down a rebellion in Guerrero, completely \"pacifying\" the state.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.141.</ref> In May 1901 he was promoted to the rank of general.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 141.</ref> In 1901-02 he suppressed a [[Maya peoples|Maya]]' rising in [[Yucat\u00e1n]]. He commanded about 500 men in his campaign against the Maya, starting in October 1901, and fought 79 different actions over the course of 39 days.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 141.</ref> Huerta was then promoted to Brigadier General and awarded the Medal of Military Merit <ref name=\"MexEncyclo\"/> In May 1902 he was promoted commander of federal army forces in Yucat\u00e1n, and in October 1902 he reported to D\u00edaz that he had \"pacified\" the Yucat\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.142.</ref> During the campaign in Yucat\u00e1n he became increasingly dependent on alcohol to continue functioning. His health began to decline, and perhaps because of his heavy drinking he complained he could not go outside in the sunshine without wearing sunglasses, and he suffered bouts of uncontrollable nervous shaking. His decaying teeth caused him much pain.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.142.</ref> In August 1903 he was appointed to head a committee tasked with reforming the uniforms of the federal army.<ref>Joseph Hefter, page 80 ''Cronica del Traje Militar en Mexico del Siglo XVI al XX'', ''Artes de Mexico No. 102, 1968''</ref> In 1907 he retired from the army on grounds of ill health, having developed cataracts while serving in the southern jungles. He then applied his technical training by taking up the position of Head of Public Works in [[Monterrey]] and planning a new street layout for the city.\n\n==Mexican Revolution under Madero==\n[[File:Huerta Madero Villa.jpg|thumb|General Huerta (left) with [[Emilio Madero]], Pres. Madero's brother, and [[Pancho Villa]], 1912.]]\nOn the eve of the 1910 [[Mexican Revolution|Revolution]] against the long-established D\u00edaz regime, Huerta was teaching mathematics in Mexico City. He applied successfully to rejoin the army with his former rank and was accepted. He did not play a major role in the early stages of the Revolution that led to the resignation of D\u00edaz, although he commanded the military escort that gave D\u00edaz safe conduct into exile in May 1911. During the interim presidency of [[Francisco Le\u00f3n de la Barra]] following the resignation of D\u00edaz and the election of [[Francisco I. Madero]] in November 1911, General Huerta  carried out a campaign in Morelos, attempting to crush the rebellion led by [[Emilio Zapata]]. Huerta's forces burned villages supporting the rebellion and attacked their residents. These actions frustrated Madero's later attempts to placate those rebels.<ref>Hart, John Mason. ''Revolutionary Mexico'', p. 252.</ref> Huerta had a record of opposing revolutionaries and intrigues with Madero's enemies. Huerta's actions in Morelos forced a break between Emiliano Zapata and Madero, who was later to rebel against Madero immediately after his November 1911 election.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that revolutionary forces supporting [[Francisco I. Madero]] had forced D\u00edaz's resignation, Madero ordered them demobilized and retained the [[Federal Army|Mexican Federal Army]] they had just defeated.  Huerta pledged allegiance to President Madero, and carried out Madero's orders to crush anti-Madero revolts by rebel generals such as [[Pascual Orozco]], who had helped topple D\u00edaz and then rebelled against his regime.  In the Orozco rebellion, Huerta saw the opportunity to eliminate revolutionary general Pancho Villa, who was also attempting to suppress the revolt. Accused of stealing a horse, Villa then faced execution by Huerta without trial.  Only Madero's last minute intervention saved the life of one of his most effective generals.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref> \n\nOrozco's rebellion was a major threat to the Madero government, since he had standing as a revolutionary and commanded significant forces. Madero sent Huerta to crush the rebellion. He had at his command troops of the Mexican Federal Army and these were joined by irregulars led by the revolutionary leader [[Pancho Villa]], at Torre\u00f3n in April 1912. Huerta offered Orozco's supporters (''Orozquistas'') amnesty, which might have weakened their forces already suffering from lack of money and arms. Huerta's forces defeated Orozco's at Rellano in May 1912. With that victory Huerta \"had suddenly become a military hero with a national reputation.\"<ref>Meyer, Michael C. ''Mexican Rebel: Pascual Orozco and the Mexican Revolution, 1910-1915''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1967, p. 82.</ref> \n\n==Huerta and Madero's overthrow==\n{{Main|Ten Tragic Days}}\nAs Madero lost support and as internal and external groups plotted to remove him from the presidency, Huerta secretly joined the conspiracy.  The coup d'etat that toppled Madero February 1913, known in Mexican history as the [[Ten Tragic Days]], was a conspiracy of Porfirio D\u00edaz's nephew, General F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz, General Bernardo Reyes, and General Madrag\u00f3n.  The plotters attempted to draw in Huerta in January, but Huerta waited for a better incentive to join, since F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz expected to be the successor to Madero. The first day of the coup, February 9, General Reyes died in battle and General Lauro Villar, the commander of Madero's forces in Mexico City, was wounded.<ref>{{cite book|first=Alan|last=Knight|page=[https://archive.org/details/mexicanrevolutio0000knig/page/483 483]|title=The Mexican Revolution. Volume 1. Porfirians, Liberals and Peasants|isbn=0-8032-7770-9|year=1990|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicanrevolutio0000knig/page/483}}</ref> Madero appointed Huerta in his stead. According to historian [[Friedrich Katz]], \"It was a decision for which [Madero] would pay with his life.\"<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref> Having secured that key position, Huerta reopened negotiations with the plotters and joined them in secret. His task was to undermine Madero militarily without betraying his own complicity and began military operations that weakened Madero's forces.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War'', p. 97.</ref> \n[[United States Ambassador to Mexico]] [[Henry Lane Wilson]],<ref name=\"McLynn\">\n{{cite book\n|first = Frank\n|last = McLynn\n|title = Villa and Zapata\n|publisher = Carroll & Graf \n|year = 2002P\n|isbn = 0-7867-1088-8\n|url-access = registration\n|url = https://archive.org/details/villazapata00fran\n}}</ref> was an active participant in the plot to overthrow Madero. Ambassador Wilson believed that Huerta would not have staged a coup had the United States not assured them that it would recognize the new regime.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 98.</ref>   Following a confused few days of fighting in Mexico City between loyalist and rebel factions of the army, Huerta had Madero and vice-president [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]] seized and briefly imprisoned on 18 February 1913 in the [[National Palace (Mexico)|National Palace]]. The conspirators then met at the US Embassy to sign ''El Pacto de la Embajada'' (The Embassy Pact), which provided for the exile of Madero and Pino Su\u00e1rez and Huerta's takeover of the Mexican government.<ref name=revs>Richards, Michael D. ''Revolutions in world history'', Routledge, 2004, [https://archive.org/details/revolutionsinwor0000rich/page/26 p. 26].</ref>\n\n==''La Mano Dura'': Presidency of Mexico==\n[[Image:Victoriano Huerta y su gabinete.tif|thumb|right|Victoriano Huerta and his cabinet]]\nTo give the coup the appearance of legitimacy, Huerta had [[foreign minister]] [[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]] assume the presidency; under the [[1857 Constitution of Mexico]], the foreign minister stood third in line for the presidency behind the Vice President and [[Attorney General of Mexico|Attorney General]]; Madero's attorney general had also been ousted in the coup. Lascur\u00e1in then appointed Huerta as [[Secretariat of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]], making him next in line for the presidency. After less than an hour in office (some sources say as little as 15 minutes), Lascur\u00e1in resigned, handing the presidency to Huerta. At a late-night special session of Congress surrounded by Huerta's troops, the legislators endorsed his assumption of power. Four days later Madero and Pino Su\u00e1rez were taken from the National Palace to prison at night and shot by officers of the [[rurales]] (federal police), who were assumed to be acting on Huerta's orders. \n\nThe Huerta government was promptly recognized by all the western European governments, but the outgoing US administration of [[William Howard Taft]] refused to recognize the new government, as a way of pressuring Mexico to end the Chamizal border dispute in favor of the US, with the plan being to trade recognition for settling the dispute on American terms.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 68.</ref> Newly inaugurated U.S. president [[Woodrow Wilson]] had a general bias in favor of liberal democracy and had distaste for Gen. Huerta, who had come to power by coup and was implicated in the murder of Madero, but was initially open to recognizing Huerta provided that he could \"win\" an election that would give him a democratic veneer.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 69.</ref> F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz and the rest of the conservative leaders had seen Huerta as a transitional leader and pressed for early elections, which they expected to be won by Diaz on a Catholic conservative platform, and were rudely surprised when they discovered Huerta wanted to keep the presidency for himself.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 64.</ref> \n[[Image:Huerta y Orozco.jpg|right|thumb|Victoriano Huerta (left) and [[Pascual Orozco]] (right).]]\nHuerta moved quickly to consolidate power within Mexico with the support of state governors.<ref>Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, p. 656.</ref> Huerta sought support from Pascual Orozco, whose rebellion against Madero Huerta had been in charge of suppressing. Orozco still held the leadership of significant forces in Chihuahua and potentially in Durango, so gaining his support was important to Huerta. Orozco had rebelled against Madero and Huerta had overthrown him, so there was the possibility of gaining his support. During a meeting of representatives of Huerta's government and Orozco's forces, Orozco laid out his terms for supporting Huerta. He sought recognition of his soldiers' service to the overthrown of Madero and pay; pensions and care of soldiers' widows and orphans, agrarian reforms, government payment of Orozquista debts that financed the campaign against Madero, and employment of Orozquistas as ''rurales''. Huerta agreed to the terms, and Orozco threw his support to Huerta on 27 February 1913.<ref>Meyer, ''Pascual Orozco'', pp. 97-98.</ref> Orozco sought to persuade Emiliano Zapata to make peace with Huerta regime. Zapata had held Orozco in high esteem as a fellow revolutionary who had rejected the Madero regime.  However, for Zapata, Orozco's support of Huerta was anathema,saying \"Huerta represents the defection of the army. You represent the defection of the Revolution.\"<ref>quoted in Meyer, ''Pascual Orozco'', p. 101.</ref>\n\nHuerta attempted to build further support for his government, and the urban working class in Mexico City made important gains before being suppressed. In particular, the leftist [[Casa del Obrero Mundial]] (House of the World Worker). The Casa organized demonstrations and strikes, which the Huerta regime initially tolerated. But then the government cracked down, arresting and deporting some leaders, and destroying the Casa's headquarters.<ref>Hart, John Mason. ''Revolutionary Mexico: The Coming Process of the Mexican Revolution''. Berkeley: University of California Press 1987, pp. 271-72.</ref> Huerta also sought to diffuse agrarian agitation, which fueled the rebellion in Morelos led by Emiliano Zapata. The most vocal intellectual in favor of land reform was [[Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez]], whose 1909 publication ''Los grandes problemas nacionales'' (The Great National Problems) focused on inequality of land tenure. Molina Enr\u00edquez joined the Huerta government heading the Department of Labor.  He had denounced the overthrow of Madero, but \"initially saw in the Huerta regime the political formula he believed Mexico required: a strong military leader capable of imposing the social reforms Mexico needed to benefit the masses.\" However, despite internal support in the Huerta regime for reform, Huerta increasingly embraced militarization and Molina Enr\u00edquez resigned.<ref>Shadle, Stanley F. ''Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez: Mexican Land Reformer of the Revolutionary Era''. Tucson: University of Arizona Press 1994, pp. 62-63.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Desconocimiento de Victoriano Huerta como Jefe del Poder Ejecutivo de la Rep\u00fablica.tif|thumb|right|Venustiano Carranza disavows Victoriano Huerta's claim to the presidency]]\n\nChihuahua Gov. [[Abraham Gonz\u00e1lez (governor)|Abraham Gonz\u00e1lez]] refused and Huerta had him arrested and murdered in March 1913.\nThe most important challenge from a state governor was by [[Venustiano Carranza]], governor of Coahuila, who drafted the [[Plan of Guadalupe]], calling for the creation of a [[Constitutionalist Army]] (evoking the 1857 Liberal Constitution) to oust the usurper Huerta and restore constitutional government. Supporters of Carranza's plan included [[Emiliano Zapata]], who nonetheless remained loyal to his own [[Plan de Ayala]]; northern revolutionary [[Francisco \"Pancho\" Villa]]; and [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n]]. However, former revolutionary Gen. [[Pascual Orozco]], whom Huerta fought when serving President Madero, now joined with Huerta as a counter-revolutionary. Four Deputies were executed over the summer of 1913 for criticizing the Huerta regime.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 67.</ref> One deputy was arrested by Mexico City police as he was delivering a speech denouncing Huerta at a rally and taken out to the countryside, where he was \"shot while trying to escape\".<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.67.</ref> Lacking popular legitimacy, Huerta chose to turn the refusal of the US to recognize his government as an example of American \"interference\" in Mexico's internal affairs, organizing anti-American demonstrations in the summer of 1913 with the hope of gaining some popular support.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 71.</ref>    \n\nBritish historian [[Alan Knight (historian)|Alan Knight]] wrote about Huerta: \"The consistent thread which ran through the Huerta regime, from start to finish, was militarisation: the growth and reliance on the Federal Army, the military takeover of public offices, the preference for military over political solutions, the militarisation of society in general\".<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1990 page 62.</ref> Huerta \"came very close to converting Mexico into the most completely militaristic state in the world.\"<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p. 62.</ref> Huerta's stated goal was a return to the \"order\" of the [[Porfiriato]], but his methods were unlike those of Diaz, who had shown a talent for compromise and diplomacy; seeking support from and playing off regional elites, using not only army officers but also technocrats, former guerrilla leaders, ''[[cacique]]s'' and provincial elites to support his regime.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 63.</ref> By contrast, Huerta relied entirely upon the army for support, giving officers all of the key jobs, regardless of their talents, as Huerta sought to rule with ''La Mano Dura'' (\"The Iron Hand\"), believing only in military solutions to all problems.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p. 63.</ref> For this reason, Huerta during his short time as President was the object of far more hatred than Diaz ever was; even the Zapatistas had a certain respect for Diaz as a patriarchal leader who had enough sense to finally leave with dignity in 1911, whereas Huerta was seen as a thuggish soldier who had Madero murdered and sought to terrorize the nation into submission.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 63.</ref> Huerta disliked cabinet meetings, ordered his ministers about as if they were non-commissioned officers and displayed in general a highly autocratic style.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 64.</ref> \n\nHuerta established a harsh military dictatorship.<ref>Richmond, \"Victoriano Huerta\", p. 657.</ref> [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] Woodrow Wilson became hostile to the Huerta administration, recalled ambassador [[Henry Lane Wilson]] and demanded Huerta step aside for democratic elections. In August 1913 Wilson imposed an arms embargo on Mexico, forcing Huerta to turn to Europe and Japan to buy arms.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 72.</ref> Reflecting the general disenchantment with Huerta's \"iron hand\" policies, a prominent conservative, Sen. [[Belisario Dom\u00ednguez]] of Chiapas, handed out copies of a speech he did not dare to deliver in the Senate, accusing Huerta of starting the civil war which he was losing, of wanting \"to cover the land with corpses . . . rather than abandon power\" and called for Congress to impeach Huerta before Mexico was plunged into the abyss.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'' 66.</ref> Dom\u00ednguez knew he was risking his life by speaking out and sent his wife and children out of Mexico before handing out copies of his speech.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.66.</ref> Dom\u00ednguez was arrested by two policemen plus Huerta's son and son-in-law, taken to a cemetery where he was \"shot while trying to escape\" for speaking out against the President. His body was dumped into the grave that his killers had already dug for him.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'', page 67.</ref> On 10 October 1913, when Congress announced it was opening an investigation of the disappearance of Sen. Dom\u00ednguez, who had last been seen several days before being forced into a police car, Huerta sent his soldiers in to shut down Congress in session and arrested 110 Senators and Deputies, of whom 74 were charged with high treason and put to work building a bullfighting arena.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.75.</ref> \n\nThe federal army Huerta took over in February 1913 numbered between 45,000-50,000 men. Huerta continued to increase the strength of the army, issuing a degree for conscripting 150,000 men in October 1913; another degree for conscripting 200,000 men in January 1914 and one for a quarter of million men in March 1914. These figures were never achieved as many men fled to fight for the Constitutionalists rather than Huerta.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 77.</ref> Together with an increase in the number of the paramilitary ''[[rurales]]'' mounted police force and the state militias, Huerta had approximately 300,000 men, or about 4% of the population, fighting for him by early 1914.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p.77.</ref> Faced with widespread reluctance to serve Huerta had to resort to the ''leva'', as vagrants, criminals, captured rebels, political prisoners and sometimes just men on the streets were rounded up to serve in the Federal Army.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 77.</ref> In Veracruz workers getting off the night shift at factories were rounded up in a ''leva'' (forced conscription), while in Mexico City poor men going to hospitals were rounded up in the ''leva''.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.77.</ref> As Indians were felt to be particularly docile and submissive to whites, the ''leva'' was applied especially heavily in the southern Mexico, where the majority of the people were Indians. Thousands of Juchiteco and Maya Indians were rounded up to fight a war in the north of Mexico that they felt did not concern them.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' page 78.</ref> A visitor to M\u00e9rida in the Yucat\u00e1n wrote of \"heart-breaking\" scenes as hundreds of Maya Indians said goodbye to their wives as they were forced to board a train while in chains.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 78.</ref> \n\nAs the men rounded up in the ''leva'' proved to be poor soldiers, prone to desertion and mutiny, Huerta had to follow a defensive strategy of keeping the army concentrated in large towns, since his soldiers in the field would either desert or go over to the rebels.<ref>Knight,  ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 79.</ref> Throughout the civil war of 1913-14 the Constitutionalists fought with a ferocity and courage that the federal army never managed.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 79.</ref> In Yucat\u00e1n about 70% of the army were men conscripted from the prisons, while one \"volunteer\" battalion consisted of captured Yaqui Indians.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 79.</ref> In October 1913, in the town of Tlalnepantla, the army's 9th Regiment, which was said to have been \"crazed with alcohol and marijuana\", mutinied, murdered their officers and went over to the rebels.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'',  p. 79.</ref> To provide volunteers, Huerta turned to Mexican nationalism and anti-Americanism in the fall of 1913, running spurious stories in the press warning of an imminent American invasion and asking for patriotic men to step up to defend Mexico.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', pp. 79-80.</ref> The campaign attracted some volunteers from the lower middle class, through they were usually disillusioned when they learned that they were going to fight other Mexicans, not the Americans.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.80.</ref> In rural Mexico a sense of Mexican nationalism barely existed at this time among the ''campesinos''. Mexico was an abstract entity that meant nothing, and most ''campesinos'' were primarily loyal to their own villages, the ''patria chicas''.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 80.</ref> Huerta's patriotic campaign was a complete failure in the countryside.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.80.</ref> The other source of volunteers was to allow wealthy landlords to raise private armies under the guise of the state militias, but few ''peons'' wanted to fight, let alone die, for Gen. Huerta, since the Constitutionalists were promising land reform.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', pp. 81-82.</ref>\n\nWhen Huerta refused to call elections, and with the situation further exacerbated by the [[Tampico Affair]], President Wilson landed US troops to [[United States occupation of Veracruz|occupy]] Mexico's most important seaport, [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]].\n\nAfter the federal army was repeatedly defeated in battle by Constitutionalist generals [[Alvaro Obreg\u00f3n]] and Pancho Villa, climaxing in the [[Battle of Zacatecas (1914)|Battle of Zacatecas]], Huerta bowed to internal and external pressure and resigned the presidency on 15 July 1914.<ref>[https://www.biografiacortade.com/victoriano-huerta-marquez/ \"Huerta's ] [https://archive.org/stream/independen79v80newy#page/n96/mode/1up Final Message to the Mexican Congress\"]. ''The Independent''. July 27, 1914. Retrieved 24 July 2012.</ref>\n\n==Exile, late life and death==\n[[Image:Delgado Huerta Ratner.jpg|right|thumb|Jos\u00e9 C. Delgado, Victoriano Huerta and Abraham F. Ratner.]]\nHuerta went into exile, first traveling to [[Kingston, Jamaica]], aboard the German cruiser [[SMS Dresden (1907)|SMS ''Dresden'']].<ref name=war>Russell, Thomas Herbert. ''America's War for Humanity'', BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SGGuoj3JRsC&pg=PA500 p. 500].</ref> From there he moved to the [[UK]], then [[Spain]], and arrived in the US in April 1915.\n\nWhile in the US he negotiated with Capt. [[Franz von Rintelen]] of German Navy Intelligence for money to purchase weapons and arrange [[U-boat]] landings to provide support, while offering (perhaps as a bargaining chip) to make war on the US, which Germany hoped would end munitions supplies to the Allies.<ref>Tuchman, Barbara W. ''The Zimmermann Telegram'' (New York: NEL Mentor, 1967), pp. 73-4.</ref> Their meetings, held at the [[Hotel Manhattan|Manhattan Hotel]] (as well as another New York hotel, \"probably the Holland House\" at Fifth Avenue and 30th Street)<ref name=\"Tuchman, p.73\">Tuchman, p. 73.</ref>, were observed by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]]men, and von Rintelen's telephone conversations were routinely intercepted and recorded.<ref name=\"Tuchman, p.73\"/>\n\nHuerta traveled from New York by train to [[Newman, New Mexico|Newman]], [[New Mexico]] (25 miles from the border), where he was to be met by Gen. [[Pascual Orozco]] and some well-armed Mexican supporters. However, a US Army colonel with 25 soldiers and two deputy US marshals intervened and arrested him as he left the train, on a charge of sedition.<ref>Blum, Howard. ''Dark Invasion: 1915 - Germany's Secret War'', Harper, 2014, p. 228.</ref> The German-initiated plan for Huerta to regain the Mexican presidency through a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] was foiled. After some time in a US Army prison at [[Fort Bliss]] he was released on bail, but remained under house arrest due to risk of flight to Mexico. A day after, he attended a dinner at Fort Bliss. Later he was returned to jail, and while so confined died, perhaps of [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]]. While the main symptom was [[jaundice|yellow jaundice]], poisoning by the US was widely suspected.<ref name=Lee>Stacy, Lee. ''Mexico and the United States'', Marshall Cavendish, 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DSzyMGh8pNwC&pg=PA405 p. 405].</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the historiography of Mexico, Victoriano Huerta is the \"demon\" of the Mexican Revolution, against whom all others are measured.<ref>LaFrance, David. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Latin American History and Culture'', vol. 3, p. 216. New  York: Charles Scribner's Sons 1996</ref>  Diverse factions and interests in Mexico came together against the Huerta regime, including the Zapatistas in Morelos and the Constitutionalists in northern Mexico under Venustiano Carranza.  Once Huerta was ousted, the loose coalition fell apart and Mexico was plunged into a civil war between the winners. Germany and Great Britain's backing of Huerta weakened their influence in Mexico while the hostility of the United States to the regime increased it. Although U.S. business interests had hoped that President Wilson would recognize the Huerta government, they realized he would not and began aligning themselves with different revolutionary factions.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 566.</ref> One historian argues that Huerta's regime was not as conservative or reactionary as portrayed, arguing that he did not attempt to \"reincarnate\" the Age of D\u00edaz. \"Huerta and his advisors both realized the days of D\u00edaz were gone forever. They did not attempt to stem the new energies and forces unleashed in 1910; rather they attempted to moderate them.\"<ref>Meyer, Michael C. ''Huerta: A Political Portrait''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1972, pp. 369-70</ref> In general, however, his regime is seen as a repudiation of democracy and Huerta himself an iron-fisted authoritarian. Despite efforts in Mexico to redress the exclusion of Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez from the pantheon of Mexican revolutionaries, since he is considered the intellectual father of the Article 27 of the 1917 Mexican Constitution empowering the state to implement [[land reform in Mexico|land reform]] and expropriate private owners of resources like oil. Molina Enr\u00edquez was tainted by his service in the Huerta government.<ref>Shadle, ''Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez'', p.4.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nHuerta has been portrayed or referenced in any number of movies dealing with the Mexican Revolution, including ''[[The Wild Bunch]]'', ''[[Duck, You Sucker!]]'' and ''[[And Starring Pancho Villa as Himself]]''.\n\nIn the 1952 film ''[[Viva Zapata!]]'', starring [[Marlon Brando]] as [[Emiliano Zapata]], Huerta is portrayed by [[Frank Silvera]].\n\nIn the 1968 film ''[[Villa Rides]]'', Huerta was played by [[Herbert Lom]].\n\nIn the novel ''The Friends of Pancho Villa'' (1996), by [[James Carlos Blake]], Huerta is a major character.\n\nBoth Victoriano Huerta and Pancho Villa are referenced in the fourth \"Indiana Jones movie\", ''Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull'' (2008), when Indiana ([[Harrison Ford]]) is recalling events in his childhood to his yet-to-be revealed son ([[Shia LaBeouf]]): \"It was a fight against Victoriano Huerta\". He then spits on the ground to show disgust at the name.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n*[[List of heads of state of Mexico]] \n* [[Huerta's Federal Army]]\n* [[La Cucaracha]]\n* [[United States occupation of Veracruz]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Caballero, Raymond |title= Orozco: Life and Death of a Mexican Revolutionary |publisher= University of Oklahoma Press |location= Norman OK |year= 2017 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Caballero, Raymond |title= Pascual Orozco, \u00bfH\u00e9roe y traidor? |publisher= Siglo XXI Editores |place= M\u00e9xico, D.F. |year= 2020 }}\n* {{cite book | first = Raymond | last = Caballero | title = Lynching Pascual Orozco, Mexican Revolutionary Hero and Paradox| publisher = Create Space | year = 2015 | isbn = 978-1514382509 }}\n*[[Friedrich Katz|Katz Friedrich]]. ''The Secret War in Mexico: Europe, the United States, and the Mexican Revolution''. Chicago: University of Chicago Press 1981.\n*[[Alan Knight (historian)|Knight, Alan]]. ''The Mexican Revolution''. 2 vols. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1990.\n*Meyer, Michael C. ''Huerta: A Political Portrait''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1972.\n*Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, pp.&nbsp;655\u2013658. Chicago: Fitzroy Dearborn 1997.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n17 - \"Temporada de Zopilotes\" ( Buzzard's Season) Paco Ignacio Taibo II, Editorial Planeta, 2000 \n{{ISBN|978-6070701160}}. Narrative of the Decena Tragica (The tragic 10 days)\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Victoriano Huerta}}\n{{EB1922 Poster|Huerta, Victoriano|Victoriano Huerta}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Victoriano Huerta}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080917123739/http://www.colotlan.gob.mx/municipio/biografias.html Colotl\u00e1n official website] biography of Victoriano Huerta\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020614174808/http://www.elbalero.gob.mx/kids/history/html/rev/biohuerta.html M\u00e9xico para ni\u00f1os] biography of Victoriano Huerta\n* [http://www.ramosfamily.org/nextgen/getperson.php?personID=I2440 Genealogy and descendancy] of Victoriano Huerta\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/008317}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of heads of state of Mexico|President of Mexico]]|before=[[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]]|after=[[Francisco S. Carvajal]]|years=19 February 1913 \u2013 15 July 1914}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{MexPostRefPresidents}}\n{{MexicanRevolution}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huerta, Victoriano}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Mexicans]]\n[[Category:Leaders who took power by coup]]\n[[Category:Mexican exiles]]\n[[Category:Mexican generals]]\n[[Category:Mexican people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1913 Mexican presidential election]]\n[[Category:Mexican Secretaries of Foreign Affairs]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Jalisco]]\n[[Category:People of the Mexican Revolution]]\n[[Category:Porfiriato]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in American detention]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican military officer and 35th President of Mexico}}\n{{Main|Mexican Revolution}}\n{{Distinguish|Adolfo de la Huerta}}\n{{Spanish name|Huerta|M\u00e1rquez}}\n{{Infobox president\n| name=Victoriano Huerta\n| nationality=Mexican\n| image=Victoriano Huerta.(cropped).jpg\n| order         = 35th\n| office        = President of Mexico\n| term_start    = 19 February 1913\n| term_end      = 15 July 1914\n| predecessor   = [[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]]\n| successor     = [[Francisco S. Carvajal]]\n| office2       = Secretary of the Interior of Mexico\n| term2         = 19 February 1913\n| predecessor2  = [[Rafael Lorenzo Hern\u00e1ndez]]\n| successor2    = [[Alberto Garc\u00eda Granados]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1850|12|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = Agua Gorda, [[Colotl\u00e1n]], [[Jalisco]], Mexico\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1916|1|13|1850|12|22|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[El Paso, Texas]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Evergreen Cemetery (El Paso, Texas)\n| spouse        = Emilia \u00c1guila\n| party         = [[Independent politician|None]]\n| vicepresident =\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Mexico}}\n| branch        = {{army|Mexico}}\n| serviceyears  = 1877-1907\n| rank          = General\n| unit          =\n}}\n\n'''Jos\u00e9 Victoriano Huerta M\u00e1rquez''' ({{IPA-es|bikto\u02c8\u027ejano \u02c8we\u027eta}}; 22 December 1850{{efn|There is dispute about the date of birth and the maternal surname of Victoriano Huerta. Many sources, including ''Gobernantes de M\u00e9xico'' by Fernando Orozco Linares give a birthdate of 23 March 1854 and a maternal surname of Ortega. However, the parish register of Colotl\u00e1n, Jalisco as filmed by the [[Genealogical Society of Utah]] on film 0443681 v. 24 p. 237 shows a baptism date of 23 December 1850, a birth date of 22 December 1850 and his mother's name as Mar\u00eda L\u00e1zara del Refugio M\u00e1rquez. The marriage record dated 21 November 1880 at Santa Veracruz parrish in Mexico City as filmed by the Genealogical Society of Utah on film 0035853 confirms his mother's name as: Del Refugio M\u00e1rquez.}} \u2013 13 January 1916) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] military officer and 35th [[President of Mexico]], who came to power by coup.\n\nAfter a military career under President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]], Huerta became a high-ranking officer under democratically-elected President [[Francisco I. Madero]] during the first phase of the [[Mexican Revolution]]. In February 1913 Huerta led a conspiracy against Madero, who entrusted him to control a minor revolt in Mexico City. The [[Ten Tragic Days]] saw the forced resignation of Madero and his vice president and their murders. The coup was backed Britain, France, and Germany as well the U.S. under the [[William Howard Taft|Taft Administration]] but the succeeding [[Woodrow Wilson|Wilson administration]] refused to recognize the new regime and allowed arms sales to rebel forces.  Britain, France, and Germany did recognize the regime, but withdrew further support when revolutionary forces showed success against the regime and continued support threatened their relationship with the U.S. Huerta was forced to resign in July 1914 and flee the country with the aid of Germany, only 17 months into his presidency, after the federal army collapsed. While attempting to intrigue with German spies in the U.S. during [[World War I]] (1914-1918), Huerta was arrested in 1915 and died in U.S. custody.\n\nHis supporters were known as ''Huertistas'' during the Mexican Revolution. He is still vilified by modern-day Mexicans, who generally refer to him as ''El Chacal'' (\"The Jackal\") or ''El Usurpador'' (\"The Usurper\").<ref>McCartney, Laton. ''The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country'', Random House, Inc., 2008, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdHi6ilyqk8C&pg=RA1-PA1900&dq=Victoriano+Huerta+Jackal&cd=1#v=onepage&q=Victoriano%20Huerta%20Jackal&f=false p. 1901].</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVictoriano Huerta was born in the settlement of Agua Gorda within the municipality of [[Colotl\u00e1n|Colotl\u00e1n, Jalisco]], son of Jes\u00fas Huerta and Mar\u00eda L\u00e1zara del Refugio M\u00e1rquez. He identified himself as [[Indigenous peoples of Mexico|indigenous]], and both his parents are reported to have been ethnically [[Huichol people|Huichol]], although his father is said to have been [[Mestizo]].<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\">Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, p. 655, Chicago: Fitzroy Dearborn 1997.</ref> Huerta learned to read and write at a school run by the local priest, making him one of the relatively few literate people in Colotl\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, George \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pages 136-145 from ''The Americas'', Volume 21, No. 2 October  1964 page 136.</ref> He had decided upon a military career early on as the only way of escaping the poverty of Colotl\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 136.</ref> In 1869 he was employed by visiting Gen. [[Donato Guerra]] to serve as his personal secretary.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.136.</ref>  In that role he distinguished himself and, with Gen. Guerra's support, gained admission to the Mexican National Military Academy ([[Heroic Military Academy (Mexico)|Heroico Colegio Militar]]) at [[Chapultepec]] in [[Mexico City]] in 1872.<ref name=\"MexEncyclo\">\n{{cite book\n|last = Coerver\n|first = Don M.\n|title = Mexico: An Encyclopedia of Contemporary Culture and History\n|publisher = ABC-CLIO\n|year = 2004\n|isbn = 1-57607-132-4\n}}</ref> As a cadet, Huerta excelled at math, leading him to specialize in artillery and topography.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.137.</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n{{External Timeline|Template:Timeline of the Mexican Revolution|Timeline of the Mexican Revolution}}\n[[File:V_Huerta.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Victoriano Huerta (1850-1916), Mexican dictator (1913-1914).]]\n\nUpon graduating from the military academy in 1877, Huerta was commissioned into the Corps of Engineers.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> After entering the army as a lieutenant in the engineers in 1877, he was put in charge of improving the Loreto and Guadalupe forts in Puebla and the castle of Perote in Veracruz.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\".  ''The Americas'', Volume 21, No. 2 October 1964 p. 137.</ref> In January 1879 he was promoted to captain and assigned to the staff of the 4th Division in Guadalajara, in charge of engineering.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 136-145 </ref> The commander of the 4th Division was [[Manuel Gonz\u00e1lez Flores|Gen. Manuel Gonz\u00e1lez]], a close associate of President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]] and former president of Mexico (1880-84).<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 136-145</ref>  In the interim, Huerta's career prospered thanks to the patronage of Gonz\u00e1lez.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\", pp. 136-45.</ref> In Mexico City, he married Emilia \u00c1guila Moya, whom he met in Veracruz, on 21 November 1880.<ref>Genealogical Society of Utah, Film 0035853</ref> The marriage produced 11 children. The names of his children surviving him in 1916 were Jorge, Mar\u00eda Elisa, Victor, Luz, Elena, Dagoberto, Eva and Celia.<ref>''El Paso Times'' obituary</ref> Huerta participated in the \"pacification campaigns\" in [[Tepic]] and [[Sinaloa]], where he distinguished himself in combat.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> He was known for ensuring that his men always got paid, often resorting to finding the money in ruthless ways.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 138.</ref> Following a complaint from the Catholic Church that Huerta had plundered a church to sell off its gold and silver to pay his men, Huerta justified his actions on the grounds that \"Mexico can do without her priests, but cannot do without her soldiers\".<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.138.</ref> On another occasion, following a complaint from a bank that he emptied out one of its branches at gunpoint to get money to pay his men, Huerta pointed out he left a receipt and would pay back the bank what he had stolen when he received the necessary funds from Mexico City.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.138.</ref> Huerta then spent nine years of his military career undertaking [[topography|topographic]] studies in the states of [[Puebla]] and [[Veracruz]]. He traveled extensively to all parts of Mexico in this position.<ref name=\"Richmond p. 655\"/> French cultural influence was very strong in 19th-century Mexico, and Huerta's hero was [[Napoleon]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.139.</ref> He supported Gen. D\u00edaz as the closest approximation to his Napoleonic ideal, believing that Mexico needed a \"strongman\" to prosper.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.139.</ref>     \n\nBy 1890 Huerta had reached the rank of Colonel of Engineers.  From 1890-95 Huerta lived in Mexico City, becoming a regular visitor to the presidential residence at [[Chapultepec Castle]], and was seen as part of D\u00edaz's \"court\".<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\", p.139.</ref> Through Huerta was well liked at the Chapultepec Castle, acquiring the persona of a trim, efficient office who was stern to his subordinates while displaying a courtly, polished manner towards his superiors, he began to suffer from severe insomnia and began drinking heavily during this time.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 139.</ref> In January 1895 he commanded a battalion of infantry against a rebellion in Guerrero led by Gen. [[Canuto Neri]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 140.</ref> The rebellion was ended when D\u00edaz brokered a deal with Neri, who surrendered in exchange for a promise to remove the unpopular state governor.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.140.</ref> Huerta confirmed his reputation for ruthlessness by refusing to take prisoners and continuing to attack the followers of Neri even after D\u00edaz had signed a ceasefire.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 140.</ref> In December 1900 Huerta commanded a successful military campaign against [[Yaqui]] Indians in [[Sonora]].<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 140-141.</ref> During the near-genocidal campaign against the Yaqui, Huerta was more concerned with mapping out the terrain of Sonora, but at times he commanded forces in the field against the Yaqui.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" pp. 140-141.</ref> From 12 April-8 September 1901 Huerta put down a rebellion in Guerrero, completely \"pacifying\" the state.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.141.</ref> In May 1901 he was promoted to the rank of general.<ref>Rausch, Georgre \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 141.</ref> In 1901-02 he suppressed a [[Maya peoples|Maya]]' rising in [[Yucat\u00e1n]]. He commanded about 500 men in his campaign against the Maya, starting in October 1901, and fought 79 different actions over the course of 39 days.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p. 141.</ref> Huerta was then promoted to Brigadier General and awarded the Medal of Military Merit <ref name=\"MexEncyclo\"/> In May 1902 he was promoted commander of federal army forces in Yucat\u00e1n, and in October 1902 he reported to D\u00edaz that he had \"pacified\" the Yucat\u00e1n.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.142.</ref> During the campaign in Yucat\u00e1n he became increasingly dependent on alcohol to continue functioning. His health began to decline, and perhaps because of his heavy drinking he complained he could not go outside in the sunshine without wearing sunglasses, and he suffered bouts of uncontrollable nervous shaking. His decaying teeth caused him much pain.<ref>Rausch, \"The Early Career of Victoriano Huerta\" p.142.</ref> In August 1903 he was appointed to head a committee tasked with reforming the uniforms of the federal army.<ref>Joseph Hefter, page 80 ''Cronica del Traje Militar en Mexico del Siglo XVI al XX'', ''Artes de Mexico No. 102, 1968''</ref> In 1907 he retired from the army on grounds of ill health, having developed cataracts while serving in the southern jungles. He then applied his technical training by taking up the position of Head of Public Works in [[Monterrey]] and planning a new street layout for the city.\n\n==Mexican Revolution under Madero==\n[[File:Huerta Madero Villa.jpg|thumb|General Huerta (left) with [[Emilio Madero]], Pres. Madero's brother, and [[Pancho Villa]], 1912.]]\nOn the eve of the 1910 [[Mexican Revolution|Revolution]] against the long-established D\u00edaz regime, Huerta was teaching mathematics in Mexico City. He applied successfully to rejoin the army with his former rank and was accepted. He did not play a major role in the early stages of the Revolution that led to the resignation of D\u00edaz, although he commanded the military escort that gave D\u00edaz safe conduct into exile in May 1911. During the interim presidency of [[Francisco Le\u00f3n de la Barra]] following the resignation of D\u00edaz and the election of [[Francisco I. Madero]] in November 1911, General Huerta  carried out a campaign in Morelos, attempting to crush the rebellion led by [[Emilio Zapata]]. Huerta's forces burned villages supporting the rebellion and attacked their residents. These actions frustrated Madero's later attempts to placate those rebels.<ref>Hart, John Mason. ''Revolutionary Mexico'', p. 252.</ref> Huerta had a record of opposing revolutionaries and intrigues with Madero's enemies. Huerta's actions in Morelos forced a break between Emiliano Zapata and Madero, who was later to rebel against Madero immediately after his November 1911 election.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that revolutionary forces supporting [[Francisco I. Madero]] had forced D\u00edaz's resignation, Madero ordered them demobilized and retained the [[Federal Army|Mexican Federal Army]] they had just defeated.  Huerta pledged allegiance to President Madero, and carried out Madero's orders to crush anti-Madero revolts by rebel generals such as [[Pascual Orozco]], who had helped topple D\u00edaz and then rebelled against his regime.  In the Orozco rebellion, Huerta saw the opportunity to eliminate revolutionary general Pancho Villa, who was also attempting to suppress the revolt. Accused of stealing a horse, Villa then faced execution by Huerta without trial.  Only Madero's last minute intervention saved the life of one of his most effective generals.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref> \n\nOrozco's rebellion was a major threat to the Madero government, since he had standing as a revolutionary and commanded significant forces. Madero sent Huerta to crush the rebellion. He had at his command troops of the Mexican Federal Army and these were joined by irregulars led by the revolutionary leader [[Pancho Villa]], at Torre\u00f3n in April 1912. Huerta offered Orozco's supporters (''Orozquistas'') amnesty, which might have weakened their forces already suffering from lack of money and arms. Huerta's forces defeated Orozco's at Rellano in May 1912. With that victory Huerta \"had suddenly become a military hero with a national reputation.\"<ref>Meyer, Michael C. ''Mexican Rebel: Pascual Orozco and the Mexican Revolution, 1910-1915''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1967, p. 82.</ref> \n\n==Huerta and Madero's overthrow==\n{{Main|Ten Tragic Days}}\nAs Madero lost support and as internal and external groups plotted to remove him from the presidency, Huerta secretly joined the conspiracy.  The coup d'etat that toppled Madero February 1913, known in Mexican history as the [[Ten Tragic Days]], was a conspiracy of Porfirio D\u00edaz's nephew, General F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz, General Bernardo Reyes, and General Madrag\u00f3n.  The plotters attempted to draw in Huerta in January, but Huerta waited for a better incentive to join, since F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz expected to be the successor to Madero. The first day of the coup, February 9, General Reyes died in battle and General Lauro Villar, the commander of Madero's forces in Mexico City, was wounded.<ref>{{cite book|first=Alan|last=Knight|page=[https://archive.org/details/mexicanrevolutio0000knig/page/483 483]|title=The Mexican Revolution. Volume 1. Porfirians, Liberals and Peasants|isbn=0-8032-7770-9|year=1990|url=https://archive.org/details/mexicanrevolutio0000knig/page/483}}</ref> Madero appointed Huerta in his stead. According to historian [[Friedrich Katz]], \"It was a decision for which [Madero] would pay with his life.\"<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 96.</ref> Having secured that key position, Huerta reopened negotiations with the plotters and joined them in secret. His task was to undermine Madero militarily without betraying his own complicity and began military operations that weakened Madero's forces.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War'', p. 97.</ref> \n[[United States Ambassador to Mexico]] [[Henry Lane Wilson]],<ref name=\"McLynn\">\n{{cite book\n|first = Frank\n|last = McLynn\n|title = Villa and Zapata\n|publisher = Carroll & Graf \n|year = 2002P\n|isbn = 0-7867-1088-8\n|url-access = registration\n|url = https://archive.org/details/villazapata00fran\n}}</ref> was an active participant in the plot to overthrow Madero. Ambassador Wilson believed that Huerta would not have staged a coup had the United States not assured them that it would recognize the new regime.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 98.</ref>   Following a confused few days of fighting in Mexico City between loyalist and rebel factions of the army, Huerta had Madero and vice-president [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Pino Su\u00e1rez]] seized and briefly imprisoned on 18 February 1913 in the [[National Palace (Mexico)|National Palace]]. The conspirators then met at the US Embassy to sign ''El Pacto de la Embajada'' (The Embassy Pact), which provided for the exile of Madero and Pino Su\u00e1rez and Huerta's takeover of the Mexican government.<ref name=revs>Richards, Michael D. ''Revolutions in world history'', Routledge, 2004, [https://archive.org/details/revolutionsinwor0000rich/page/26 p. 26].</ref>\n\n==''La Mano Dura'': Presidency of Mexico==\n[[Image:Victoriano Huerta y su gabinete.tif|thumb|right|Victoriano Huerta and his cabinet]]\nTo give the coup the appearance of legitimacy, Huerta had [[foreign minister]] [[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]] assume the presidency; under the [[1857 Constitution of Mexico]], the foreign minister stood third in line for the presidency behind the Vice President and [[Attorney General of Mexico|Attorney General]]; Madero's attorney general had also been ousted in the coup. Lascur\u00e1in then appointed Huerta as [[Secretariat of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]], making him next in line for the presidency. After less than an hour in office (some sources say as little as 15 minutes), Lascur\u00e1in resigned, handing the presidency to Huerta. At a late-night special session of Congress surrounded by Huerta's troops, the legislators endorsed his assumption of power. Four days later Madero and Pino Su\u00e1rez were taken from the National Palace to prison at night and shot by officers of the [[rurales]] (federal police), who were assumed to be acting on Huerta's orders. \n\nThe Huerta government was promptly recognized by all the western European governments, but the outgoing US administration of [[William Howard Taft]] refused to recognize the new government, as a way of pressuring Mexico to end the Chamizal border dispute in favor of the US, with the plan being to trade recognition for settling the dispute on American terms.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 68.</ref> Newly inaugurated U.S. president [[Woodrow Wilson]] had a general bias in favor of liberal democracy and had distaste for Gen. Huerta, who had come to power by coup and was implicated in the murder of Madero, but was initially open to recognizing Huerta provided that he could \"win\" an election that would give him a democratic veneer.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 69.</ref> F\u00e9lix D\u00edaz and the rest of the conservative leaders had seen Huerta as a transitional leader and pressed for early elections, which they expected to be won by Diaz on a Catholic conservative platform, and were rudely surprised when they discovered Huerta wanted to keep the presidency for himself.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 64.</ref> \n[[Image:Huerta y Orozco.jpg|right|thumb|Victoriano Huerta (left) and [[Pascual Orozco]] (right).]]\nHuerta moved quickly to consolidate power within Mexico with the support of state governors.<ref>Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, p. 656.</ref> Huerta sought support from Pascual Orozco, whose rebellion against Madero Huerta had been in charge of suppressing. Orozco still held the leadership of significant forces in Chihuahua and potentially in Durango, so gaining his support was important to Huerta. Orozco had rebelled against Madero and Huerta had overthrown him, so there was the possibility of gaining his support. During a meeting of representatives of Huerta's government and Orozco's forces, Orozco laid out his terms for supporting Huerta. He sought recognition of his soldiers' service to the overthrown of Madero and pay; pensions and care of soldiers' widows and orphans, agrarian reforms, government payment of Orozquista debts that financed the campaign against Madero, and employment of Orozquistas as ''rurales''. Huerta agreed to the terms, and Orozco threw his support to Huerta on 27 February 1913.<ref>Meyer, ''Pascual Orozco'', pp. 97-98.</ref> Orozco sought to persuade Emiliano Zapata to make peace with Huerta regime. Zapata had held Orozco in high esteem as a fellow revolutionary who had rejected the Madero regime.  However, for Zapata, Orozco's support of Huerta was anathema,saying \"Huerta represents the defection of the army. You represent the defection of the Revolution.\"<ref>quoted in Meyer, ''Pascual Orozco'', p. 101.</ref>\n\nHuerta attempted to build further support for his government, and the urban working class in Mexico City made important gains before being suppressed. In particular, the leftist [[Casa del Obrero Mundial]] (House of the World Worker). The Casa organized demonstrations and strikes, which the Huerta regime initially tolerated. But then the government cracked down, arresting and deporting some leaders, and destroying the Casa's headquarters.<ref>Hart, John Mason. ''Revolutionary Mexico: The Coming Process of the Mexican Revolution''. Berkeley: University of California Press 1987, pp. 271-72.</ref> Huerta also sought to diffuse agrarian agitation, which fueled the rebellion in Morelos led by Emiliano Zapata. The most vocal intellectual in favor of land reform was [[Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez]], whose 1909 publication ''Los grandes problemas nacionales'' (The Great National Problems) focused on inequality of land tenure. Molina Enr\u00edquez joined the Huerta government heading the Department of Labor.  He had denounced the overthrow of Madero, but \"initially saw in the Huerta regime the political formula he believed Mexico required: a strong military leader capable of imposing the social reforms Mexico needed to benefit the masses.\" However, despite internal support in the Huerta regime for reform, Huerta increasingly embraced militarization and Molina Enr\u00edquez resigned.<ref>Shadle, Stanley F. ''Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez: Mexican Land Reformer of the Revolutionary Era''. Tucson: University of Arizona Press 1994, pp. 62-63.</ref>\n\n[[Image:Desconocimiento de Victoriano Huerta como Jefe del Poder Ejecutivo de la Rep\u00fablica.tif|thumb|right|Venustiano Carranza disavows Victoriano Huerta's claim to the presidency]]\n\nChihuahua Gov. [[Abraham Gonz\u00e1lez (governor)|Abraham Gonz\u00e1lez]] refused and Huerta had him arrested and murdered in March 1913.\nThe most important challenge from a state governor was by [[Venustiano Carranza]], governor of Coahuila, who drafted the [[Plan of Guadalupe]], calling for the creation of a [[Constitutionalist Army]] (evoking the 1857 Liberal Constitution) to oust the usurper Huerta and restore constitutional government. Supporters of Carranza's plan included [[Emiliano Zapata]], who nonetheless remained loyal to his own [[Plan de Ayala]]; northern revolutionary [[Francisco \"Pancho\" Villa]]; and [[\u00c1lvaro Obreg\u00f3n]]. However, former revolutionary Gen. [[Pascual Orozco]], whom Huerta fought when serving President Madero, now joined with Huerta as a counter-revolutionary. Four Deputies were executed over the summer of 1913 for criticizing the Huerta regime.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 67.</ref> One deputy was arrested by Mexico City police as he was delivering a speech denouncing Huerta at a rally and taken out to the countryside, where he was \"shot while trying to escape\".<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.67.</ref> Lacking popular legitimacy, Huerta chose to turn the refusal of the US to recognize his government as an example of American \"interference\" in Mexico's internal affairs, organizing anti-American demonstrations in the summer of 1913 with the hope of gaining some popular support.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 71.</ref>    \n\nBritish historian [[Alan Knight (historian)|Alan Knight]] wrote about Huerta: \"The consistent thread which ran through the Huerta regime, from start to finish, was militarisation: the growth and reliance on the Federal Army, the military takeover of public offices, the preference for military over political solutions, the militarisation of society in general\".<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press, 1990 page 62.</ref> Huerta \"came very close to converting Mexico into the most completely militaristic state in the world.\"<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p. 62.</ref> Huerta's stated goal was a return to the \"order\" of the [[Porfiriato]], but his methods were unlike those of Diaz, who had shown a talent for compromise and diplomacy; seeking support from and playing off regional elites, using not only army officers but also technocrats, former guerrilla leaders, ''[[cacique]]s'' and provincial elites to support his regime.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 63.</ref> By contrast, Huerta relied entirely upon the army for support, giving officers all of the key jobs, regardless of their talents, as Huerta sought to rule with ''La Mano Dura'' (\"The Iron Hand\"), believing only in military solutions to all problems.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p. 63.</ref> For this reason, Huerta during his short time as President was the object of far more hatred than Diaz ever was; even the Zapatistas had a certain respect for Diaz as a patriarchal leader who had enough sense to finally leave with dignity in 1911, whereas Huerta was seen as a thuggish soldier who had Madero murdered and sought to terrorize the nation into submission.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 63.</ref> Huerta disliked cabinet meetings, ordered his ministers about as if they were non-commissioned officers and displayed in general a highly autocratic style.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 64.</ref> \n\nHuerta established a harsh military dictatorship.<ref>Richmond, \"Victoriano Huerta\", p. 657.</ref> [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] Woodrow Wilson became hostile to the Huerta administration, recalled ambassador [[Henry Lane Wilson]] and demanded Huerta step aside for democratic elections. In August 1913 Wilson imposed an arms embargo on Mexico, forcing Huerta to turn to Europe and Japan to buy arms.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 72.</ref> Reflecting the general disenchantment with Huerta's \"iron hand\" policies, a prominent conservative, Sen. [[Belisario Dom\u00ednguez]] of Chiapas, handed out copies of a speech he did not dare to deliver in the Senate, accusing Huerta of starting the civil war which he was losing, of wanting \"to cover the land with corpses . . . rather than abandon power\" and called for Congress to impeach Huerta before Mexico was plunged into the abyss.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'' 66.</ref> Dom\u00ednguez knew he was risking his life by speaking out and sent his wife and children out of Mexico before handing out copies of his speech.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.66.</ref> Dom\u00ednguez was arrested by two policemen plus Huerta's son and son-in-law, taken to a cemetery where he was \"shot while trying to escape\" for speaking out against the President. His body was dumped into the grave that his killers had already dug for him.<ref>Knight, Alan ''The Mexican Revolution'', page 67.</ref> On 10 October 1913, when Congress announced it was opening an investigation of the disappearance of Sen. Dom\u00ednguez, who had last been seen several days before being forced into a police car, Huerta sent his soldiers in to shut down Congress in session and arrested 110 Senators and Deputies, of whom 74 were charged with high treason and put to work building a bullfighting arena.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.75.</ref> \n\nThe federal army Huerta took over in February 1913 numbered between 45,000-50,000 men. Huerta continued to increase the strength of the army, issuing a degree for conscripting 150,000 men in October 1913; another degree for conscripting 200,000 men in January 1914 and one for a quarter of million men in March 1914. These figures were never achieved as many men fled to fight for the Constitutionalists rather than Huerta.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 77.</ref> Together with an increase in the number of the paramilitary ''[[rurales]]'' mounted police force and the state militias, Huerta had approximately 300,000 men, or about 4% of the population, fighting for him by early 1914.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution: Counter-Revolution and Reconstruction'', p.77.</ref> Faced with widespread reluctance to serve Huerta had to resort to the ''leva'', as vagrants, criminals, captured rebels, political prisoners and sometimes just men on the streets were rounded up to serve in the Federal Army.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 77.</ref> In Veracruz workers getting off the night shift at factories were rounded up in a ''leva'' (forced conscription), while in Mexico City poor men going to hospitals were rounded up in the ''leva''.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.77.</ref> As Indians were felt to be particularly docile and submissive to whites, the ''leva'' was applied especially heavily in the southern Mexico, where the majority of the people were Indians. Thousands of Juchiteco and Maya Indians were rounded up to fight a war in the north of Mexico that they felt did not concern them.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'' page 78.</ref> A visitor to M\u00e9rida in the Yucat\u00e1n wrote of \"heart-breaking\" scenes as hundreds of Maya Indians said goodbye to their wives as they were forced to board a train while in chains.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 78.</ref> \n\nAs the men rounded up in the ''leva'' proved to be poor soldiers, prone to desertion and mutiny, Huerta had to follow a defensive strategy of keeping the army concentrated in large towns, since his soldiers in the field would either desert or go over to the rebels.<ref>Knight,  ''The Mexican Revolution'' p. 79.</ref> Throughout the civil war of 1913-14 the Constitutionalists fought with a ferocity and courage that the federal army never managed.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 79.</ref> In Yucat\u00e1n about 70% of the army were men conscripted from the prisons, while one \"volunteer\" battalion consisted of captured Yaqui Indians.<ref>Knight,''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 79.</ref> In October 1913, in the town of Tlalnepantla, the army's 9th Regiment, which was said to have been \"crazed with alcohol and marijuana\", mutinied, murdered their officers and went over to the rebels.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'',  p. 79.</ref> To provide volunteers, Huerta turned to Mexican nationalism and anti-Americanism in the fall of 1913, running spurious stories in the press warning of an imminent American invasion and asking for patriotic men to step up to defend Mexico.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', pp. 79-80.</ref> The campaign attracted some volunteers from the lower middle class, through they were usually disillusioned when they learned that they were going to fight other Mexicans, not the Americans.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.80.</ref> In rural Mexico a sense of Mexican nationalism barely existed at this time among the ''campesinos''. Mexico was an abstract entity that meant nothing, and most ''campesinos'' were primarily loyal to their own villages, the ''patria chicas''.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p. 80.</ref> Huerta's patriotic campaign was a complete failure in the countryside.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', p.80.</ref> The other source of volunteers was to allow wealthy landlords to raise private armies under the guise of the state militias, but few ''peons'' wanted to fight, let alone die, for Gen. Huerta, since the Constitutionalists were promising land reform.<ref>Knight, ''The Mexican Revolution'', pp. 81-82.</ref>\n\nWhen Huerta refused to call elections, and with the situation further exacerbated by the [[Tampico Affair]], President Wilson landed US troops to [[United States occupation of Veracruz|occupy]] Mexico's most important seaport, [[Veracruz (city)|Veracruz]].\n\nAfter the federal army was repeatedly defeated in battle by Constitutionalist generals [[Alvaro Obreg\u00f3n]] and Pancho Villa, climaxing in the [[Battle of Zacatecas (1914)|Battle of Zacatecas]], Huerta bowed to internal and external pressure and resigned the presidency on 15 July 1914.<ref>[https://www.biografiacortade.com/victoriano-huerta-marquez/ \"Huerta's ] [https://archive.org/stream/independen79v80newy#page/n96/mode/1up Final Message to the Mexican Congress\"]. ''The Independent''. July 27, 1914. Retrieved 24 July 2012.</ref>\n\n==Exile, late life and death==\n[[Image:Delgado Huerta Ratner.jpg|right|thumb|Jos\u00e9 C. Delgado, Victoriano Huerta and Abraham F. Ratner.]]\nHuerta went into exile, first traveling to [[Kingston, Jamaica]], aboard the German cruiser [[SMS Dresden (1907)|SMS ''Dresden'']].<ref name=war>Russell, Thomas Herbert. ''America's War for Humanity'', BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009, [https://books.google.com/books?id=9SGGuoj3JRsC&pg=PA500 p. 500].</ref> From there he moved to the [[UK]], then [[Spain]], and arrived in the US in April 1915.\n\nWhile in the US he negotiated with Capt. [[Franz von Rintelen]] of German Navy Intelligence for money to purchase weapons and arrange [[U-boat]] landings to provide support, while offering (perhaps as a bargaining chip) to make war on the US, which Germany hoped would end munitions supplies to the Allies.<ref>Tuchman, Barbara W. ''The Zimmermann Telegram'' (New York: NEL Mentor, 1967), pp. 73-4.</ref> Their meetings, held at the [[Hotel Manhattan|Manhattan Hotel]] (as well as another New York hotel, \"probably the Holland House\" at Fifth Avenue and 30th Street)<ref name=\"Tuchman, p.73\">Tuchman, p. 73.</ref>, were observed by [[United States Secret Service|Secret Service]]men, and von Rintelen's telephone conversations were routinely intercepted and recorded.<ref name=\"Tuchman, p.73\"/>\n\nHuerta traveled from New York by train to [[Newman, New Mexico|Newman]], [[New Mexico]] (25 miles from the border), where he was to be met by Gen. [[Pascual Orozco]] and some well-armed Mexican supporters. However, a US Army colonel with 25 soldiers and two deputy US marshals intervened and arrested him as he left the train, on a charge of sedition.<ref>Blum, Howard. ''Dark Invasion: 1915 - Germany's Secret War'', Harper, 2014, p. 228.</ref> The German-initiated plan for Huerta to regain the Mexican presidency through a [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] was foiled. After some time in a US Army prison at [[Fort Bliss]] he was released on bail, but remained under house arrest due to risk of flight to Mexico. A day after, he attended a dinner at Fort Bliss. Later he was returned to jail, and while so confined died, perhaps of [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]]. While the main symptom was [[jaundice|yellow jaundice]], poisoning by the US was widely suspected.<ref name=Lee>Stacy, Lee. ''Mexico and the United States'', Marshall Cavendish, 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=DSzyMGh8pNwC&pg=PA405 p. 405].</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn the historiography of Mexico, Victoriano Huerta is the \"demon\" of the Mexican Revolution, against whom all others are measured.<ref>LaFrance, David. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Latin American History and Culture'', vol. 3, p. 216. New  York: Charles Scribner's Sons 1996</ref>  Diverse factions and interests in Mexico came together against the Huerta regime, including the Zapatistas in Morelos and the Constitutionalists in northern Mexico under Venustiano Carranza.  Once Huerta was ousted, the loose coalition fell apart and Mexico was plunged into a civil war between the winners. Germany and Great Britain's backing of Huerta weakened their influence in Mexico while the hostility of the United States to the regime increased it. Although U.S. business interests had hoped that President Wilson would recognize the Huerta government, they realized he would not and began aligning themselves with different revolutionary factions.<ref>Katz, ''The Secret War in Mexico'', p. 566.</ref> One historian argues that Huerta's regime was not as conservative or reactionary as portrayed, arguing that he did not attempt to \"reincarnate\" the Age of D\u00edaz. \"Huerta and his advisors both realized the days of D\u00edaz were gone forever. They did not attempt to stem the new energies and forces unleashed in 1910; rather they attempted to moderate them.\"<ref>Meyer, Michael C. ''Huerta: A Political Portrait''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1972, pp. 369-70</ref> In general, however, his regime is seen as a repudiation of democracy and Huerta himself an iron-fisted authoritarian. Despite efforts in Mexico to redress the exclusion of Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez from the pantheon of Mexican revolutionaries, since he is considered the intellectual father of the Article 27 of the 1917 Mexican Constitution empowering the state to implement [[land reform in Mexico|land reform]] and expropriate private owners of resources like oil. Molina Enr\u00edquez was tainted by his service in the Huerta government.<ref>Shadle, ''Andr\u00e9s Molina Enr\u00edquez'', p.4.</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nHuerta has been portrayed or referenced in any number of movies dealing with the Mexican Revolution, including ''[[The Wild Bunch]]'', ''[[Duck, You Sucker!]]'' and ''[[And Starring Pancho Villa as Himself]]''.\n\nIn the 1952 film ''[[Viva Zapata!]]'', starring [[Marlon Brando]] as [[Emiliano Zapata]], Huerta is portrayed by [[Frank Silvera]].\n\nIn the 1968 film ''[[Villa Rides]]'', Huerta was played by [[Herbert Lom]].\n\nIn the novel ''The Friends of Pancho Villa'' (1996), by [[James Carlos Blake]], Huerta is a major character.\n\nBoth Victoriano Huerta and Pancho Villa are referenced in the fourth \"Indiana Jones movie\", ''Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull'' (2008), when Indiana ([[Harrison Ford]]) is recalling events in his childhood to his yet-to-be revealed son ([[Shia LaBeouf]]): \"It was a fight against Victoriano Huerta\". He then spits on the ground to show disgust at the name.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Mexico}}\n*[[List of heads of state of Mexico]] \n* [[Huerta's Federal Army]]\n* [[La Cucaracha]]\n* [[United States occupation of Veracruz]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last= Caballero, Raymond |title= Orozco: Life and Death of a Mexican Revolutionary |publisher= University of Oklahoma Press |location= Norman OK |year= 2017 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Caballero, Raymond |title= Pascual Orozco, \u00bfH\u00e9roe y traidor? |publisher= Siglo XXI Editores |place= M\u00e9xico, D.F. |year= 2020 }}\n* {{cite book | first = Raymond | last = Caballero | title = Lynching Pascual Orozco, Mexican Revolutionary Hero and Paradox| publisher = Create Space | year = 2015 | isbn = 978-1514382509 }}\n*[[Friedrich Katz|Katz Friedrich]]. ''The Secret War in Mexico: Europe, the United States, and the Mexican Revolution''. Chicago: University of Chicago Press 1981.\n*[[Alan Knight (historian)|Knight, Alan]]. ''The Mexican Revolution''. 2 vols. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1990.\n*Meyer, Michael C. ''Huerta: A Political Portrait''. Lincoln: University of Nebraska Press 1972.\n*Richmond, Douglas W. \"Victoriano Huerta\" in ''Encyclopedia of Mexico'', vol. 1, pp.&nbsp;655\u2013658. Chicago: Fitzroy Dearborn 1997.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n17 - \"Temporada de Zopilotes\" ( Buzzard's Season) Paco Ignacio Taibo II, Editorial Planeta, 2000 \n{{ISBN|978-6070701160}}. Narrative of the Decena Tragica (The tragic 10 days)\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Victoriano Huerta}}\n{{EB1922 Poster|Huerta, Victoriano|Victoriano Huerta}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Victoriano Huerta}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080917123739/http://www.colotlan.gob.mx/municipio/biografias.html Colotl\u00e1n official website] biography of Victoriano Huerta\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020614174808/http://www.elbalero.gob.mx/kids/history/html/rev/biohuerta.html M\u00e9xico para ni\u00f1os] biography of Victoriano Huerta\n* [http://www.ramosfamily.org/nextgen/getperson.php?personID=I2440 Genealogy and descendancy] of Victoriano Huerta\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/008317}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of heads of state of Mexico|President of Mexico]]|before=[[Pedro Lascur\u00e1in]]|after=[[Francisco S. Carvajal]]|years=19 February 1913 \u2013 15 July 1914}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{MexPostRefPresidents}}\n{{MexicanRevolution}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huerta, Victoriano}}\n[[Category:1850 births]]\n[[Category:1916 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cirrhosis]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Mexicans]]\n[[Category:Leaders who took power by coup]]\n[[Category:Mexican exiles]]\n[[Category:Mexican generals]]\n[[Category:Mexican people imprisoned abroad]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1913 Mexican presidential election]]\n[[Category:Mexican Secretaries of Foreign Affairs]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Jalisco]]\n[[Category:People of the Mexican Revolution]]\n[[Category:Porfiriato]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in American detention]]\n", "name_user": "JamieEditsWiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoriano_Huerta"}
{"title_page": "Zhukov Pochinok", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhukov Pochinok\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|19|N|37|19|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhukov Pochinok''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 25&nbsp;km, to Boylovo is 6&nbsp;km. Bolshaya Gorka is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhukov Pochinok\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|19|N|37|19|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhukov Pochinok''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 5 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 25&nbsp;km, to Boylovo is 6&nbsp;km. Bolshaya Gorka is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhukov_Pochinok"}
{"title_page": "Red Top (missile)", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n| image= Red Top missile.png\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= Red Top missile\n|name=Red Top\n|type=[[Air-to-air missile]]\n|origin=United Kingdom\n|era=Cold War\n|platform=aircraft\n|target=aircraft\n|manufacturer=Hawker Siddeley Dynamics\n|design_date=\n|production_date=\n|service=1964 - 1988\n|used_by= United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait\n|wars=\n|spec_type= homing missile\n|diameter= 0.23 m\n|wingspan=0.91 m\n|length=3.32 m\n|weight= 154 kg\n|speed=Mach 3.2\n|vehicle_range=7.5 miles (12 km)\n|ceiling=\n|filling=31 kg (68.3 lb) [[annular blast fragmentation]]\n|engine=''Linnet'' solid fuel motor\n|steering=control surfaces\n|guidance=[[infrared homing]], limited [[all-aspect]]\n|variants=?\n|number=\n|detonation=''Green Garland'' infrared proximity; secondary contact [[fuze]]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[Hawker Siddeley]]''' (later [[British Aerospace]]) '''Red Top''' was the third indigenous British [[air-to-air missile]] to enter service, following the [[de Havilland Firestreak]] and limited-service [[Fireflash]]. Originally a modified version of the Firestreak, Red Top emerged as a much more capable weapon, with roughly double the range, a more sensitive seeker giving limited all-aspect capability, and an even larger warhead than the already-large one in Firestreak. Although much more powerful than Firestreak, both missiles remained in service until 1988 when the last of the [[English Electric Lightning]]s retired.\n\n==Development==\n===Improved Blue Jay===\nEven before the original [[de Havilland Firestreak|Firestreak]] entered service, improvements were being studied to increase its performance. Still known by its [[rainbow code]] \"Blue Jay\", Blue Jay Mk. II introduced an improved seeker and more powerful motor, while Mk. III derated the motor to limit acceleration when launched at high speed in order to avoid overheating due to aerodynamic heating. Neither project was proceeded with.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=35}}\n\n===Blue Vesta===\nLooking for a further improved weapon for the [[Operational Requirement F.155]] interceptors, in 1955 the Air Ministry issued OR.1131 for an all-aspect design capability against enemy aircraft traveling at Mach 2. De Havilland responded with Blue Jay Mk. IV, which was later given its own rainbow code, '''Blue Vesta'''.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}\n\nBlue Vesta adopted the PbTe seeker of Mk. II, further improved by cooling it to improve its sensitivity in what became known as the \"Violet Banner\" seeker. The motor was further upgraded to the new Magpie III. To handle the aerodynamic heating issues, the fins were made of steel rather than aluminum, and featured cut-away sections to keep the rear portions of the surfaces out of the Mach cones, a feature they referred to as \"mach tips\".{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}{{efn|More widely known today as a cropped delta.}}\n\nWork on Blue Vesta was curtailed after 1956 as the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]] (RAE) concluded that the rapid closing speeds of two Mach 2+ aircraft would be so quick that the missile would have no chance to be launched while it was still within the range of its seeker. They suggested moving to the much larger [[radar]]-guided [[Red Hebe]], although some low-level work on Blue Vesta's underlying technologies continued.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}\n\n===Red Top===\nF.155 was canceled in the aftermath of the release of the [[1957 Defence White Paper]]. It was decided to proceed with the development of the Lightning largely because it was already close to being complete. Blue Vesta was reactivated in July 1957 to arm this aircraft. For security reasons, yet another rainbow code was assigned in November 1957 and it became Red Top.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nIn contrast to Blue Vesta, Red Top was a simpler design, more of a rationalised, upgraded version of the earlier Firestreak. Lower launch speeds allowed the steel wings and fins to be replaced, and these were enlarged to provide more maneuvering power. The fuselage was straightened, removing the boat-tail design of the Firestreak and allowing the new \"Linnet\" rocket motor to more completely fill the increased volume. Other oddities of the Firestreak, like the fin actuators being in the nose and requiring pushrods running the length of the fuselage were removed, giving it a much more logical layout and further increasing internal volume.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nThe all-aspect [[lead telluride]] (PbTe) seeker developed for Blue Vesta was replaced by a much less expensive [[indium antimonide]] (InSb) system known as \"Violet Banner\". This seeker lacked the sensitivity of the PbTe model and did not offer true all-aspect capability, but it offset this loss to some degree through a greatly increased the [[field of view]] to 60&nbsp;degrees. Firestreak's tube-powered electronics were replaced by [[transistor]]ized versions, which greatly improved reliability and eliminated the need for continual cooling. The new \"Green Garland\" IR [[proximity fuse]] required only one row of \"windows\", further simplifying the layout.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nThese changes allowed the warhead to be moved to the forward fuselage from its former rear-mounted location. This allowed it to be enlarged to 31&nbsp;kg (68.3&nbsp;lb) from Firestreak's already prodigious 22.7&nbsp;kg (50&nbsp;lb) and added an [[expanding-rod warhead]] in place of the earlier blast fragmentation type.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nThe Red Top was faster<ref name=Boyne267/> and had greater range and maneuvrability than the Firestreak, and its [[infrared seeker]] enabled a wider range of engagement angles. Although not offering the true all-aspect capability planned for Blue Vesta, Violet Banner did allow head-on attacks against supersonic aircraft.<ref>[http://www.vectorsite.net/aveeltg.html The English Electric (BAC) Lightning<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  \"Unlike modern [1990s] missiles, Red Top and Firestreak could only be fired outside cloud, and in winter, skies were rarely clear over the UK.\"<ref name=Black141>Black, Ian, ''The Last of the Lightnings'', pub PSL, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85260-541-3}}, p141.</ref>\n\n===Almost cancelled===\nAlthough Red Top was a relatively straightforward upgrade to Firestreak, [[Duncan Sandys]] almost cancelled it as well. He felt that Firestreak would be acceptable during the short period before the [[Bristol Bloodhound|Bloodhound Mk. II]] [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] entered service in the early 1960s and eliminated the need for [[interceptor aircraft]] altogether. The [[Air Staff]] argued this point, ultimately convincing him that Red Top's head-on attack profile against new Soviet supersonic bombers known to be in development was an urgent requirement.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nAt a February 1958 meeting of the Controller of Guided Weapons and Electronics, the group earmarked Red Top for both Lightning and the [[Fleet Air Arm]]'s [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]. It was expected that Red Top would offer a dramatic leap in performance for Sea Vixen, as its enlarged motor significantly improved its performance when launched subsonically, the relative improvement is less when launched from Lightning. There was also some discussion of mounting four Red Top on [[Blackburn Buccaneer]], likely the B.112 version that had been developed for long-duration [[combat air patrol]].{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nIndependently, in 1959 Jon Fozard of [[Hawker Aircraft]] also considered using Red Top on the [[Hawker Siddeley P.1127]], assuming it to have a larger engine, a pair of Red Top, and the [[AIRPASS]] radar from the Lightning.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n===Testing and service===\n[[File:Red Top.jpg|right|thumb|Red Top on display at the [[Royal Air Force Museum Cosford|RAF Museum Cosford]].]]\n[[File:Hawker Siddeley Red Top missile.jpg|thumb|Hawker Siddeley Red Top missile mounted on an [[English Electric Lightning]] at the [[RAF Museum]] at [[Hendon]], [[London]]. ]]\n\nRed Top testing began using the new fuselage layout with the original Firestreak faceted nosecone and leftover Magpie III motors from the Blue Jay Mk. II program. Ten such lash-ups had been fired by June 1959. Guidance tests with the new motor and seeker were carried out from an [[English Electric Canberra]] beginning in early 1960 and firing from the Lightning in September 1961.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\nThe Red Top entered service in [[1964 in aviation|1964]], arming the [[English Electric Lightning]] and [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]. It remained in limited service until the final retirement of the Lightning in [[1988 in aviation|1988]].<ref>Gibson 2007, p. 41, 42</ref> Unusually, the missile that the Red Top was intended to replace \u2013 Firestreak \u2013 also remained in limited service on the Lightning until 1988. This was because Red Top's larger wing area required the Lightning to have a larger fin to maintain stability, leaving Firestreak on the other models that were already in service.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n===Further upgrades===\nWhile development of Red Top was being carried out, another adaptation of the original Firestreak was being considered to produce a [[semi-active radar homing]] version that would allow a single airframe to be converted from IR to radar by changing the nose section. Initially known as Blue Jay Mk. V, this became \"Blue Dolphin\", but this was cancelled in 1958{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nA longer-ranged Red Top Mk. 2 was also proposed, replacing the Linnet rocket with a [[liquid fuel rocket]] running on MADI/RFNA, likely the de Havilland Spartan.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n== Former operators ==\n[[File:Red Top operators.png|thumb|Map with Red Top operators in blue]]\n; {{KUW}}\n* [[Kuwait Air Force]]\n; {{SAU}}\n* [[Royal Saudi Air Force]]\n; {{UK}}\n* [[Royal Air Force]]\n* [[Royal Navy]], [[Fleet Air Arm]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Rainbow Codes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book\n  | last1 = Gibson| first1 = Chris\n  | first2 = Tony| last2 = Buttler\n  | title = British Secret Projects: Hypersonics, Ramjets and Missiles\n  | publisher = Midland Publishing\n  | year= 2007\n  | pages = 47\u201353\n  | isbn = 978-1-85780-258-0 \n  |ref=harv\n}}\n\n{{UKmissiles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Top (Missile)}}\n[[Category:Cold War air-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Air-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n| image= Red Top missile.png\n| image_size = 250\n|caption= Red Top missile\n|name=Red Top\n|type=[[Air-to-air missile]]\n|origin=United Kingdom\n|era=Cold War\n|platform=aircraft\n|target=aircraft\n|manufacturer=Hawker Siddeley Dynamics\n|design_date=\n|production_date=\n|service=1964 - 1988\n|used_by= United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait\n|wars=\n|spec_type= homing missile\n|diameter= 0.23 m\n|wingspan=0.91 m\n|length=3.32 m\n|weight= 154 kg\n|speed=Mach 3.2\n|vehicle_range=7.5 miles (12 km)\n|ceiling=\n|filling=31 kg (68.3 lb) [[annular blast fragmentation]]\n|engine=''Linnet'' solid fuel motor\n|steering=control surfaces\n|guidance=[[infrared homing]], limited [[all-aspect]]\n|variants=?\n|number=\n|detonation=''Green Garland'' infrared proximity; secondary contact [[fuze]]\n}}\n\nThe '''[[Hawker Siddeley]]''' (later [[British Aerospace]]) '''Red Top''' was the third indigenous British [[air-to-air missile]] to enter service, following the [[de Havilland Firestreak]] and limited-service [[Fireflash]]. Originally a modified version of the Firestreak, Red Top emerged as a much more capable weapon, with roughly double the range, a more sensitive seeker giving limited all-aspect capability, and an even larger warhead than the already-large one in Firestreak. Although much more powerful than Firestreak, both missiles remained in service until 1988 when the last of the [[English Electric Lightning]]s retired.\n\n==Development==\n===Improved Blue Jay===\nEven before the original [[de Havilland Firestreak|Firestreak]] entered service, improvements were being studied to increase its performance. Still known by its [[rainbow code]] \"Blue Jay\", Blue Jay Mk. II introduced an improved seeker and more powerful motor, while Mk. III derated the motor to limit acceleration when launched at high speed in order to avoid overheating due to aerodynamic heating. Neither project was proceeded with.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=35}}\n\n===Blue Vesta===\nLooking for a further improved weapon for the [[Operational Requirement F.155]] interceptors, in 1955 the Air Ministry issued OR.1131 for an all-aspect design capability against enemy aircraft traveling at Mach 2. De Havilland responded with Blue Jay Mk. IV, which was later given its own rainbow code, '''Blue Vesta'''.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}\n\nBlue Vesta adopted the PbTe seeker of Mk. II, further improved by cooling it to improve its sensitivity in what became known as the \"Violet Banner\" seeker. The motor was further upgraded to the new Magpie III. To handle the aerodynamic heating issues, the fins were made of steel rather than aluminum, and featured cut-away sections to keep the rear portions of the surfaces out of the Mach cones, a feature they referred to as \"mach tips\".{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}{{efn|More widely known today as a cropped delta.}}\n\nWork on Blue Vesta was curtailed after 1956 as the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]] (RAE) concluded that the rapid closing speeds of two Mach 2+ aircraft would be so quick that the missile would have no chance to be launched while it was still within the range of its seeker. They suggested moving to the much larger [[radar]]-guided [[Red Hebe]], although some low-level work on Blue Vesta's underlying technologies continued.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=36}}\n\n===Red Top===\nF.155 was canceled in the aftermath of the release of the [[1957 Defence White Paper]]. It was decided to proceed with the development of the Lightning largely because it was already close to being complete. Blue Vesta was reactivated in July 1957 to arm this aircraft. For security reasons, yet another rainbow code was assigned in November 1957 and it became Red Top.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nIn contrast to Blue Vesta, Red Top was a simpler design, more of a rationalised, upgraded version of the earlier Firestreak. Lower launch speeds allowed the steel wings and fins to be replaced, and these were enlarged to provide more maneuvering power. The fuselage was straightened, removing the boat-tail design of the Firestreak and allowing the new \"Linnet\" rocket motor to more completely fill the increased volume. Other oddities of the Firestreak, like the fin actuators being in the nose and requiring pushrods running the length of the fuselage were removed, giving it a much more logical layout and further increasing internal volume.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nThe all-aspect [[lead telluride]] (PbTe) seeker developed for Blue Vesta was replaced by a much less expensive [[indium antimonide]] (InSb) system known as \"Violet Banner\". This seeker lacked the sensitivity of the PbTe model and did not offer true all-aspect capability, but it offset this loss to some degree through a greatly increased the [[field of view]] to 60&nbsp;degrees. Firestreak's tube-powered electronics were replaced by [[transistor]]ized versions, which greatly improved reliability and eliminated the need for continual cooling. The new \"Green Garland\" IR [[proximity fuse]] required only one row of \"windows\", further simplifying the layout.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nThese changes allowed the warhead to be moved to the forward fuselage from its former rear-mounted location. This allowed it to be enlarged to 31&nbsp;kg (68.3&nbsp;lb) from Firestreak's already prodigious 22.7&nbsp;kg (50&nbsp;lb) and added an [[expanding-rod warhead]] in place of the earlier blast fragmentation type.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=40}}\n\nThe Red Top was faster<ref name=Boyne267/> and had greater range and maneuvrability than the Firestreak, and its [[infrared seeker]] enabled a wider range of engagement angles. Although not offering the true all-aspect capability planned for Blue Vesta, Violet Banner did allow head-on attacks against supersonic aircraft.<ref>[http://www.vectorsite.net/aveeltg.html The English Electric (BAC) Lightning<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  \"Unlike modern [1990s] missiles, Red Top and Firestreak could only be fired outside cloud, and in winter, skies were rarely clear over the UK.\"<ref name=Black141>Black, Ian, ''The Last of the Lightnings'', pub PSL, 1996, {{ISBN|1-85260-541-3}}, p141.</ref>\n\n===Almost cancelled===\nAlthough Red Top was a relatively straightforward upgrade to Firestreak, [[Duncan Sandys]] almost cancelled it as well. He felt that Firestreak would be acceptable during the short period before the [[Bristol Bloodhound|Bloodhound Mk. II]] [[Surface-to-air missile|SAM]] entered service in the early 1960s and eliminated the need for [[interceptor aircraft]] altogether. The [[Air Staff]] argued this point, ultimately convincing him that Red Top's head-on attack profile against new Soviet supersonic bombers known to be in development was an urgent requirement.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nAt a February 1958 meeting of the Controller of Guided Weapons and Electronics, the group earmarked Red Top for both Lightning and the [[Fleet Air Arm]]'s [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]. It was expected that Red Top would offer a dramatic leap in performance for Sea Vixen, as its enlarged motor significantly improved its performance when launched subsonically, the relative improvement is less when launched from Lightning. There was also some discussion of mounting four Red Top on [[Blackburn Buccaneer]], likely the B.112 version that had been developed for long-duration [[combat air patrol]].{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nIndependently, in 1959 Jon Fozard of [[Hawker Aircraft]] also considered using Red Top on the [[Hawker Siddeley P.1127]], assuming it to have a larger engine, a pair of Red Top, and the [[AIRPASS]] radar from the Lightning.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n===Into service===\n[[File:Red Top.jpg|right|thumb|Red Top on display at the [[Royal Air Force Museum Cosford|RAF Museum Cosford]].]]\n[[File:Hawker Siddeley Red Top missile.jpg|thumb|Hawker Siddeley Red Top missile mounted on an [[English Electric Lightning]] at the [[RAF Museum]] at [[Hendon]], [[London]]. ]]\n\nRed Top testing began using the new fuselage layout with the original Firestreak faceted nosecone and leftover Magpie III motors from the Blue Jay Mk. II program. Ten such lash-ups had been fired by June 1959. Guidance tests with the new motor and seeker were carried out from an [[English Electric Canberra]] beginning in early 1960 and firing from the Lightning in September 1961.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\nThe Red Top entered service in [[1964 in aviation|1964]], arming the [[English Electric Lightning]] and [[de Havilland Sea Vixen]]. It remained in limited service until the final retirement of the Lightning in [[1988 in aviation|1988]].<ref>Gibson 2007, p. 41, 42</ref> Unusually, the missile that the Red Top was intended to replace \u2013 Firestreak \u2013 also remained in limited service on the Lightning until 1988. This was because Red Top's larger wing area required the Lightning to have a larger fin to maintain stability, leaving Firestreak on the other models that were already in service.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n===Further upgrades===\nWhile development of Red Top was being carried out, another adaptation of the original Firestreak was being considered to produce a [[semi-active radar homing]] version that would allow a single airframe to be converted from IR to radar by changing the nose section. Initially known as Blue Jay Mk. V, this became \"Blue Dolphin\", but this was cancelled in 1958{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=41}}\n\nA longer-ranged Red Top Mk. 2 was also proposed, replacing the Linnet rocket with a [[liquid fuel rocket]] running on MADI/RFNA, likely the de Havilland Spartan.{{sfn|Gibson|Buttler|2007|p=42}}\n\n== Former operators ==\n[[File:Red Top operators.png|thumb|Map with Red Top operators in blue]]\n; {{KUW}}\n* [[Kuwait Air Force]]\n; {{SAU}}\n* [[Royal Saudi Air Force]]\n; {{UK}}\n* [[Royal Air Force]]\n* [[Royal Navy]], [[Fleet Air Arm]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Rainbow Codes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{Cite book\n  | last1 = Gibson| first1 = Chris\n  | first2 = Tony| last2 = Buttler\n  | title = British Secret Projects: Hypersonics, Ramjets and Missiles\n  | publisher = Midland Publishing\n  | year= 2007\n  | pages = 47\u201353\n  | isbn = 978-1-85780-258-0 \n  |ref=harv\n}}\n\n{{UKmissiles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Red Top (Missile)}}\n[[Category:Cold War air-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Air-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Maury Markowitz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInto service", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Top_(missile)"}
{"title_page": "Zhornovets", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhornovets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|14|N|37|16|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhornovets''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Semizerye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 2 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 8&nbsp;km. Kaduy is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhornovets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|14|N|37|16|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhornovets''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Semizerye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 2 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 8&nbsp;km. Kaduy is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhornovets"}
{"title_page": "Zhidelevo", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhidelevo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|38|N|37|08|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhidelevo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 8 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 65&nbsp;km, to Nikolskoye is 33&nbsp;km. Danilkovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Zhidelevo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0416\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Kaduysky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|38|N|37|08|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Zhidelevo''' ({{lang-ru|\u0416\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 8 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 65&nbsp;km, to Nikolskoye is 33&nbsp;km. Danilkovo is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhidelevo"}
{"title_page": "Borough of Basildon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See {{Infobox settlement}} for the full list of available fields -->\n<!-- Elements common to United Kingdom -->\n| official_name           = Borough of Basildon\n| settlement_type         = [[Non-metropolitan district]], [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|Borough]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_shield            =\n| shield_size             = \n| shield_alt              = \n| shield_link             = \n| image_map               = Basildon UK locator map.svg\n| mapsize                 = 150px\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Basildon shown within Essex\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[United Kingdom]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Countries of the United Kingdom|Constituent country]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Regions of England|Region]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Non-metropolitan county]]\n| subdivision_type4       = Status\n| subdivision_type5       = Admin HQ\n| subdivision_name1       = [[England]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[East of England]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Essex]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Non-metropolitan district]], [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name5       = [[Basildon]]\n| established_title1      = Incorporated\n| established_date1       = 1 April 1974\n| government_type         = Non-metropolitan district council\n| governing_body          = [[Basildon Borough Council]]\n| leader_party            = {{English district control|GSS=E07000066}}\n| leader_title            = Leadership\n| leader_name             = Committee\n| leader_title1           = [[List of MPs elected in the 2015 United Kingdom general election|MPs]]\n| leader_name1            = [[John Baron (politician)|John Baron]]<br />[[Stephen Metcalfe (politician)|Stephen Metcalfe]]<br />[[Mark Francois]]\n| area_total_km2          = 110.02\n| area_rank               = {{English district area rank|GSS=E07000066}} [[List of English districts by area|(of {{English district total}})]]\n| population_total        = {{English district population|GSS=E07000066}}\n| population_as_of        = {{English statistics year}}\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_rank         = {{English district rank|GSS=E07000066}} [[List of English districts by population|(of {{English district total}})]]\n| population_blank1_title = Ethnicity\n| population_blank1       = 94.5% White<br />2.0% S. Asian<br />1.5% Black<br />1.2% Mixed\n| website                 = {{URL|www.basildon.gov.uk/}}\n| timezone                = [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n| utc_offset              = 0\n| timezone_DST            = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +1\n\n<!-- Elements common to administrative division of this type (English two-tier district) -->\n| blank1_name             = [[ONS coding system|ONS code]]\n| blank2_name             = [[Ordnance Survey National Grid|OS grid reference]]\n\n<!-- Elements unique to this article -->\n| blank1_info             = E07000066\n| blank2_info             = {{gbmappingsmall|TQ735895}} \n}}\nThe '''Borough of Basildon''' is a [[Non-metropolitan district|local government district]] in south [[Essex]] in the [[East of England]], centred on the town of [[Basildon]]. The district was formed under the [[Local Government Act 1972]] on 1 April 1974 from the former area of [[Basildon Urban District]] and the part of [[Thurrock Urban District]] that was within the Basildon New Town. The population of the district as of 2010 is about 172,000. The council made an application for [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|borough status]] in February 2010 and this was given approval that year, with Cllr Mo Larkin becoming the first mayor in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.basildon.gov.uk/website2/newsroom.nsf/APR/CCC4336CF850161A8025779F002EFDBE?OpenDocument |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718062153/http://www2.basildon.gov.uk/website2/newsroom.nsf/APR/CCC4336CF850161A8025779F002EFDBE?OpenDocument |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 July 2011 |title=Basildon to get its first Mayor |publisher=Basildon District Council |date=15 September 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-11315875 | title=Basildon district becomes borough | publisher=BBC News | date=15 September 2010 | accessdate=26 March 2011 }}</ref> The local authority is [[Basildon Borough Council]].\n\n==Governance==\n{{see also|Basildon local elections}}\nElections to [[Basildon Borough Council]] are held in three out of every four years, with one third of the 42 seats on the council being elected at each election. Both the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] and [[UK Labour Party|Labour]] parties have controlled the council at different times, as well as periods when no party has had a majority. The Conservative party controlled the council through a cabinet system of governance after winning a majority at the [[2003 Basildon Council election|2003 election]]. In May 2017 the council switched to a committee system with no party in overall control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/15198740.political-row-breaks-out-over-change-to-council-system/|title=Political row breaks out over change to council system|last=Chapman|first=Chloe|date=3 April 2017|website=Echo|language=en|access-date=21 March 2019}}</ref> The council is currently composed of the following councillors:<ref name=\"hold\">{{cite news|title=Your Councillors|url=http://www.basildonmeetings.info/mgMemberIndex.aspx?FN=PARTY&VW=LIST&PIC=0|publisher=Basildon Borough Council|accessdate=31 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"1\" align=\"center\" valign=\"top\" | '''Party'''\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Councillors'''<br />\n|-\n{{party colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| 20\n|-\n{{party colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| 15\n|-\n{{Party colour|Independent}}\n| Independents\n| 6\n|-\n{{party colour|UKIP}}\n| [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]]\n| 1\n|-\n|}\n\n===Parish and town councils===\nThere are eight town, parish and village councils at present. They cover one quarter of the district and are:<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Local Councils\n| publisher = basildon.gov.uk\n| url = http://www.basildon.gov.uk/article/520/Local-Councils\n| accessdate = 2017-07-23\n}}</ref>\n\n*Billericay Town Council\n*Bowers Gifford and North Benfleet Parish Council\n*Great Burstead & South Green Parish Council\n*Little Burstead Parish Council\n*Ramsden Bellhouse Parish Council\n*Ramsden Crays Parish Council\n*Noak Bridge Parish Council\n*Shotgate Parish Council\n\n==Boundaries==\nTo the north it borders the Borough of [[Chelmsford (borough)|Chelmsford]], to the east it borders the District of [[Rochford (district)|Rochford]] district, to the south east the Borough of [[Castle Point]] and to the west it borders the Borough of [[Brentwood (borough)|Brentwood]]. To the south the district has a boundary with the [[unitary authority]] of [[Thurrock]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Basildon.png|right|thumb|300px|Constituencies within the Basildon district. <br />Blue: Billericay and Basildon <br />Red: Basildon South and Thurrock East <br />Green: Rayleigh and Wickford]]\nThe [[district]] has three main population centres. The towns of [[Billericay]] and [[Wickford]] are two of the areas which both have surrounding villages. Occasional proposals have been made to move Billericay and Wickford to other districts, leaving Basildon more focused on the new town.<ref name=cooksey>LGCE.  ''Final Recommendations on the Future Local Government of: Basildon & Thurrock, Blackburn & Blackpool, Broxtowe, Gedling & Rushcliffe, Dartford & Gravesham, Gillingham & Rochester Upon Medway, Exeter, Gloucester, Halton & Warrington, Huntingdonshire & Peterborough, Northampton, Norwich, Spelthorne and the Wrekin.''  December 1995.</ref>\n\nThe other, largest, population centre is commonly referred to as [[Basildon]] and comprises three original settlements: [[Laindon]], Basildon and [[Pitsea]] (from west to east) which have merged with other minor settlements to form the New Town, which is a continuous urban area.\n\nThe remaining land, approximately half of the district is designated as [[green belt]], has several [[site of special scientific interest|sites of special scientific interest]]. Two are around Billericay and the remainder are to the south of Basildon New Town. There are also wildlife areas of varying sizes around most of the district, except in the East.\n\nThe source of the [[River Crouch]] is in the district. The river runs across the district, through [[Wickford]] before it leaves the district.\n\nThe district is linked well by road and rail with significant surrounding destinations, including [[London]].\n\nIn the west of the Basildon district, the [[Dunton Plotlands]] is an area of small plots of land used as weekend cottages or smallholdings inhabited during the mid twentieth century.\n\n=== List of settlements ===\nIt contains the towns of:\n\n* [[Basildon]] (the administrative headquarters)\n** [[Laindon]]\n** [[Langdon Hills]]\n** [[Pitsea]]\n** [[Vange]]\n* [[Billericay]]\n* [[Wickford]]\n\nVillages within the district are:\n* [[Bowers Gifford]]\n* [[Crays Hill]]\n* [[Dunton Wayletts]]\n* [[Great Burstead]]\n* [[Little Burstead]]\n* [[Nevendon]]\n* [[North Benfleet]]\n* [[Ramsden Bellhouse]]\n* [[Shotgate]]\n* [[Great Berry]]\n\n==Regeneration plans==\nBasildon District is a prosperous business location and has in recent years seen significant inward investment and jobs growth. Throughout Basildon District there are major developments planned estimated to total nearly \u00a32 billion. These include:\n\n*The regeneration of Basildon, Wickford, Pitsea, and Laindon Town Centres\n*A new Sporting Village and improvements to playing pitches and sports facilities throughout the District to make Basildon the Centre for Sport in South Essex. The sporting village is expected in 2010, and is being highly sought after as an Olympic training base for one of the top teams, including the Russians. Its combined benefits, of having some of the top facilities so close to London, including one of the few Olympic (50m) size pools in the UK, will make it a true asset to whatever team(s) use it.\n*The creation of a health and education research centre near Basildon and Thurrock University Hospital and FE College\n*Investment in the Basildon Enterprise Corridor, the largest business area in the Thames Gateway outside London, home to 45,000 jobs and over 5,000 businesses, including Ford, Selex, Visteon, Case New Holland, [[First Data]] Europe, International Financial Services Limited, RBS, and Starbucks\n*The creation of one of the largest wetland nature reserves in Europe in the Thames Marshes by the RSPB, Land Restoration Trust, Basildon District Council and Veolia\n*A strategic review of the District's housing, with investment in housing estates such as Craylands, Five Links and Felmores to create first class places to live\n\nCoordinating and promoting this programme of investment is the Basildon Renaissance Partnership which was set up in 2003 by Basildon District Council. Its partners also include the East Of England Development Agency, English Partnerships, Essex County Council, and the Thames Gateway South Essex Partnership with support from the Department for Communities and Local Government.\n\nThe BBC noted the council had decided to sell for \u00a31 a plot of land it bought next to the golf course for \u00a31m in order to build a 4 star hotel.  The Conservative leader described the sale as an exciting step forward.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-47172198|title=Basildon Council to sell land it bought for \u00a31m for \u00a31|work=BBC news|date=8 February 2019|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe district is connected to [[London]] and [[Southend-on-sea|Southend]] via two train operators: [[c2c]] and [[Abellio Greater Anglia]]. The route operated by c2c is the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]]. Three principal stations of the railway line are in the district: [[Basildon railway station]], [[Laindon railway station]] and [[Pitsea railway station]]\n\nThe former [[First Great Eastern|Great Eastern]] service (now [[Abellio Greater Anglia]]) operates on the [[Shenfield to Southend Line]]. Trains stop at [[Billericay railway station|Billericay]] and [[Wickford railway station]]. At Wickford, the [[Crouch Valley Line]] diverges from the Shenfield to Southend line.\n\nThree [[Primary status|primary route]]s are within the district. The [[A127 road|A127]] goes through its centre, the [[A13 road (Great Britain)|A13]] goes through the south-east at Pitsea. Both these primary routes connect the district with [[Greater London]] and Southend-on-Sea. At Bowers Gifford at a terminus of the A13's [[primary status]] there is a junction with the beginning of primary status for the [[A130 road|A130]] with runs along a small section of the western boundary of the district. The A130 connects the district with [[Chelmsford]]. The [[A129 road|A129]] is the major road link between Billericay and Wickford, which are linked via [[Great Britain road numbering scheme|A-Roads]] to the urban area of Basildon, Pitsea and Laindon by the [[A176 road|A176]] and the [[A132 road (England)|A132]], respectively.\n\n==Freedom of the Borough==\nThe following people and military units have received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of Basildon.\n \n{{Expand list|date=September 2019}}\n\n===Individuals===\n* [[Max Whitlock]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}}: February 2016.\n* [[Stuart Bingham]]: February 2016.\n* [[Trudi Westmore-Cox]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}}: September 2019.\n* [[Donald Sheppard]]: September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yellowad.co.uk/basildon-war-hero-and-hospice-founder-awarded-freedom-of-the-borough/|title=Basildon war hero and hospice founder awarded Freedom of the Borough|last=Thomson|first=Charles|date=2019-11-25|website=Yellow Advertiser|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===Military Units===\n* The [[Royal Anglian Regiment]]: April 2011.\n\n<ref>https://www.basildon.gov.uk/article/3938/Freedom-of-the-Borough?contactid=3046</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://basildon.gov.uk/ Basildon District Home Page]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160304003558/http://www.basildonrenaissance.co.uk/ Basildon Renaissance Partnership]\n* [http://www.basildonheritage.org.uk/ Basildon Heritage]\n* [http://basildonhistory.wix.com/essex Basildon Borough History]\n\n{{Essex}}\n{{East_of_England}}\n{{coord|51.5705|0.4545|type:adm3rd_dim:15000_region:GB-ESS|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basildon, Borough of}}\n[[Category:Borough of Basildon| ]]\n[[Category:Non-metropolitan districts of Essex]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See {{Infobox settlement}} for the full list of available fields -->\n<!-- Elements common to United Kingdom -->\n| official_name           = Borough of Basildon\n| settlement_type         = [[Non-metropolitan district]], [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|Borough]]\n| image_skyline           = \n| imagesize               = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_shield            =\n| shield_size             = \n| shield_alt              = \n| shield_link             = \n| image_map               = Basildon UK locator map.svg\n| mapsize          